<HEADLINE>
CELTICS FALTER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A look of disbelief mixed with frustration crossed the
face of every Boston player as the final minutes elapsed in their
contest against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   During stoppages in play, they stared blankly at each other,
hands on hips. The Celtics were left to face a numbing reality.
Once again, they put themselves in position for another
disappointing loss. Once again, the played nearly three quarters of
solid basketball only to watch their lead disappear in agonizing
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, Boston was faced with the
possibility of another fourth-quarter collapse and could not
respond. The result was a devastating 94-84 loss that extended the
Celtics' losing streak to three and pushed them back to .500. The
threat of an early season tailspin looms.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics squandered a respectable 14-point, third-quarter
lead, watching their opponent draw even 2:40 into the fourth
quarter. They were outrebounded 30-9 in the second half, and 16-6
in the final frame as they slipped farther and farther behind the
Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   The game at sparkling new Phillips Arena before 13,736 fans was
deja vu for the Celtics with the memory of Friday's 21-point
collapse against Milwaukee still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time they didn't have as far to fall. Now, Boston has
a lot longer to think about its final-quarter failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good basketball team and right now we're not putting
it together for four quarters,'' said Antoine Walker, who finished
with 16 points, but only one basket in the fourth. ``We've got to
look ourselves in the mirror right now and find out what the
problem is. We have to figure out what we're doing wrong and try to
correct it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first player to the last player, we've got to look
ourselves in the mirror. The good thing is we've got a week off to
figure out what the mistakes are. You're working so hard for three
quarters, trying to get the lead and then you blow it. It hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston entered a scoring drought after Dana Barros hit a
3-pointer with 1:57 left in the third quarter. The trey gave the
Celtics their second 14-point lead (73-59). But then, the lead
rapidly disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Free throws by Dikembe Mutombo, Lorenzen White, and a 3-pointer
by Isaiah Rider closed the gap to 5 points. Time expired in the
third with Kenny Anderson launching an unsuccessful, off-balance
jump shot. The Hawks celebrated their comeback on the way back to
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' scorers didn't find the basket until Pervis Ellison
hit two free throws in the fourth with 10:07 left to stop an 11-0
Hawk run and push the Celtics' lead back to 3 points. But it was
not enough to get Boston back on track.
</P>
<P>
   A Rider jumper gave the Hawks a 2-point lead with 8:30 left to
play, breaking a 75-75 tie and pushing the home team ahead for
good.
</P>
<P>
   A jumper and free throw by Rider with 1:20 left gave Atlanta a
8-point lead. Before the final buzzer, the Hawks pushed the lead to
10 points with free throws. Rider, the Hawks' leading scorer, saved
his best for last. He poured in 13 of his game-high 30 points in
the final quarter. Mutombo, who leads the league in rebounding,
posted 17 boards.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led the Celtics with 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that we weren't playing so well, and they
weren't playing so well,'' said Rider. ``But we were playing well
enough to get the game. When we got to within 3, at that point in
time, I knew it was a game. I just decided to turn up the pace a
little bit and pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to be more aggressive and kept the defense on their
toes a little bit instead of playing passive. The good thing was we
responded on defense as well as offense, and that's why we got over
the hump. It was a great team performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Cetlics had the better team play. Poor ball
movement was a problem in the second-half demise of the Celtics
against the Bucks Friday night, so the visitors looked to reverse
the trend against the Hawks. The visitors' first basket came after
a good team effort. After grabbing and offensive rebound following
a Walker miss, Ellison looked toward the basket, but thought better
of taking a shot and dished the ball to Anderson waiting at the
foul line. The guard converted on the open shot and Ellison drew
praise from Pitino for a ``nice play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino continued to appluad the teamwork as they opened up an
8-point gap (20-12) with 4:36 left to play in the first quarter.
Boston started a mini-run when Vitaly Potapenko entered the game,
replacing Ellison who sustained a gash above his right eye that
required three stiches.
</P>
<P>
   On his first offensive move of the game, Potapenko drove to the
basket then kicked the ball out to Andrian Griffin (14 points) for
a wide-open 3-pointer. Boston's next time down the court, Potapenko
passed to Walker who made an easy layup. The forward made a
3-pointer to cap the run.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hawks battled back behind the shot-making of Alan
Henderson and Rider, tying the score with 2:44 left in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics responded with increased defensive pressure,
allowing the Hawks to score just one more basket before the end of
the first frame. Boston, behind the fresh legs of Dana Barros and
Tony Battie, opened a 28-22 lead by the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks made a short-lived comeback at the start of the
second, closing to within 2 points (28-26).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our own fault,'' said Pitino of the collapse. ``We ran
out of gas and got killed on the backboards. They deserved to win.
The mentally tough team wins it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
