<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS FIND A CURE CALLED THE BULLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks were sick. They were hurting. A home game
against the Chicago Bulls was just what the coach ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks got a feel-good, 95-83 victory against the Bulls
yesterday before a Reunion Arena crowd of 14,436.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a must-win for us,'' Mavericks center Shawn Bradley
said. ``It was Chicago, who's not doing very well this year, but if
you let them stay in the game they might be able to get you late.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, forward Cedric Ceballos was filling up the
garbage can with Kleenex in his battle with the flu, and guard
Steve Nash was in the training room for treatment on his sprained
right ankle. Guard Robert Pack (right groin) did not dress, and
forward Gary Trent (left hamstring) still is on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   But after suiting up the NBA-minimum eight players the past two
games, the Mavericks took what they could get. Ceballos played 24
minutes and produced 10 points, and Nash was good for 35 minutes,
seven points and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just so happy to have some players back,'' Mavericks
coach Don Nelson said. ``They're not sharp. We proved that. But
it's good to have them back on the floor, and hopefully, it'll be
downhill a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks entered with a five-game losing streak. The Bulls
entered with a six-game losing streak. Somebody had to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, six-time NBA champions this decade, are not a shell
of themselves. They are mere memories of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls were so bad they threatened a team record for fewest
points in a quarter. Chicago scored four points in the final 57.4
seconds of the third quarter to give it 10 points, four better than
the franchise low set against Miami on Nov. 6, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know that,'' Bulls guard Hersey Hawkins said.
``But we've come out probably four or five times this year and not
played particularly well in the third quarter. It's nothing new. I
don't think they were doing anything particularly special. I think
we just missed a lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls (1-12) dictated the tempo in the first half. They
didn't run, which allowed them to hide their deficiencies and stay
within 47-46 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was going to kind of be like that, so we had to
kind of just fight through it,'' Mavericks guard Erick Strickland
said. ``That was all we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (5-9) continued their second-quarter struggles.
They hit their average of 23 points in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't start out that way. The Mavericks hit eight of their
first 10 field-goal attempts to go up 41-32 with 5:40 remaining in
the half. But the Bulls went on a 12-0 run to take their first lead
of the game. During that 4:01 stretch, the Mavericks were 0-for-8
from the field and had two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter, however, belonged to the Mavericks. The Bulls
made only three of their first 17 shots after halftime and had five
turnovers in falling behind, 69-53.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' 7-foot duo of Dirk Nowitzki and Bradley
dominated. Nowitzki outscored the Bulls, 11-10, in the third
quarter, and Bradley had two of his five blocks and six of his 17
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, however, left complaining about the officiating. In
the second half, the Mavericks were called for only two fouls, and
the Bulls never went to the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen this ever in my life,'' Bulls forward Dickey
Simpkins said. ``I guess there's always a first for something in
the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is a worst in the NBA, and right now, it's the Bulls.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
