<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-INSIDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES, LONGHORNS SERVED STATE PROUDLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been many times when I've been proud to call myself a
Texan, but perhaps never more so than over the past week as the
tragic events at the Texas A&AMP;M bonfire site played themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional period culminated Friday with A&AMP;M's gallant
comeback against Texas. By then I thought it didn't matter any more
who won the game. I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' victory was right for all the right reasons. Or at
least 12 good ones that I can think of off the top of my head.
</P>
<P>
   Really, nothing would have changed emotionally if the Longhorns
had won, except that the Aggies ``needed'' to win this time; they
needed it to make a statement of their feelings, their emotions,
their sadness, their love for lost comrades.
</P>
<P>
   Even Texas and its fans must have felt it. What a moment when
the Longhorns band played ``Amazing Grace'', raised the Aggies'
flag high and lowered their own. What a classy statement of
heartfelt friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' archrivals were saying, in so many words, that they
recognized that something much more important than a football game
was at stake. They were saying in a gesture far greater than words
that they understood, they cared, and as fellow Texans and fellow
human beings, they were standing beside the Aggies in their time of
sorrow and grief.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures we have seen from College Station have spoken to
our hearts: Aggie football players, shouldering timbers to help in
the rescue efforts; the bouquets of flowers, the remembrances left
by devastated students at the bonfire site; the sea of candles at
Thursday night's vigil; the tears streaming down the face of A&AMP;M
quarterback Randy McCown in the wake of the Aggies' victory.
</P>
<P>
   We sometimes become so engrossed in our petty little games and
rivalries that we forget the things that really matter. That point
was driven home in a dramatic and horrible way, but to their
everlasting credit, those who were at the center of the tragedy,
whatever their affiliation or school colors, responded with
dignity, grace and compassion.
AFC suspect Sorry, AFC, but the Cowboys' 20-0 butt-kicking of Jimmy
Johnson's Dolphins on Thursday throws your entire conference into
``suspect'' status. Yeah, yeah, so the AFC has all these eight-win
teams. So what?
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys can push the Dolphins, supposedly a solid AFC
Super Bowl contender, around as they did using a plain-vanilla
offensive game plan and with two of their top three cornerbacks
sidelined, you have to wonder what's real and what's cardboard over
there.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the NFC isn't dead after all.
</P>
<P>
   And the manipulative, lip-smacking Johnson may be the only man
in America this side of Don King who can actually make Jerry Jones
look like a sympathetic figure.
A young pitching star? The Rangers have been tentatively penciling
in left-hander Matt Perisho as their fifth starter going into
spring training, but Doug Davis' splendid season in the Arizona
Fall League may give them at least one other option.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, also a left-hander, was the league's pitcher of the year
while tying for first in the league with five victories and
finishing fifth with a 2.25 earned-run average over a
league-leading 36 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug Davis knows how to pitch,'' says Chris Cron, who managed
Rangers prospect-laden Mesa. ``He's got a bulldog mentality. He
competes like crazy, and he's got good stuff to go along with
that.''
Nervous days Adrian Beltre's grievance against the Dodgers for
signing him to a contract when he was only 15, a clear violation of
major-league rules, has a lot of scouts nervously checking their
hole cards.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Caribbean players before their 16th birthdays is a more
common practice than anyone would care to admit.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Beltre happily took the money he was offered
and now has bitten the hand that brought him the dough in order to
play the system and become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Makes you wonder how many other Latin players are scrambling for
their real birth certificates now.
A Rose by any other name ... You figure Pete Rose really wants his
case against baseball settled?
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way: Rose's national TV confrontation with
interviewer Jim Gray during the World Series has brought him
sympathy and, even more important, more lucrative paydays as he has
become more in demand than ever.
</P>
<P>
   But once his situation regarding the Hall of Fame is resolved,
he knows he'll need to secure another managing job because out of
sight is out of mind, and he'll be hard-pressed to continue
commanding the $20,000-$50,000 fee he's charging now to appear at
baseball card shows.
</P>
<P>
   Best estimates have Rose pulling in in excess of $1 million a
year in appearance fees and assorted other gigs.
Welcome to Windy Losersville So you're worried about the Stars'
fall from grace, the Cowboys' mediocre season, the forgettable Mavs
and the fact that the Rangers can't get past the first round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Cheer up, it could be worse. Chicagoans woke up this morning
with their NBA Bulls and their NHL Blackhawks both in last place in
their respective leagues, and the Bears lost to the Lions on
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even gotten to the White Sox or Cubs yet.
A turkey a day A video clip on a sportscast in the greater LA area
recently showed George W. Bush _ yep, our guv and would-be
president _ ``turkey bowling.'' Yes, he was actually rolling frozen
turkeys, but I wouldn't say he was throwing strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was from a TV show filmed at an amusement park in
Arlington, Texas, a few years ago, when Bush owned the Texas
Rangers,'' turkey bowling inventor Derrick Johnson told Randy
Youngman of the ``Orange County Register''.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, host Norm Hitzges can be heard predicting that the
footage would someday sabotage Bush's presidential aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, Johnson says, are clamoring for copies of the
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The Allison Brigade There are more than a few folks in Lubbock
who are wondering why Texas Tech doesn't have former Red Raiders
quarterback Rodney Allison on its list of coaching candidates to
replace Spike Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Allison is on the same Clemson staff as Rich
Rodriguez, the leading candidate for the job. Allison is coaching
defense, but he's an offensive coach _ he was Brett Favre's
quarterback coach at Southern Mississippi _ and his resume includes
stops at Duke, Southern Miss., Auburn and Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say Tech officials have been contacted by Favre and
Jets coach Bill Parcells recommending that Allison be interviewed,
and athletic director Gerald Myers has indicated that he'll be
contacting some new candidates this week. But the fact that
Allison's name hasn't come up previously is not a good sign.
A sorry Starry night The sad thing isn't that the Stars are taking
so long to get motivated again about defending their Stanley Cup,
it's that they're playing with so little heart and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   They won last season because they were willing to outwork every
team they played. They had pride in themselves and in each other.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming more and more obvious as this goes on that they
don't have the grit or determination to repeat what they
accomplished a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The party's over, in more ways than one.
REVO'S RIMSHOTS
As deep as it gets When the Lakers' crowd recently included Dustin
Hoffman, Jack Nicholson and Dyan Cannon, ``Los Angeles Times''
columnist Bill Plaschke was forced to conclude that the crowd had
much better depth than the team's roster.
Some eggs with your ham? Anybody else think John Madden's humor has
gotten as dry as the turkey legs he drools over every Thanksgiving
Day? Maybe he should switch to ham for a change. For obvious
reasons.
The Tiger dilemma The best chance the PGA has of selling fans on
the tight competitiveness of its players is those huge appearance
fees that keep drawing Tiger Woods across the Atlantic to Europe.
Lawrence of San Francisco Do not argue with a 49ers' fan about
Lawrence Phillips' impact on the team before he was released. It
was, after all, Phillips who missed the block that got Steve Young
kayoed, maybe for the last time.
Did I hear right? Lennox Lewis says he'd like to fight Mike Tyson
now that he has disposed of Evander Holyfield. It's a fight that
could mean big money, but littler ears.
Mom's viewpoint Stephon Marbury of the hapless 2-11 New Jersey Nets
received an interesting pep talk from his mom in front of reporters
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are a winner, and the other guys on this team don't
care,'' Mabel Marbury told him. ``It's not important to them. All
you need is some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it chicken soup for the struggling NBA soul. I'm sure
Stephon's teammates understood.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
