<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER, YOU'VE READ IT HERE FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ottawa suspends wayward forward Alexei Yashin for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado goalie Patrick Roy allows seven goals in a game.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Stanley Cup champion] Stars drop to the bottom of
the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the NHL season is only a quarter of the way through and
we've already seen plenty of wacky headlines. Here's a few more we
could be seeing in the next 60-some games:
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Owen Nolan edges Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr for
scoring title
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's got to happen sometime, and Nolan has shown himself up
to the task playing on the Sharks' first line with Vincent
Damphousse. What were the Canadiens thinking when they got rid of
him?
</P>
<P>
   New York Rangers trade for both Alexei Yashin and Keith Primeau
</P>
<P>
   Both are sitting out demanding oodles of money. Coincidentally,
the Rangers love spending oodles and oodles of money. Their
payroll, by far the biggest in the NHL, has resulted in a
well-below .500 record. And adding two spoiled whiners is just the
thing this overpaid, underachieving bunch would do.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher snubbed again; Norris Trophy
once again given to non-defensive defenseman
</P>
<P>
   Ask around the league who the best defenseman in the NHL is, and
Stars captain Hatcher gets mentioned a lot. Look at the voting for
the Norris Trophy, supposedly given to the NHL's best defenseman,
and it's tough to find his name at all. The award is all about
scoring, a bit strange considering the role of the defenseman first
and foremost is to prevent goals.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia finally gets to Cup Finals The Flyers got off to a
rough start this season but have apparently made the necessary
adjustments. A lineup featuring captain Eric Lindros, John LeClair,
Mark Recchi and Rod Brind'Amour has to break through sometime, and
this just could be that season.
</P>
<P>
   New York Islanders disappear for 10 days; nobody notices
</P>
<P>
   No team in the NHL has scored less goals or won fewer games than
the Islanders have this season. The problem is an old one, though.
If a team stinks and nobody pays to see it, does it really stink?
The few fans who do show up will tell you the answer is a
resounding ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada calls for national day of mourning
</P>
<P>
   If the season were to end today, all three of the California
teams (Los Angeles, San Jose and Anaheim) would make the playoffs
while historic, proud franchises like Montreal and Edmonton are
struggling to reach .500. And they thought the Cup vacationing in
Texas was bad?
Anaheim star Selanne even surprises himself It's pop quiz time with
guest Teemu Selanne of the Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Who has scored the most goals in the NHL since 1992?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, Hull?'' Selanne said, guessing Stars sniper
Brett Hull had to be close since he's nearing 600 goals.
</P>
<P>
   No, and imagine the surprise when Selanne learned that the
answer was himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have guessed that,'' Selanne said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Selanne has scored 324 goals since arriving on the NHL
scene in 1992. He also has the fourth-highest goals-per-game (.636)
and sixth-highest point-per-game (1.32) ratios in NHL history. He
ranks second among Anaheim's all-time leaders in goals (174) and
assists (185). He also led all NHL goal scorers last season with
47.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a player who doesn't really consider himself a pure
goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys have great shots. Some guys have soft hands. Some
guys are able to read the play and be in the right spot,'' Selanne
said. ``I don't have to shoot it very hard so I have to put the
puck in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   The puck hadn't been going in the right place _ the goal _
before Selanne arrived Friday in Texas to play the Stars. He hadn't
scored since Nov. 7 when he had a goal and assist against Edmonton.
Eight games passed, a groin pull sidelining him for three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, five goal-less, scoreless games is a lot for Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if that's a record, but if that is, I don't want
to have it,'' Selanne said.
</P>
<P>
   If it was, he quickly ended it by scoring three goals against
the Stars. He called the hat trick a ``confidence boost,'' bumping
him into the top 10 in the NHL in scoring, a place he's usually in
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   So back to the quiz.
</P>
<P>
   Who do you think are the best goal scorers in the NHL, Selanne?
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Bondra, \RJohn\S LeClair, \RPavel\S Bure, Keith Tkachuk,
Hull. There are a lot of guys,'' Selanne said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   He forgot to include himself.  &LR; subheds:Around the East A quick
glance at standings seems to indicate that maybe the Southeast
Division isn't the exactly the toughest. The division-leading
Florida Panthers have the least amount of points of any division
leader and only two of the five teams are above .500. If the Stars
were in the Southeast, they'd be in third instead of last.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine the Tampa Bay Lightning's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't won a game against a divisional opponent this
season, the streak of futility extending after Friday's 3-3 tie
with the Carolina Hurricanes. ``We've got to realize all division
games are worth four points,'' said defenseman Petr Svoboda. ``And
there's no doubt we haven't played well against our division the
last few years. I know we're a young team, but if we work real
hard, our focus should be on getting to the top of this division.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lindros almost wasn't a Philadelphia Flyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers and Carolina Hurricanes reportedly came close to
making a blockbuster trade last week that would've sent Lindros to
Carolina and unsigned restricted free agent Keith Primeau to
Philadelphia. Primeau wants $5 million a season and said he won't
return to Carolina.  &LR; subheds:Around the West Some guys have in-laws
that inspire jokes. Some guys have in-laws that inspire scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Phoenix Coyotes forward Jeremy Roenick, he's one of
the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick said he talked to his father-in-law about how tough it
has become to score a hat trick in the NHL before Thursday's game
against New Jersey. Roenick then went out and notched his seventh
hat trick, his first as a Coyote and his first since Feb. 24, 1994,
and his eighth on Friday against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not a guy who scores in bunches,'' Roenick said.
``It's ironic we were talking about it and it happened. I feel real
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has been in survival mode for most of this season,
trying to hang in until No. 1 center Peter Forsberg returned. Well,
he's baaaaaack.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg played in last night's] game against Calgary, saying he
wanted to ``start at home` after having shoulder surgery that
sidelined him for the first 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder feels good,'' Forsberg said. ``It's been a while
since I've played. Everybody else has been playing so I know I'll
be struggling at the beginning but I'm excited to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as excited as the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg led Colorado in points (97) and assists (67) last
season, adding an NHL-high 24 points in postseason action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
