<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA-CHARLOTTE BEATS PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ The Sparkletts Invitational tournament doesn't work
like other four-team men's basketball tournaments. Here, the host
plays the best team in the first round instead of in the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   So Pepperdine played North Carolina-Charlotte on Saturday and
lost 80-74.
</P>
<P>
   Many, including the coaches, thought this was to be today's
marquee matchup. But television reared its head and mandated this
should be the big first-day game.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last year. Pepperdine faced Rhode Island in the
first round, when Jim Harrick returned to the area, and Fox Sports
televised it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, UNC-Charlotte coach Bobby Lutz was told that his
49ers _ which have reached the NCAA second round each of the past
two seasons _ would open with Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make the decision,'' he said. ``When you're the visitors,
you do what you're told.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, said Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff, no
network televised this contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we knew, we should've flip-flopped,'' van Breda Kolff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only the 1,683 at Firestone Fieldhouse saw Pepperdine (2-1)
trail by 10 for much of the game, only to go on a 19-8 run in a
6-minute, 42-second span of the second half to take a 72-71 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough, however, as the 49ers (2-0) scored the game's
final seven points in the last 1:33 and moved to today's 5 p.m.
championship against St. Bonaventure, which UNC-Charlotte already
has defeated this season. Pepperdine meets Colorado State at 2:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Waves know what it's like to play an established NCAA
Tournament team. They can point to the little things that made a
difference:
</P>
<P>
   __Kenny Whitehead, a career 31-percent free-throw shooter, made
all six of his attempts to build the 49ers' lead to 65-53 with 9:14
to play.
</P>
<P>
   __In the first half, UNC-Charlotte went 7 of 15 from the 3-point
line. Jobey Thomas, who sank the eventual game-icing 3-pointer with
52.4 seconds to play, and James Zimmerman were a combined 9 of 15
from beyond the arc. Zimmerman finished with 19 points and Thomas
had 16.
</P>
<P>
   __Pepperdine started slowly, falling behind 24-14 with 8:26 left
in the first half, and trailed 41-32 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to pull it all together,'' said Pepperdine forward
Kelvin Gibbs, who led the Waves with 19 points. ``Don't matter if
we come back unless we win.''
</P>
<P>
   A positive: center Nick Sheppard scored 10 consecutive points in
the second half and finished with 14, matching his highest as a
Wave. Sheppard scored a career-high 19 while playing for Louisiana
State three seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   But again, as van Breda Kolff said, ``For us, it's all about
winning. No moral victories.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even if the tournament runs differently than others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
