<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STANFORD-AUBURN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD BEATS AUBURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ And to think, coach Mike Montgomery was
actually worried that Stanford wouldn't stand up to Auburn's
physical play.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Auburn should've been concerned. Stanford
manhandled the No. 2 Tigers, crushing them on the boards and
suffocating them defensively in a 67-58 victory Saturday in the
sixth annual John Wooden Classic at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 Stanford (5-0) solidified its position among the nation's
elite using the size of former Harvard-Westlake High twin towers
Jason and Jarron Collins, the timely play of freshman Curtis
Borchardt (15 points) and the hustle of fellow freshman Casey
Jacobsen to frustrate Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal now has wins over nationally ranked Duke and
Auburn, the latter of which has four starters back from a club that
won the Southeastern Conference Championship and reached the Sweet
16 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jarron Collins had 13 points and held Tigers All-American Chris
Porter to six points on 3-of-13 shooting. Jason Collins had 12
points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to get beat on the boards and we wanted to get
back in transition defense, because that's where Auburn beats
you,'' Jarron Collins said. ``I thought we did a great job in both
of those areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (2-1) got 21 points from Scott Pohlman and 15 points from
Doc Robinson. But the Tigers couldn't overcome Porter's poor
shooting and Stanford's size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was physical enough,'' Porter said. ``I was
getting open shots but they just weren't falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford outrebounded Auburn 46-29 and held the Tigers to a
miserable 29 percent shooting from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took it to us in the paint,'' said Auburn coach Cliff
Ellis. ``That was the game. When we play against physical teams, we
have to hold our ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Borchardt, 6-foot-10 freshman from Washington, broke a 56-56 tie
with a three-pointer with 1:35 remaining. The Cardinal outscored
the Tigers 11-2 the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ability to stay with them on the boards was critical,''
Montgomery said. ``It came down to toughness and stops in the paint
and big plays on our part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
