<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-IONA-LADN     11-28 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-IONA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA ROUTS IONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe practice doesn't make perfect, but it sure
beats the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA Bruins, so ragged in the season-opening victory, looked
like a very different team Saturday in their 105-73 victory over
Iona before a Pauley Pavilion crowd of 7,273.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Steve Lavin credited the improved play to finally
having enough bodies healthy for a week of full five-on-five
practice, but he seemed unsure just what to make of the 32-point
victory.
</P>
<P>
   First Lavin called it progress, but pretty soon he had elevated
it to a breakthrough, and then a model for how the 13th-ranked
Bruins want to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a breakthrough in practice, and I think you saw
a breakthrough in our game,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   This game saw the Bruins (2-0) play hard, and mostly under
control, the entire night. It saw all 10 Bruins on the roster play
at least 14 minutes, and all contribute. It saw their press lead to
28 Iona turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   And it saw some uplifting performances from two Bruins who had
struggled in the opening victory over Fairfield at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Earl Watson, battling a sore tailbone, right elbow and
the ghost of Baron Davis, hit only 3 of 12 field-goal attempts in
the opener and a couple of fans taunted him. Earlier in the week,
he said the tailbone was bothering him to the point where he
expected to sit out and miss the first game of his UCLA career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I was going to play,'' Watson said. ``But coach
Lavin said to wait and make a decision after the last practice.
Then that practice went real well for me, and I thought I might as
well play.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Gaels (1-2), Watson was a man who looked comfortable
and very healthy. He led the Bruins with 18 points, seven assists,
three steals and a block. And he has now started 66 consecutive
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in with a different mindset,'' Watson said. ``I knew I
wouldn't have my usual speed. I just decided to put it out of my
mind, and it ended up helping.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Young, bothered by a right thumb sprain and the tape wrapped
around it, went 0 for 6 from the field and 0 for 3 from the
free-throw line against Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   But against Iona, Young hit 5 of 6 from beyond the 3-point line
(6 of 8 overall) and helped squash outmanned Iona's lone comeback
early in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my mind early, I wasn't going to let the tape affect
my game,'' Young said. ``This week was all about trying to get my
rhythm back, and it just carried over into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of other Bruins contributed, too. Jerome Moiso had 14
points and 10 rebounds. Dan Gadzuric played animated, with 11
points, six rebounds and two blocks. Sean Farnham started
unexpectedly at forward, hit all three of his shots for eight
points, and grabbed five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean had a great week of practice and we decided to give him a
start today, and he gave us a lift,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, for just the second game of the season, the Bruins
looked fairly polished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we want to play, to take advantage of our
depth,'' Lavin said. ``We hope over the course of the game, we can
wear people out. Tonight was like a model for the way we'd like to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   For Iona, it was something less. Former NBA player Jeff Ruland
returned to his alma mater and led the Gaels to a 16-14 mark last
season. He returns five starters, but only forward Tariq Kirksay
was a consistent threat against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Kirksay led everyone with 24 points, 15 coming in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA led by nine at that point (43-34), but Watson and the
Bruins kept stretching the lead in the second half, and Iona faded
under the wave of UCLA's interchangeable parts.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin called off the full-court press when the lead first hit 30
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I see why they are ranked (13th) in the country,'' Ruland
said. ``They have tremendous athletic ability, they played hard
overall and are a good defensive team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
