<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-SKINS-LADN     11-28 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SKINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA CHIPS IN _ FOR $50,000 EAGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIO, Calif. _ On a day filled with erratic golf and missed
opportunities, leave it to the youngest competitor in Skins Game
history to supply some much-needed dramatics Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, the 19-year-old Spanish sensation, chipped in for
eagle on the eighth hole to win $50,000. It was one of only a few
memorable shots supplied by the talented foursome of Garcia, Fred
Couples, David Duval and Mark O'Meara in this 17th edition of the
competition on the demanding Landmark Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Couples won the most skins, worth $125,000, thanks to a birdie
putt on the first hole and another on the fifth. But he also drove
one ball out of bounds and picked up his ball after another errant
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who was shut out in 1997, still hasn't won any money. He
missed a three-footer on No. 7 to give a $75,000 skin to O'Meara,
the defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipated David making it for sure,'' O'Meara said.
</P>
<P>
   Duval didn't seem particularly upset over his miss, just as he
appears low-key about the weekend. He hasn't played much golf since
teaming with Couples to win the Shark Shootout a couple of weeks
ago, and didn't get into Palm Springs until Thanksgiving night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any expectations one way or the other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear, however: The par-72, 7,288-yard course,
which has been open for less than a month, was as difficult as the
players, who have had little practice time on it, thought it would
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, Landmark built a pretty tough course that's
different from a daily-fee club,'' Couples said. ``It's a country
club that everyone can play. You're not going to see flat bunkers
... you have fairways that give you a little bit of a chance, but
you're going to be in the rocks a lot. Which I was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is very, very tough and very, very good. We like
that. It could easily have been flat and made for the public to
(play) a little quicker. But if they do hit good shots, they can go
away saying, `Geez, I played the fifth hole and they made a birdie
here.' They can go away and talk about something that happened in
the Skins Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples started quickly by putting a 67-yard sand wedge to three
feet on the par-4, 382-yard first hole and making it for a $25,000
skin. The next three holes were haved with pars until the par-4,
471-yard fifth hole, which Couples birdied from 12 feet. That was
good for another $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara then got into the act two holes later when his par was
worth $75,000. Couples was out of hole off the tee and picked up,
Garcia was in heavy rough just off the green in two and did no
better than bogey and Duval missed another putt, this time from
three feet for a halve.
</P>
<P>
   It got interesting on the next hole, a 570-yard par 5. Couples
drove out of bounds, but Duval, Garcia and O'Meara each were in
good position off the tee. Duval's second shot was pin-high but
just left of the green, and O'Meara put his second shot in a bunker
short of the putting surface. His third shot came up 50 feet short
of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   That left it up to Garcia, who supplied the theatrics with his
35-yard sand wedge up and over a bunker and into the cup for an
eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to get the club under the ball,'' said Garcia,
who could not see the bottom of the flag from his position. ``When
I saw it bounce, I knew it was close.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's back nine will be worth $750,000 _ including a $200,000
``Super Skin'' on the par-5, 536-yard 18th hole _ and should lead
to better golf. The players definitely know what is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow we're playing for a ton of money,'' Couples said.
``We're all very close, even though David has nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to get some more today,'' Garcia said,
``but that's the way skins is played. Somebody makes birdie and
gets all of them. I'm looking forward to tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
