<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-DOMINGUEZHILLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BEATS DOMINGUEZ HILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Buzzers blared, sirens sounded, and strobe lights
flashed in all four corners of the Matadome at Cal State Northridge
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   No, the CSUN men's basketball team did not win the Big Sky
Conference title or break some national record to trigger the
ruckus. The outside disturbances were caused by a tripped fire
alarm late in the first half. It had little effect on the Matadors,
who defeated Cal State Dominguez Hills 80-65 in CSUN's home opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell said of the
disturbance, which was still going on after the game. ``I've seen a
lot, but I've never seen anything like that before. It was a big
distraction for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Toros, outside forces only made things worse. The
Division II school wanted an upset as badly as CSUN did last Friday
when it lost its season opener to USC.
</P>
<P>
   This time, CSUN had to protect itself against a smaller program.
The Matadors (1-1) were reminded late in the first half that the
Toros were ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell turned on the full-court press and stretched a 30-27
lead into a 44-36 margin in the final minutes of the first half.
Guard Marco McCain hit two 3-pointers during the stretch but
sprained his thumb just before halftime and was limited the rest of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors methodically put Dominguez Hills away in the second
half behind a steady offense. Meanwhile, Dominguez Hills was
limited to 39 percent shooting in the second half (11 of 28).
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had the definite size advantage,'' said CSUN center
Brian Heinle, who had a game-high 21 points on 8-of-12 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Heinle found himself open often, as the Toros (0-2) had trouble
matching up with what was basically a five-guard offense. Dominguez
Hills' biggest player was 6-foot-5 Jason Patton, who fouled out
with 4 minutes, 18 seconds remaining after playing just 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of size left room in the middle for CSUN's Hewitt
Rolle, who collected a career-high 14 rebounds to go with eight
points. Rolle started both games for the Matadors this season while
Andre Larry serves a two-game suspension for playing in an
unsanctioned summer league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable starting,'' Rolle said. ``If I have to come
off the bench, I'll still feel the same way about playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors outrebounded Dominguez Hills 40-27 and shot 50.8
percent (33 of 65) from the field. The only bad news came on the
injury front. The Matadors learned 6-6 forward Jermar Welch will
have surgery on his left thumb Tuesday to repair torn ligaments he
suffered in the USC game. He will miss eight to 10 weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
