r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-TRAILBLA     11-28 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-TRAILBLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FALL TO TRAIL BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In their first bookie-proof performance of a
rapidly aging season, the Los Angeles Clippers didn't cover
anything but their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly didn't cover whatever the underdog's side of the
spread was for Saturday's Staples Center date with mighty Portland,
the Trail Blazers rolling to an 88-71 victory in front of 14,552
refund-conscious patrons.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clippers defensive coverage was a bit friendly, too, the
merciless Blazers (13-2) requiring little finesse to finish their
offensive sets. Damon Stoudamire fattened up on the generosity with
24 points, and Scottie Pippen went for 10 points, 10 assists and
nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, which didn't need a rain check on the first crucial
shopping weekend of the season, pushed its lead to 25 midway
through the final act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, we just kind of laid down,'' said rookie Lamar Odom,
who had six rebounds and six assists, but his 15 points came at the
mercy of 6-of-18 shooting from the field. ``I don't even know what
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Say, goodnight.
</P>
<P>
   Portland coach Mike Dunleavy, whose team defeated Houston in
overtime Friday, was shooting for diplomacy: ``We kind of needed
any easy win.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We competed until it was 33-30 (Portland),'' said Clippers
coach Chris Ford, whose young team might have entertained a
residual funk after letting Friday's game at Seattle slip away. ``I
just wish our guys had competed; not competing is a thing I can't
accept.''
</P>
<P>
   The point total was the Clippers' bottom line for the season. A
five-point salvo during the last 34.5 seconds prevented the
Clippers from slaughtering the franchise-record for fewest points
(68).
</P>
<P>
   Their field-goal percentage (32.9) threatened to bend lower than
the Blazers will pick in next June's NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   They missed 12 of 25 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Their relentless sharing offense generated 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Their leading scorer, Derek Anderson, scored six points in 29
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' go-to citizen, Maurice Taylor, didn't suit up for
the seventh consecutive game after spraining his left foot two
weeks ago. After having the wheel examined at halftime, Taylor is
expected to play in Tuesday's game with Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't assume anything,'' Ford said of Taylor's return,
citing conditioning and other potential hazards. ``I just wish we
had done whatever it takes to show the crowd you're working your
butt off.''
</P>
<P>
   We didn't ask any fans, but we're certain they could see a
little butt left over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
