<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL _ Georgia Sen. Paul Coverdell is acting as George
Bush's ``point man'' in the Senate, keeping Bush informed about
actions in Washington and his fellow Senators informed about Bush.
That task grew testy during Bush's recent criticism of
congressional Republicans. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Five years and billions of
dollars after launching the most ambitious attack on illegal
immigration in the nation's history, the U.S. Border Patrol cannot
show any sign that the flow across the U.S.-Mexico border has
slowed. In fact, it appears to have increased despite the agency's
aggressive new strategy. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-DANGER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Many illegal immigrants are
losing their lives in the deserts and mountains and cactus scrub
that dominate the border. That was not part of the plan. In April,
a freak snowstorm in the mountains east of San Diego killed eight
immigrants. Throughout the border, ranchers and agents regularly
find bodies, especially during droughts when watering holes and
livestock tanks that sustain illegal immigrants dry up. No one
knows how many bodies lie undiscovered.(Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-SMOKE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Fifteen-year-old Langston Burgess
and others in the Teen Waves Wellness Coalition want to hear more
ideas about knocking down smoking percentages at the Teen Tobacco
Summit. The strategy they've focused on is more effective warning
labels on cigarette packs. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
