<SLUG> BC-FASHION-VALVO29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dress to the nines to ring out '99
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _Carmen Marc Valvo's doctor father dreamed
that his son would become a plastic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   But the young Valvo loved fashion. He sketched bellbottoms for
his sister's Barbies and later earned a degree in fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   He's designed under his own name for the last decade, and his
slinky, glittery evening wear has earned fans among the glitterati
that include Gwyneth Paltrow, Jennifer Aniston and Salma Hayek.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, he's now doing the work of a plastic surgeon, but with
scissors instead of scalpels. ``To help a woman feel as beautiful
as she can, that's my biggest reward,'' Valvo says.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent visit to Boca Raton's Saks Fifth Avenue, the
46-year-old Valvo offered these designs for living it up on New
Year's Eve:
</P>
<P>
   _ If you've chosen a floor-length gown, wear it long.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dress too short is a common mistake, Valvo says.
``Women say they want to dance, but if it clears your toe, you're
not going to walk on it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tailor your accessories to your dress. And don't overdo it.
</P>
<P>
   With a microbeaded gown, all you need is ``a great, fabulous
earring,'' Valvo says. ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you're wearing a strapless black cashmere
gown, ``break out the family jewels.''
</P>
<P>
   _ To thine own self be true.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to be Lauryn Hill if you more closely resemble Lauren
Bacall. Know if you are more Demi Moore or Mary Tyler Moore. Then
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   One of Valvo's favorite celebrity clients is actress Julia
Ormond because ``she has a good sense of what suits her and what
doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cover up.
</P>
<P>
   Valvo says he likes women to look like women, ``to dress as sexy
and bare and mysterious as she feels comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   But he designs jackets, boleros and stoles for all his gowns
because he feels it's more dramatic for a woman to make an entrance
covered up and then _ ta-da! _ reveal what's under her wrap.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go all out.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, Valvo is playing host to family and friends
at his home in the Hamptons, and they'll all sit down for a
black-tie dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get as dressy as you possibly can, even if you're entertaining
at home,'' he says. ``Indulge. It's the last time this century that
you're going to be able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: stacisturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
