A3149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-LANE-COLUMN29-COX     11-28 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Car coaching can be a lesson in fear
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The first instinct of parents is to
protect their young. So why do we teach them how to drive?
</P>
<P>
   The foolishness of doing this occurred to me as I watched a stop
sign get big very fast, right in front of me.
</P>
<P>
   I did not shout. Not out of self-control but because nothing
happened when I opened my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the sign, a truck, a dump truck weighed
down with gravel, roared past, flinging loose pebbles in its wake,
its engine whining under its burden. And we kept moving toward it,
my teen-aged daughter at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But she stopped abruptly, the car stalled out. When I opened my
eyes, I wasn't in heaven. I was in Brevard County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time ... press the clutch ... or get out of gear ...
before hitting ... the brake ... and do it ... a little ... a
little ... sooner,'' I suggested. My words were came out in little
clumps as I concentrated on resuming a process of breathing in and
breathing out. Something that normally happens all by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody drives manual shifts anymore,'' my daughter informed me
matter-of-factly and not at all like someone who might have
troubled my colleagues to write a very moving obituary on a
weekend. ``You are the only one who drives one who's not like
driving a truck or something.''
</P>
<P>
   She had a point. I learned how to drive in a manual-transmission
car. Like your first love, your first car shapes the rest of your
life. I learned to drive in a Volkswagen bug, the real old kind
that lacked the extras. Extras like a gas gauge.
</P>
<P>
   Because I started as a bug driver, I developed a few odd driving
habits. I step on the gas at the base of hills to build enough
momentum to get over the top. And I shift gears later than I really
should. I like to hear a bit of a whine before I flick the shift.
</P>
<P>
   These are not bad things. These are not dangerous things. They
just don't always make sense to automotive critics. Or
``passengers'' as they are sometimes called.
</P>
<P>
   I am a good driver but a poor judge of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Mellow, nonjudgmental people get into my car and are transformed
into purists of the road. There is a worn spot on my passenger-side
car mat from their incessant pounding of imaginary brakes. I hate
it when they loudly promise, to no one I can see, that they will
live better lives if they reach their destination intact.
</P>
<P>
   They generally behave like wimps. It disgusts me when they start
whimpering and attempting to fling the door open before I've
stopped the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Enduring such insults at the hands of a carping, fault-finding
society, I resolved to do better by my kids and pass on the family
driving techniques. Not just the basics, but the skills that took
me a lifetime to perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Like how to steer with your knees while using both hands to open
the cellophane on a Little Debbie cake. How to know the difference
between the death-grind of worn brakes and the familiar
metal-on-metal sounds of deferrable maintenance. How to discern the
difference between a stop sign that means it and a stop sign that
is just for show.
</P>
<P>
   They don't teach you those things in drivers ed. They come from
hard-won experience.
</P>
<P>
   I had intended to transmit this rich storehouse of knowledge.
Now I'm not so sure. The first time out took a lot out of me.
</P>
<P>
   One tends to assume that a lot of driving is automatic, that
skills such as driving inside the white lines somehow are
instinctual.
</P>
<P>
   It takes only one outing with a student driver to understand
otherwise. This is not useful knowledge. It increases one's normal
fears of the road. You can drive with confidence only if you just
assume _ however falsely _ that cars naturally tend to stay on the
road. Finding out this is false is a tough lesson.
</P>
<P>
   I drove home at 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   I am over it now and back to my old form. But Lesson Two cannot
be too far away and I dread what I will learn next. Still, I'm
going to keep with it. This will all be worth it when I'm at last
able to take my turn as a hypercritical, complaining passenger. I'm
already memorizing the ``Florida Driver's Handbook'' and practicing
my lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like you signaled 100 feet before that turn.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
