<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-REPETITIVE-MOTION-29-     11-28 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPETITIVE-MOTION-29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author claims stretches may help repetitive motion injuries
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Sue MacDonald was a skeptical reporter, so she
wasn't buying Richard H. Rossiter's claims until he put her through
20 minutes of stretches. It relieved 20 years of pain in her
telephone shoulder. ``You should write a book about this,'' she
told him.
</P>
<P>
   Rossiter wrote ``Overcoming Repetitive Motion Injuries the
Rossiter Way'' with MacDonald to give more people access to
Rossiter's pain-relieving techniques of manipulating connective
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Where physicians typically treat a sore wrist, say, by focusing
on the wrist, Rossiter approaches the soreness as a symptom of a
broader problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as a chain,'' he says of the linkage among
tendons, ligaments and smaller connective tissues. Ideally, if a
person puts the thumb and forefinger of one hand on the bridge of
his nose and wiggles the fingers of his other hand, he'll feel some
movement up at the nose. ``It's a continuous strand all through the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   So fixing only the broken link in a chain won't solve the
problem, Rossiter says, without also loosening the kinks throughout
the chain that put stress on that link in the first place. ``If
everything's tight, then one of them has got to break. You've got
to loosen each link.''
</P>
<P>
   No extensive research has been done on the Rossiter System, but
the role of connective tissue in repetitive-motion injuries is well
understood by physical therapists and physiatrists, the burgeoning
and progressive specialty of physical and rehabilitative medicine.
``That's what is injured,'' says Dr. Dave Mitchell, a physiatrist
who is not familiar with Rossiter's program.
</P>
<P>
   Rossiter says the companies using his regimen have consistently
seen decreases in costs associated with repetitive-motion, or
repetitive-stress injuries (RMIs or RSIs). Workers' compensation
costs at Hollytex Carpet Mills in Anadarko, Okla., were $550
million for a company of 500 in 1993, the year it signed up
Rossiter. Those costs dropped steadily for three years before
leveling off at $65 million a year, according to the company. And
despite letting employees do 20 to 30 minutes of stretches two or
three times a week on company time, Hollytex reported no decline in
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration put RSIs in the spotlight this week
by announcing new workplace ergonomics regulations aimed at
reducing the 1.8 million such workplace injuries every year.
Although businesses are balking at the estimated $4.2 billion
annual cost, that is far less than the $13 billion in treatment
costs and $100 billion in lost productivity attributed to RSIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an epidemic of carpal tunnel syndrome,'' says
Mitchell, attributing it largely to computer keys that don't have
the give of typewriter keys. Golfer's or tennis elbow also has
become widespread, he says, ``and they all hurt like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   RSIs surface in necks, shoulders, arms, fingers, lower backs,
legs and elsewhere as a result of continually repeating any motion
from typing to cutting to lifting. Besides pain, they can cause
tingling and numbness.
</P>
<P>
   Rossiter's search for a better way to treat them began with his
quest to relieve his own chronic shoulder pain from his injury as
an Army helicopter pilot. Now 49, the Little Rock, Ark., resident
found the answer at the Rolf Institute of Structural Integration's
deep-tissue manipulation of connective tissue, became a certified
Rolfer himself and developed his simpler techniques with the help
of clients who were otherwise untreatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I've got a patient who's doing everything I tell them to
do and they're not getting better, I'm pretty sure the problem is
connective tissue,'' Mitchell says. ``It's hard to fix. That's why
the athletes say they'd rather break it than sprain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients should bear in mind that carpal tunnel syndrome
involves nerve damage that can require surgery, Mitchell says, and
Rossiter agrees that some people will need the stronger treatments
of drug injections or surgery. What Rossiter regrets is that so
many people try drugs or surgery first, damaging their connective
tissue to the point where ``we can only get you back maybe halfway,
if you're lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go with the least invasive way first,'' Rossiter says.
``If stretching all the tissue back out fixes the problem, that was
obviously the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In 10 years of teaching the stretches, Rossiter has ``never had
a hint of a liability complaint,'' says MacDonald, who writes for
The Cincinnati Enquirer. The book and its photos describe six
stretches for the arm-to-neck axis and four for the lower back.
</P>
<P>
   To do the stretches, a patient needs a partner with a clean pair
of socks because the partner starts by applying a foot's width of
weight to a particular area of connective tissue. The foot's warmth
alone begins stretching the tissue, and the patient augments the
stretch by extending his or her limbs in a specified way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like Silly Putty,'' MacDonald says. ``When you
add warmth to it with your hand, it gets more supple and more
pliable and then you can stretch it out and loosen it up.''
</P>
<P>
   People often say the stretches themselves ``hurt good,'' she
says. ``You're very aware there's tension in the body, but you can
feel yourself stretching the pain away.'' Afterward, she says the
limb feels free and loose, not so heavy anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I think people just get used to living with pain,''
MacDonald says. ``I think people today are so stressed and tight
that sometimes they don't realize how you're supposed to feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
