<HEADER>
A3151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-STAYLIT-TREES29-COX     11-28 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAYLIT-TREES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    His idea keeps trees lighted
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ John Janning, the Ohio inventor who helped
make liquid-crystal display calculators and wrist watches possible,
knows his latest invention won't have the same world-changing
significance.
</P>
<P>
   But the way he sees it, his Stay Lit Christmas tree light system
will mean peace on Earth for Christmas tree owners and a
respectable financial return for him and his shareholders. That's
good enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   Janning, who bills himself as an ``inventor for hire,'' has
developed light strands that remain lit when one or more burn out,
fall out or come loose. The product goes to market for the first
time this year and is being sold through retailers such as Kmart,
Lowe's and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Stay Lit will do is end frustration in the world,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janning's interest in Christmas lights first sparked in the
mid-1990s when his wife repeatedly asked him to locate bad bulbs on
the holiday tree. After using the lengthy and frustrating process
of trial and error to locate them, the scientist decided to find a
better way.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: he developed a small tube that when slid over a
bulb would indicate whether it still worked. With the apparatus, he
could find a faulty bulb on a 50-light strand within 30 seconds
without pulling out a bulb, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janning made 50 of the tubes and gave them to family as gifts.
He also offered the idea to decoration maker Noma. The two sides
never struck a deal, but executives told Janning that if he
developed a foolproof light strand, they wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   Janning took them up on the offer and developed one within two
weeks. He created a shunt _ two zener diodes on single chip inside
a plastic tube small enough to fit in the socket underneath the
bulb. When a bulb stops carrying current for any reason, the shunt
completes the circuit between the working bulbs so the strand
remains lit.
</P>
<P>
   Noma U.S. has licensed indoor/outdoor Stay lit light strings in
the U.S. while Alderbrook has Canadian licensing rights for the
50-light indoor string. Janning also is negotiating international
licensing rights through Stay Lit International, an organization he
owns with shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Uses for the Stay Lit product are expected to grow. Noma
executives want to include the lights not only on pre-lit trees,
which this year are sold only at Lowe's, but also on other Yuletide
decorations such as icicles, statuaries and wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry estimates, there are about 14 billion
Christmas light sockets in the U.S. Noma wants Stay Lit to account
for 10 percent of that market next year and then 20 percent after
that. To meet that demand next year, Noma will need one billion
chips, Janning said.
</P>
<P>
   If Janning's invention hits it big, it wouldn't be his first.
While employed at NCR Corp., Janning developed the molecular
alignment process that allowed for widespread use of liquid crystal
display technology. Janning retired from NCR in 1988 but continues
to do consulting for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Stay Lit bulbs go to market, Janning is working to make
his current invention obsolete. He has developed a new chip that
encases 10 diodes in a small rectangular box small enough to fit
underneath the Christmas bulbs. The new apparatus costs less to
produce and is more efficient than the shunt currently used in Stay
Lit bulbs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like socks on a rooster,'' he said. ``It's really, really
neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: Timtresslar(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
