<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BORDER-DANGER29-COX     11-28 1977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-DANGER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More agents, immigrants travel dangerous terrain
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Many illegal immigrants are losing their lives
in the deserts and mountains and cactus scrub that dominate the
border. That was not part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured that once we could contain the heavy entry points,
the downtown areas, ... that would be the deterrent,'' said de la
Vina, the Border Patrol chief. ``We never figured they would move
into the desert. (In San Diego) we weren't even patrolling those
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, a freak snowstorm in the mountains east of San Diego
killed eight immigrants. Throughout the border, ranchers and agents
regularly find bodies, especially during droughts when watering
holes and livestock tanks that sustain illegal immigrants dry up.
No one knows how many bodies lie undiscovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we're killing people,'' said Nathan Selzer of
Proyecto Libertad, an immigrant advocacy group in Harlingen. ``The
immigration service knows full well that these people are not going
to simply stop coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual body count is elusive. Mexico counted 357 last year.
The Border Patrol's 1998 total was 276, not including those on the
Mexican side. When University of Houston researchers recently
combed border death records, they found 1,600 suspected migrant
deaths from 1993 to 1997. They concluded that, overall, deaths have
not increased much; however, more people are dying from heat and
cold while fewer are killed by cars on San Diego's freeways or from
other causes.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol, which has added rescue work to its duties,
blames the immigrant deaths on the coyotes, who are thriving as
more and more people search for a way around the blockades. The
coyotes routinely lead poorly prepared groups on days-long marches
through dangerous terrain or pack them into unventilated
semitrailers. The sick, the weak and the injured often are left to
fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In late July, Jesus Carrillo and two relatives floated across
the river on an inner tube and began walking through the mesquite
scrub, following the coyote they met in the restaurant next to the
Nuevo Laredo bus station. The man's price seemed reasonable _ $800
each to Dallas _ but that was before Carrillo saw the coyote slide
the hypodermic needle into the bruised crook of his arm. It was too
late by then.
</P>
<P>
   After five hours on the dirt path, the coyote stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Don't move; I'll be right back,''' Carrillo said.
The smuggler never returned. By the next afternoon, with the July
temperatures hovering at 105 degrees and their water down to a half
gallon, they somehow found their way to Interstate 35, emerging 50
yards from the Border Patrol checkpoint. They gladly surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants aren't the only people risking their lives on the
border. Agents face additional dangers as the new strategy forces
immigrants into more rugged terrain. Three agents, each with three
years' experience or less, have died in the mountains east of San
Diego after driving or falling off cliffs while pursuing suspected
illegal immigrants. San Diego Sector spokesman Roy Villareal said
footprints left by one of them ``indicate he was in full stride.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s have been the deadliest decade ever for Border Patrol
agents, surpassing even the 1920s, when agents routinely exchanged
fire with Prohibition-era bootleggers. Twelve of the 16 agents who
died on duty in the '20s were murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of this decade's 17 on-duty deaths have come since
January 1995, after the new strategy began. In addition to two
fatal falls, seven agents died in auto or aircraft accidents, three
suffered heart attacks, and four were shot to death _ including two
gunned down near Harlingen last year while backing up local
officers.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO'S `POBLACION FLOTANTE'
</P>
<P>
   In a small concrete building on the Mexican side of the bridge
connecting Laredo with Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas, Octavio Reyes
Gonzalez waits for the Border Patrol buses and vans to deliver the
would-be immigrants who have been caught.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes, a Mexican immigration agent, ushers as many as 500 people
a day into his cramped office and asks them to fill out a
questionnaire _ little more than name, age and hometown _ before
they melt back into the streets. In Nuevo Laredo alone, 160,000
Mexicans were sent back over the bridge last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look tired, they have no money, and they're hungry,''
Reyes said. ``Some people say they're going back home; some say
they're going to try again. Some people are stuck over here because
they don't have any money to go back home. We call them the
`poblacion flotante.''' The floating population.
</P>
<P>
   They are the ones who worry Mexican border towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sleep in abandoned lots and houses. Then they finally end
up invading (private) land, and they set up their small huts,''
said Nuevo Laredo City Council Member Ernesto Ferrara Theriot.
``That's when the problem comes to the city government, because
after several months they come asking for water and city
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestor Rodriguez, a professor at the University of Houston
Center for Immigration Research, said other border cities are
facing the same problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not going to stop coming, so there's going to be a
pressure point somewhere, and it's happening in those Mexican
border towns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To relieve the pressure, Nuevo Laredo gives free bus tickets to
people who want to return home _ though Reyes said the tickets
don't come close to meeting the demand. Reynosa city spokesman
Francisco Garcia said his city plans to revive its $10,000-a-year
bus ticket program, because it's cheaper to send them home than to
provide ``all the things they need to live.''
</P>
<P>
   With no city homeless shelters in Reynosa, displaced migrants
turn to the few church-run shelters in town. At the Guadalupe
Catholic Church shelter, where dozens come every day to eat
church-cooked lunches, Father Oscar Guadalupe Lozano said the 19
beds are not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are 30 or 35 who stay here, who sleep in any
corner so they're not out in the street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECTION OR OCCUPATION?
</P>
<P>
   Most U.S. border residents seem to support the new strategy.
Behind the counter at Zepeda Hardware in Brownsville, Mary Zepeda
said the agents have driven away the gangs of juveniles who used to
shoplift with impunity from downtown stores. Upriver in San Pedro,
Jesus Mesa said the people who used to pass his house ``like ants,
day and night'' no longer ask him for water or old shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Brownsville Police Chief Ben Reyna said the bandits who used to
lurk along the riverbank, robbing, raping and killing illegal
immigrants before fleeing into Mexico, have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even remember the last (bandit crime) we had,'' he
said. ``We're very, very pleased with what the Border Patrol is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol may never be able to control the entire
border, but reducing traffic through border cities is a major
accomplishment, said Michael Fix, director of immigration studies
for the Urban Institute, a Washington, D.C., think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point is, this is kind of a shield for the border
cities,'' Fix said, ``and that in itself I think is justification
for doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cameron County Judge Gilbert Hinojosa is not pleased,
especially after a Border Patrol agent at the airport asked him to
declare his citizenship and wouldn't let him board the plane until
he did. His secretary, who lives near the river, has been stopped
several times so agents could search her vehicle for illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really do make us feel like we're in occupied
territory,'' Hinojosa said. ``People here are loyal U.S. citizens
... and that they have to be submitted to this kind of harassment
so (Border Patrol) can stop illegal aliens from going to Chicago
and Denver and Detroit is just an insult.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics question why the nation's leaders have focused so
much attention on the Mexico border while only about 300 agents
guard the 4,000-mile border with Canada, and millions of illegal
immigrants who have overstayed their visas are virtually ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a sort of insidious form of racism: We don't want
brown people,'' said Ouisa Davis, who works for Diocesan Migrant
and Refugee Services in El Paso. ``(Illegal immigrants) are easy
targets. These people have no political power.''
</P>
<P>
   INS officials estimate that as many as half of all illegal
immigrants did not sneak across the border but entered using
tourist, student or business visas and remained in the country
after their visas expired. INS officials say no one is actively
looking for them. Only about 8,500 so-called visa overstayers were
caught and deported in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   SHOULD BUILDUP CONTINUE?
</P>
<P>
   Whether Americans want to continue the border buildup is the
billion-dollar question.
</P>
<P>
   While polls consistently find that most Americans consider
illegal immigration a serious problem, immigration agents say the
public often winces at the reality of crackdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Pass rancher Dob Cunningham understands this
contradiction. He wants relief from the immigrants who march across
his property, leaving downed fences and empty water jugs in their
wake. But he can't help but admire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for those people,'' Cunningham said.
``They'll walk from Mexico to Dallas for a job, and people here
won't cross the street for one.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress set the wheels for the buildup in motion as the country
was pulling out of a recession, and supporters had a list of
reasons for controlling the border _ protecting American jobs from
cheap foreign labor; stopping drug traffickers; giving schools and
welfare agencies relief from dependent foreigners; protecting
border cities from crime.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the nation's economy humming and demand for workers
increasing, some immigration experts think support for the buildup
is fading in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Krikorian, the Center for Immigration Studies director, said the
anti-immigrant sentiment that rose from California's recession in
the early 1990s and the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center by
foreign terrorists ``created momentum to do something, but that
momentum has passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol expansion is now the focus of a political
battle. The Clinton administration has declared its continued
support for the strategy but recently tried to slash money for new
agents from its 2000 budget, arguing that the Border Patrol needed
a ``breather'' to let new agents gain experience.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Congress pushed through money for another
1,000 new agents next year, although the agency was able to add
only 369 agents last year. The Border Patrol blamed attrition and a
tight labor market. Congress accused the agency and the
administration of dragging their heels.
</P>
<P>
   Krikorian said Americans need to understand that illegal
immigration isn't a problem to be solved ``but a permanent
phenomenon, like the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees the changing of immigration routes as a sign of success.
But Antonio Zavaleta, a vice president at the University of Texas
at Brownsville, said America's booming economy will continue to
lure impoverished people, regardless of the obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Bob Santos doesn't see how anything will turn away the
people he chases every day, the thin young men and the wrinkled old
men and the women clutching infants, all of them poor and desperate
and repeating the illegal immigrants' mantra: I just want to work
to help my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff hits home,'' Santos said, driving down a
dust-choked trail next to the Rio Grande. ``You want to stop it?
You need to improve conditions in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
