<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BORDER-PATROL29-COX     11-28 2496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rising captures suggest migrants skirt blockades
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Five years and billions of dollars after
launching the most ambitious attack on illegal immigration in the
nation's history, the U.S. Border Patrol cannot show any sign that
the flow across the U.S.-Mexico border has slowed. In fact, it
appears to have increased despite the agency's aggressive new
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol has doubled in size since 1994 and completely
changed tactics: By concentrating agents and high-tech equipment to
blockade major border cities, the Border Patrol hoped to deter many
would-be crossers and force the rest into rural areas, where they
could not blend into city crowds to avoid capture.
</P>
<P>
   The agency insists the strategy works, pointing to dramatic
results at major crossing points as proof: Apprehensions of illegal
immigrants have hit a 24-year low near San Diego, and have dropped
by half in El Paso, Texas, since 1993. Many immigrants say crossing
the border is now more difficult and more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But by applying the agency's own measuring stick _ the number of
apprehensions _ along the entire border, the strategy appears to be
failing: Agents apprehended more than 1.5 million people last year.
That's 300,000 more than in 1993 and just under the all-time record
of 1.6 million in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol cannot say how many people get past its
agents. But immigrants interviewed in Austin, in Mexico and on the
border say the blockades have had little impact on the overall flow
of people lured north by U.S. jobs that pay more in a day than most
Mexicans earn in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal immigrants reacted to the blockades by going around
them. They have shifted their routes on a grand scale, flooding the
more lightly guarded areas such as Southeast Arizona, where
apprehensions have more than tripled since the new strategy began.
</P>
<P>
   The blockades also are undercut by a revolving door that sends
98 of every 100 people caught at the border back to Mexico with no
criminal charges. They avoid formal deportation; the Border Patrol
avoids overwhelming already swamped federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we can put these people in detention facilities
when you're talking about 1.5 million (apprehensions) a year,''
said Border Patrol Chief Gus de la Vina.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that many illegal immigrants see the border
blockades more as an inconvenience than a deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Flores Roman, a 29-year-old Juarez construction worker
who says he's made ``countless'' illegal trips into the United
States to work, avoids the line of agents at El Paso by crossing
near lightly patrolled Fabens, 30 miles downriver.
</P>
<P>
   When agents caught him in July in a Fabens pecan orchard, Flores
was back in Mexico within two hours. ``When they take me back,'' he
said before hopping on a Border Patrol bus, ``I'm going to try
again.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Vina said the Border Patrol is confident that as it
expands the blockades in phases across the 2,000-mile border, the
pressure will wear down immigrants like Flores: ``We catch them, we
send them back. They make another attempt, and we catch them
again.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no deadline for completing the strategy, and the Border
Patrol cannot say how much money or how many agents it will
ultimately need. Outside estimates go as high as 20,000 agents _
roughly 2 1/2 times the current 8,351-member force, which has a
1999 budget of $864 million.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Border Patrol is having difficulty recruiting
enough agents to maintain its expansion. In Washington, the Clinton
administration has tried to slow the agency's growth. And the U.S.
General Accounting Office, which reviews the strategy annually, has
concluded that ``despite the investment of billions of dollars,''
the Immigration and Naturalization Service _ the Border Patrol's
parent agency _ ``did not know whether the investment was producing
the intended results.'' The total cost of the strategy since 1994
is approaching $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If the strategy ultimately works _ and even Border Patrol agents
say that's a big if _ it would have major implications for Austin
and other U.S. cities that rely on illegal labor. In the meantime,
the strategy has had repercussions, some of them unintended, all
along the border:
</P>
<P>
   _ Since the buildup began, hundreds of immigrants have died from
extreme heat or cold after venturing into harsh terrain to avoid
the blockades. Several agents have died chasing them over the same
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   _ The blockades have given more business to smugglers. Coyotes,
as the smugglers of people are called, are raising their fees _ the
going rate from the border to Austin is $1,000 to $1,500 a person,
up from about $700 a few years ago _ and often leaving stragglers
behind to die during the journey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mexican border cities say the buildup has flooded them with
penniless deportees who are straining city services, though many
U.S. border residents say it has reduced crime in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Some immigration experts see a gut-level conflict as a nation of
immigrants tries to figure out how to confront illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to see guys in Smokey the Bear hats on the
border, but nobody wants to see Jose across the street with his
nice family get deported, and that's why we can't get anywhere on
this problem,'' said Mark Krikorian, executive director of a
Washington-based think tank, Center for Immigration Studies, which
favors reduced immigration and the Border Patrol expansion.
</P>
<P>
   THE BORDER BLOCKADES
</P>
<P>
   Where the Rio Grande winds through Brownsville on its way to the
Gulf of Mexico, the forces gathered on the riverbank look prepared
to repel an invasion. Here, the United States has deployed hundreds
of agents equipped with advanced technology to keep out some of the
hemisphere's poorest people.
</P>
<P>
   As helicopters thump overhead, Border Patrol agents sit in
parked vehicles within sight of each other on the wide levee.
Insects swirl around stadium-style lights pointed at open fields.
Agents in air-conditioned boxes perched on hydraulic legs scan the
river's edges with night-vision cameras, which turn body heat into
ghostly green silhouettes. Sensors buried under well-worn dirt
paths wait for passing footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Across the river, people sit in stands of brush and narrow
ravines, watching and waiting. Some plan to work and live in the
United States indefinitely. Others will spend most of each year
working north of the border and return home for the winter
holidays. A good number are border residents who lack the papers or
the inclination to use the international bridges and routinely
cross the river to visit friends and family, shop and work.
</P>
<P>
   To stop them, the Border Patrol's McAllen Sector, which includes
Brownsville, has grown from 501 to 1,166 agents in the past three
years. Agents are now stationed around the clock along the river
from the Gulf of Mexico to the Harlingen area.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we said is, as opposed to sitting back and waiting for
these individuals, let's get right up in their face,'' said Jaime
Salazar, a Brownsville Border Patrol supervisor. ``If they come to
the riverbank on the Mexican side and look into the U.S., they need
to see a big old friendly Border Patrol agent smiling at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar blockades are in place in El Paso, Laredo, San Diego and
Nogales, Ariz., and apprehensions dropped in each city after the
new strategy began, although they are up again in Nogales.
Meanwhile, apprehensions have increased dramatically in places such
as Eagle Pass, Douglas, Ariz., and the El Centro Sector in
southeast California _ where the total skyrocketed from 27,654 to
225,279 in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Are more or fewer people trying to cross since the blockades
began? Are agents catching a higher or lower percentage of those
who attempt to cross? The Border Patrol isn't sure because
apprehensions are an imperfect measure of success. They reflect
total arrests but not how many individuals are caught, and many
illegal immigrants are caught repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Border Patrol stations began using a new computer
system, called IDENT, which allows agents to take digital
photographs and fingerprints of illegal immigrants. Many immigrants
give agents false names and carry no identification.
</P>
<P>
   The $84.6 million system tells agents in the field how many
times someone has been caught. Each Border Patrol station appears
to have a different threshold for sending someone to federal court
for prosecution and formal deportation. In Laredo, it's the sixth
apprehension. In Eagle Pass, it's the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   When IDENT debuted, the INS hailed it as a tool to help track
migration patterns and repeat offenders. But so far, it has not
shed any light on whether the new border strategy is actually
deterring illegal immigrants. Agency officials have not yet
finished analyzing IDENT data to see if the number of repeat
offenders has changed.
</P>
<P>
   The new operations have raised tensions in some places. In
California, agents have been the targets of bullets, rocks and
Molotov cocktails. Last year near San Diego, agents shot at four
illegal immigrants in one week, killing two of them, after the
immigrants allegedly wielded rocks or tried to run down agents with
cars. The shootings were ruled justified.
</P>
<P>
   In Southeast Arizona, which has overtaken San Diego as the
nation's busiest crossing point, an estimated 600 Mexicans
simultaneously rushed agents in April, a sight one agent compared
to ``the beginning of a 10K run.'' Angry Arizona ranchers have
resorted to rounding up illegal immigrants at gunpoint, and
residents of that state have demanded that the governor call in the
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   HOLES IN THE DIKE
</P>
<P>
   For most of the Border Patrol's 75-year existence, badly
outnumbered agents have tried to hold back generations of
bootleggers, drug smugglers, bandits and immigrants, with little
success. The INS estimates that more than 5 million illegal
immigrants now live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   John Attanasio, a veteran agent now working at the Border Patrol
Academy in South Carolina, remembers the feeling of futility:
``When you're the only (agent), and a hundred people are running by
you, and you yell `Stop! Stop!' and they keep running by you on
both sides, you feel kind of stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The old way of doing things required agents to roam in search of
people who had already crossed the border, chasing them through
downtown streets, pulling them over on highways, tracking them
through ranchland, and sometimes lying in wait for large groups
along remote footpaths.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in 1993 when Sylvestre Reyes, the new chief
of the Border Patrol's El Paso Sector, looked at the mess he had
inherited: 250,000 illegal immigrants caught each year pouring over
the border; downtown merchants upset about loitering and
shoplifting; citizens complaining of being hassled for looking
Mexican. Reyes, now a congressman, concentrated 400 of the sector's
600 agents within sight of each other along a 20-mile stretch of
the river.
</P>
<P>
   The move created an uproar in Mexico, but Operation Hold the
Line made apprehensions plunge almost overnight. When they kept
dropping, from 285,000 to 79,000 in a year, Washington took notice,
and Reyes' experiment became the blueprint for a new era for the
Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   When the Border Patrol changed tactics, illegal immigrants did
what they have always done. They adapted, tapping into a grapevine
that reaches into even the smallest villages of Mexico and Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   Some already in the United States no longer make their annual
trip home, deciding to stay in the country for longer periods to
avoid the risk and expense of sneaking across the border. Other
immigrants pass through lightly guarded cities such as Eagle Pass
or try to wiggle through the blockades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had heard that it would be easy to cross here, so this is
where we came,'' said Joel Lopez Torrez, a 29-year-old Mexican
farmer who was caught near Eagle Pass as he tried to get to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In Eagle Pass, which isn't yet using the blockades,
apprehensions have more than tripled since 1994. On a given shift,
the station might have as few as 20 agents trying to patrol 56
miles of twisting river. In July, they caught more than 4,300
illegal immigrants. Forty-eight people have died in the area this
year on both sides of the river, according to the Mexican
consulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting overrun, but the guys are handling it,'' said
agent Esteban Ramirez, a 23-year veteran. ``You do what you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Even where the Border Patrol is strongest, people regularly slip
past them _ often to the amazement of agents.
</P>
<P>
   Smugglers have sent local youths across the river as decoys, and
one bought a used Federal Express truck to transport groups.
Immigrants have tied pieces of carpet to their feet to obscure
their tracks. El Paso agents have found flashlights stashed in
storm drains _ clues that the immigrants were passing underneath
them. Agents recently discovered a network of 50 to 60 hand-dug
tunnels under the city.
</P>
<P>
   Near Laredo, Border Patrol supervisor Jose ``Joe Bob'' Gonzales
ducked into a maze of passages the immigrants had burrowed into the
thick apron of cane at the river's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as (an illegal immigrant) sees you, he hits that path
and he keeps going and going, then he turns north and ffft, he's
gone,'' Gonzales said. ``You know, you could put a guy every
quarter-mile here, and they'd still find a way to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   They are desperate. Although Mexico's economy is rebounding
since a devastating 1994 peso devaluation, unemployment and low pay
are still chronic problems. Poverty, combined with recent natural
disasters _ an ongoing drought in the north, floods in the south _
continue driving people over the border.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Angel Amaro Morales, 29, said he could not support his wife
and three children on the $40 a week he earned working construction
in Monterrey. When agents caught him in Laredo this summer _ for
the third time this year _ he said he and his companions planned to
cross again to resume their march to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot go home now, he said. ``There's no work.''
</P>
<P>
   EFFECTS OF BUILDUP
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol buildup has had repercussions, some of them
unintended, along the 2,000-mile boundary:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hundreds of immigrants have died from extreme heat or cold
venturing into harsh terrain to avoid the blockades, and several
agents have died while pursuing them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Business is booming for people smugglers who lead immigrants
around the blockades. Trips to Austin can cost $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mexican border cities say they are besieged by destitute
deportees who become squatters, overwhelming local services. Many
U.S. border residents say the blockades have brought relief from
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
