u a BC-TEEN-SMOKE29-COX     11-28 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-SMOKE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teens try to nix smoking trend, want more direct warning labels
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Langston Burgess thrusts Tic Tacs upon youngsters
who smoke. ``I hate the smell,'' he says. He wears T-shirts and
pins with anti-smoking messages. He tries to alarm the kids who do
smoke and inform the ones who don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make it a trend,'' said the 15-year-old Dunbar
sophomore, but it's an uphill battle. More than one-third of white
American teen-agers smoke, and while the rate for blacks is lower,
it has nearly doubled in the past two years to 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten a few people to quit,'' Langston said. It's hard
to reach young smokers, though. Sometimes, he said, ``We're like up
a creek without a paddle. It feels like there's nothing we can
really do. We're just trying to get the word out, trying to get the
percentages lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgess and others in the Teen Waves Wellness Coalition want to
hear more ideas about knocking down those percentages from 9:30
a.m. to noon Saturday at the Teen Tobacco Summit. The strategy
they've focused on is more effective warning labels on cigarette
packs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're basically meaningless,'' said Larry Black, a
13-year-old eighth-grader at Fairview Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't pay attention to them,'' said Brian Selman,
Black's classmate.
</P>
<P>
   The subject came up last spring when Dr. David Satcher, the U.S.
surgeon general, came to town to speak at the commencement for the
Wright State University School of Medicine, which sponsors the teen
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do cigarette packs have warning labels that many people
don't understand?'' Burgess asked him. Some labels raise the
specters of carbon monoxide and emphysema, for example, but most of
his friends don't know enough about either one to be afraid of
them. If teen-agers understood these dangers, he said, maybe they
wouldn't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the labels need to be improved and made clearer,''
Satcher told Langston, Larry and Brian in June. He said they should
think of some ideas and send them to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should say in very big letters: 'Smoke kills,'''
Langston said last week. ``'Hey, you! You smoke, you die.' We want
warning labels to be more blunt. We don't want people to think of
cigarettes like a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is concentrating especially on keeping nonsmokers
from starting, if only because that's more practical than trying to
talk nicotine addicts out of smoking. Mychal Edwards, a 16-year-old
member, thinks the best way is to make the consequences of smoking
more vividly clear.
</P>
<P>
   Let kids see an elderly smoker fighting for breath on his
respirator, Mychal said. Show them the fantastic high school
basketball player in his gym class whose only weakness is he can't
run up and down the court without going into coughing jags. Let
them hear from the smoker he waited on at McDonald's, whose voice
sounded more like croaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one reason I wouldn't mess with smoking,'' Mychal
said. ``You could lose your voice. You could lose everything. Your
whole body gets messed up. We need to show people how smoking hurts
you. We need to say, `You could actually end up like this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
