   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-STASI (Berlin) _ Files belonging to the old East German
secret police, the Stasi, continue to surface and make their mark
in a country where many people had served as informers during the
Cold War. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ISLAM (Dateline TK) _ Zamfara, a northern Nigerian
state, has begun imposing Islamic law, the greatest challenge yet
to the young democracy that is struggling to hold this diverse west
African country together. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RDP (Moscow) _ Russian tanks and infantry backed by
warplanes fought Sunday to cut off the last major supply route
between Grozny and the rest of rebel-controlled Chechnya, clashing
for hours with about 500 militants. (Summary from wires.) By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   TRADETALKS-PROTESTS (Seattle) _ In what is shaping up as one of
the biggest protest efforts in years, people from more than 500
organizations have poured into Seattle. They accuse the 134-nation
Geneva-based World Trade Organization, which is holding its
ministerial meeting here this week, of favoring free trade at the
expense of the environment, consumer safety, and workers' rights.
By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-BASQUES (Madrid) _ The Basque separatist movement, ETA,
says that it is calling off a 14-month-old cease-fire, setting off
a round of finger-pointing over why hopes for a peace accord with
Madrid has unravelled. Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PLO (Jerusalem) _ Several Palestinians who this past week
wrote an open letter protesting against the leadership of Yasser
Arafat have now been arrested. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   URUGUAY-VOTE (Montevideo, Uruguay) _ The country votes in a
final round of presidential elections. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-FREESPEECH (Winnipeg, Manitoba) _ Increasingly in Canada,
unpopular speech is illegal speech, and new laws aimed at stifling
remarks that could be construed as insensitive or offensive are
running up against others protecting freedom of expression. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE (Undated) _ Schools are expelling high school
students at a higher rate in the wake of Columbine and other school
violence. The level of tolerance has gone way down for student
misbehavior. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-CRUISESHIPS (Juneau, Alaska) _ The cruise ship industry,
once embraced as a savior for a lagging state economy, has worn out
its welcome here. Fed up with giant ships that discharge waste in
their pristine waterways and tourists who flood their downtown,
residents of Alaska's capital approved a $5 tax on every passenger
last month. The small town of Haines voted to limit the number of
cruise ships allowed at its dock. And several people have suggested
publicly that one cruise line be barred from the state's waters.
But in fighting to restrict the $12 billion cruise ship industry,
Alaskans also have a powerful opponent they may not have expected
-- their own representatives in the U.S. Congress. By Douglas
Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO-CROSS (Boise, Idaho) _ Issues about the constitutionality
of having a 60-foot cross on the skyline.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-VIRGINIA (Blacksburg, Va.) _ A look at college football
fever in the unlikely place of Blacksburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   COSMIC-EMPTINESS (Undated) _ Like the sorcerer's apprentice, who
could not banish the spirits that his spells had conjured up,
astronomers around the world have been trying -- with increasing
desperation -- to disprove the astonishing discovery, announced
early last year, that distant galaxies are being swept apart from
one another by a tide formed of apparently empty space. But almost
two years of effort to do so have yielded observational data that
only support the conclusion. Just last month, a subtle but
initially promising objection by one group of astronomers was shot
down by a new analysis of that data. The result, scientists are
reluctantly concluding, is that something in the theory of
elementary particle physics is terribly wrong. To explain the
observations, scientists say, they must answer a question that
sounds paradoxical: How much does emptiness weigh? By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY-SCHIZOPHRENIA (Undated) _ By the time most psychiatrists
encounter schizophrenia, the illness is already in full flower. But
scientists have long surmised that it starts much earlier, the
demons beginning to nibble at the edges of young people's lives
well before the most flagrant symptoms of psychosis appear. If
those at highest risk could only be identified early, mental health
researchers have believed, it might someday be possible to prevent
the disorder, or at least to mitigate its most devastating effects.
And researchers are now beginning, in a systematic way, to
investigate the earliest stages of schizophrenia, attempting to
find signs that could predict its onset. By Erica Goode.
</P>
