<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      11-28 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WARTS AND ALL,' THESE HILLBILLIES ARE PROUD OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're searching for a television heroine, look no further
than Iree Bowling.
</P>
<P>
   She has lived all but five months of her 68 years in dirt-poor
Mudlick Hollow, a valley in eastern Kentucky. But her presence _ to
say nothing of her pride _ rivets you to the screen in ``American
Hollow,'' the excellent HBO documentary produced and directed by
Rory Kennedy, in a way whippet-thin Hollywood actresses only wish
they could manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had hard times and we've had good times and we've had
sad times,'' Iree says in the film as she prepares to kill a couple
of chickens for dinner. ``It ain't been easy, but we survived.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Hollow'' follows the Bowling family for a year, a
year in which one family member will be arrested, one will be
dumped at the altar and one will divorce a husband who not only
routinely beat her but bragged about it.
</P>
<P>
   It's an invaluable look at a way of life unknown _
incomprehensible even _ to most Americans who when they hear the
word hillbilly conjure up images of Jed Clampett and Jethro Bodine.
The Bowlings are the genuine item, and they're not ashamed of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillbillies everyone thinks is stupid and ornery and no
good,'' Iree's son Lanzlo says. ``We are hillbillies and proud to
be hillbillies.''
</P>
<P>
   Real jobs are scarce, and every member of the family receives
some form of government assistance. But they also work, gathering
moss and roots to sell or doing odd jobs to supplement their
income.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been easy to make it around here,'' Neil, one of
Iree's sons, says as he scours the ground for bloodroot. ``I've
always thought it was if you weren't too sorry to get out and do
somethin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Iree wouldn't even slow down for the filmmakers. Kennedy talked
about her first time meeting the Bowlings' matriarch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was Iree putting out her laundry and making quilts and
out in the garden,'' Kennedy said from New York last week. ``She
was doing all the things that are really her life. She did them
while we were there. There was not a lot of sitting around talking
to us. If we were going to hang out, we were going to work with her
on her terms. It was pretty clear that she was a special person.''
</P>
<P>
   So many people talk about family values _ talk about them by
e-mail with their far-flung relatives, that is, when they're not
too busy slurping cafe latte in the latest trendy overgrown coffee
shop while their children endure forced ``play dates'' between FAO
Schwarz shopping sprees.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowlings ARE family values, with all the good and bad that
implies. Only one of Iree's 13 children has left the hollow. Others
have tried, but somehow always drift back. HOME and FAMILY aren't
just buzzwords to the Bowlings _ they are their only means of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that was striking about the family
was this family does live in poverty, and they face innumerable
challenges,'' Kennedy said. ``There's something about the Bowlings
where you can see this indomitable spirit that enables them to
overcome these difficulties. I think the film is not just a
portrait of need and want and poverty. It's also a celebration of
that spirit that we can all identify with on some level.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. But it's rarely a pretty picture. Clint, 17, argues,
often profanely, with his parents. Clint's fiancee talks about how
most of her friends are married by the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some girls have babies when they're 12 years old,'' she says
matter-of-factly. ``I do think that's kind of young to have a baby,
because you're still a baby when you're 12 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   When Edgar Bowling is arrested on a breaking and entering
charge, the family tries to pool together $5,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirt's dirt,'' Edgar's brother, Neil, says as he prepares to
put up his property deed for bail. ``Your brother's your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Iree, meanwhile, counts out $500 cash, explaining that she had
hoped to use the money to fix up part of her house and buy a VCR.
There is no trace of self-pity in her voice as she unfolds the
bills. She's simply doing what she can for her son.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough _ nothing the Bowlings can scrape together is
worth $5,000, so Edgar waits in jail 17 days until the charges are
dropped due to a case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's camera is everywhere _ with Iree's daughter Samantha
as she returns to look at the home where her husband beat her, at
the annual Labor Day family picnic, in Lanzlo's kitchen as he
worriedly awaits his monthly shipment of Prozac. ``Right now I'd
kill to get it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When Clint's fiancee breaks up with him, we're in the bedroom
with him, on the phone; her voice is heard as well. And when he
bolts the house, the camera follows, so that we see him shrieking
as he punches a hole in a wooden shed, the pain in his hand no
match for the pain in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the camera never intrudes. The Bowlings never seem to be
acting and often seem to forget they're being filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really didn't have any reason to play to the camera,''
Kennedy said. ``They are who they are and they're proud of who they
are and are ready to embrace their life, warts and all.''
</P>
<P>
   Clint wants to leave Mudlick Hollow, and you ache for him to do
so. He yearns for more, and it doesn't take a social scientist to
figure out that if he stays, he won't find it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``American Hollow'' also shines a light on some of the
happiness and pride inside the falling-down shacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I been fortunate to raise 13 children and live here and teach
them how to work and what to do,'' Iree says _ and you feel like
hugging her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm doing a good job.'' &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
