<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Nov. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brisk winds from the northwest will import noticeably colder air
into the Great Lakes and interior Northeast on Monday. Snow showers
will accompany a jet stream disturbance as it sweeps southeast
through the region, whitening the landscape from northern Ohio to
the New England mountains. As the chilly air is heated and
moistened upon crossing the Great Lakes, locally heavier snow
showers will form downwind of Lake Erie and Lake Ontario. Up to a
half foot of snow is possible in a few spots in northeast Ohio and
northwestern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest winds descending the Appalachian Mountains on Monday
will suppress clouds near the Northeast Seaboard. Amid abundant
sunshine, daytime readings will reach into the 40s in the afternoon
from Washington, D.C., to Boston. Much colder air will reach the
Northeast and Middle Atlantic coasts on Monday night and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Windswept rain will lash portions of the West Coast Monday as a
plume of Pacific moisture arrives ahead of an approaching cold
front. Rain will occur from north of Los Angeles to the Northwest
Coast. The rain will turn heavy for a time over northern California
as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather and ample sunshine will cover an expansive area from
southern California to lower Mississippi Valley as high pressure
near 20,000 feet remains across the region. Very strong winds from
the west will buffet the northern Rockies with gusts locally
exceeding 60 mph from the Front Range of Montana to eastern
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Damp Days
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since September 28, not a drop of rain fell
in Juneau, Alaska, on Saturday. The streak of 59 days with at least
a trace of rain fell short of the record of 68 damp days set in
1977. While the recent wetness has been notable, Juneau, which is
in the path of many storms that cross the Gulf of Alaska, typically
has rain on about 70 percent of the days at this time of year.
Persistent clouds during this wet spell have contributed to
unusually mild nights. Indeed, Saturday brought the first reading
below 28 degrees to Juneau this season, setting a new mark for the
latest hard freeze on record.
</P>
</TEXT>
