A3233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-420&AMP;ADD     11-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASQUE SEPARATISTS END CEASE-FIRE, WARN OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ The Basque separatist group ETA announced Sunday that
it would end a 14-month cease-fire. The rebels warned that armed
attacks could resume as early as Friday in their long struggle for
an independent homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire has been the longest period of calm in three
decades of separatist violence and had initially raised hopes that
both sides would use it as an opportunity to work out a lasting
peace for a conflict that authorities say has killed about 800
people.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to do so, said the rebel's statement, published
Sunday in the Basque newspaper Gara, lay with the governments of
Spain and France and also with moderate Basque nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish government disagreed. In response to the ETA
announcement, Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar accused the rebels of
intransigence and said that they were solely responsible for
breaking the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``ETA is wrong again if it thinks that with coercion, blackmail
or terror it will cause a breakdown in democracy and freedom,''
Aznar said in a six-minute statement that was nationally televised.
``ETA is wrong to think it can turn citizens into hostages and put
a price on peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The peace effort, which began on Sept. 16, 1998, when the rebels
announced an indefinite cease-fire, has been stalled for months.
There was only one round of talks between the government and the
rebels, on May 19 in Switzerland. In August the rebels said they
would not attend a second meeting, accusing the government of
seeking political gain from the truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is blocked and poisoned,'' ETA's statement said
Sunday. ``Responding to a pledge to defend the Basque country, the
decision has been taken to reactivate the use of armed struggle.
From December 3, it is up to ETA to inform its operational
commandos when to take action.''
</P>
<P>
   ETA, whose initials stand for the Basque words for Basque
Homeland and Liberty, has insisted on self-determination for 2.6
million people who live in Spain's four historic Basque provinces
and 250,000 others in the French part of the Basque region.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has said it was only willing to discuss
possible leniency for hundreds of Basque prisoners and exiles.
Madrid has also called for the rebels to permanently renounce
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has done, is doing and will do all it can to
achieve a lasting peace,'' Aznar said Sunday. National elections
are due to be held by April, and the peace process is likely to be
a backdrop to his campaign for a second term.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rebels' peace overture last year followed in the steps of
the Irish Republican Army, but while the peace process in Northern
Ireland has lurched forward, the effort here has deteriorated to
its lowest ebb.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish political leaders of all stripes expressed deep
disappointment Sunday at the end of the cease-fire, but they urged
Spaniards not to lose hope for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Six million people marched in the streets in July 1997 to demand
peace after the rebels kidnapped and killed a Basque town
councilman, Miguel Angel Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   That outpouring of public sentiment was seen as a turning point
in the fight against terrorism, along with the increasingly
efficient police crackdown against the rebels in Spain and in their
rear guard hideouts in France.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel supporters complained that even after the cease-fire took
effect, the police continued to arrest top ETA leaders, including
the detention last month of Belen Gonzalez Penalva, whom
authorities say represented the rebels at the peace talks last May.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the police said that they have detected rebel attempts
to prepare for new attacks, including the brazen theft of
industrial dynamite in France in September, although authorities
recovered some of the explosives soon after.
</P>
<P>
   But Xabier Arzalluz, the head of the moderate Basque Nationalist
Party, questioned whether ETA would actually ``carry through on its
threat'' to resume attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Arzalluz's party governs in the Basque regional parliament with
support from the Euskal Herritarrok _ or Basque Citizens _
coalition that is considered to be ETA's political wing. He blamed
both the rebels and the Spanish government for bungling the chance
to convert the cease-fire into a lasting peace, and he denied the
rebels' accusation that his moderate nationalists had not done
their part for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar, who survived a rebel car bomb attempt on his life in
1995, said that since the cease-fire had begun his government had
opened the door for many Basque separatists in exile to return to
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also released more than 130 rebel prisoners,
who were convicted or awaiting trial, and has transferred dozens
more to jails closer to their homes in the Basque region. But for
the rebels, these moves were apparently not enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
