<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SHOPPING-ONLINE-1050(     11-28 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-ONLINE-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE RETAILERS HAVE VISIONS OF HOLIDAY SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many Internet retailers, success this holiday shopping
season rests on the shoulders of the customer service team or the
technical support staff _ whose job it is to keep a Web site from
crashing. But for executives of Bluefly.com, a discount apparel
merchant, success rides on the back of a Himalayan mountain goat _
the source of Pashmina.
</P>
<P>
   Pashmina has turned out to be the season's must-have fabric _ a
cashmere blended with silk to produce shawls and scarves of great
warmth, and even greater cachet. Bluefly executives had decided to
build the site's holiday promotions around their Pashmina items,
but they hit a slight snag when, two weeks ago, they sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's walking around asking when the Pashmina's coming in
because everything's on hold until then,'' said Jonathan Morris,
Bluefly's executive vice president. ``It's like the Furby of the
fashion world.''
</P>
<P>
   Such glitches are but one version of the nightmares before
Christmas that may be haunting many an e-commerce executive the
next month. Some Internet retailers, including Toys ``R'' Us, have
already had problems on their sites, while others are struggling to
fill open seams in their order processing and customer service
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But ready or not, the e-tailing rush is under way. Internet
shopping surveys indicate that online holiday spending started in
earnest the 10 days before Thanksgiving. Forecasts call for more
than 20 million holiday shoppers to click up $6 billion or more in
purchases, or triple last year's holiday total. And while retailers
focus on this year's action, they know that any breakdowns will
jeopardize next year's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, some Web sites were already straining to keep up
with demand. KBkids.com, a partnership of KB Toys and BrainPlay.com
turned away some shoppers because it was overloaded for parts of
the day. And both eToys and Amazon.com said they were already out
of some Pokemon toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between Christmas '98 and '99 online is that
last year, there were simple failures, like sites not working
properly, that consumers were relatively OK with because everyone
had the same problems,'' said Ford Cavallari, executive vice
president of Renaissance Worldwide, a strategy consulting firm.
``This year consumers expect more, and a lot of sites won't be able
to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   While nearly every e-commerce executive interviewed acknowledges
losing sleep over holiday-shopping jitters, the ones with the worst
insomnia are probably the retailers who are entering their first
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that pops me out of bed in a bad dream is a
major critical system failure where the site goes boom,'' said
Michael Clebnik, chief executive of BuyItOnline.com, a new online
mall. ``I think that's true for any company that's going through
its growth stages like us, where we're not in a financial position
to spend tens of millions to say `Here, buy as many servers as you
need so we can scale to the size of Yahoo.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clebnik, who began operations in May, said he planned to add
servers _ the workhorse computers that support the site _ in
sufficient numbers to ensure a 50 percent buffer between peak
traffic and total system capacity. He has also set up a backup
database for customer order and billing information, in case the
first database fizzles. ``We have to do it,'' he said. ``Any loss
of confidence in our system is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for more experienced e-commerce sites, like Garden.com,
this is a worry. Garden.com, a purveyor of cut flowers and
gardening supplies, has three holiday seasons under its belt. But
this year the company has added more sophisticated features to its
site _ like the ability to recognize each returning customer and
display a personalized page.
</P>
<P>
   ``So not only is our traffic going up, but what customers do
while they're on the site is hitting our database more,'' said
Cliff Sharples, Garden.com's chief executive, adding that the
company spent between $2 million and $3 million in August for a
systems upgrade to handle the increased usage.
</P>
<P>
   John Hnanicek, chief information officer of eToys, said his
company spent ``in the seven figures'' last month on a system that
gauges the site's performance every 20 seconds, and alerts
executives to any performance lags. ``It lets me sleep well because
I know I'll get a phone call if there's anything to worry about,''
he said. So far, at least, there have been no nocturnal calls.
</P>
<P>
   More pressing for Hnanicek and others, perhaps, is the issue of
so-called fulfillment _ actually processing and shipping what the
customer has ordered. According to Jupiter Communications, the top
Internet retailers can each expect to process 58,000 orders each
day, and they will have to impress upon warehouse workers the
urgency of picking, packing and shipping as if the entire business
were at stake. Instilling that sense of mission can be difficult,
however, when those workers are third-party vendors, as is so often
the case with e-commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the fun things about eToys,'' said Hnanicek, who
spoke from Fingerhut's Provo, Utah, warehouse, which handles a
large percentage of eToys' shipments. ``When we talk to the staff
here, we can ascribe a little higher meaning to the stuff we sell,
because they're bringing Christmas to kids. It's not like we're
selling auto parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, of Bluefly, which is based in New York, said his site's
fulfillment and marketing anxieties should subside within a week,
when a shipment of several thousand Pashmina scarves and shawls is
expected to arrive at the Chicago company, Marketing Out of the
Box, that handles Bluefly's fulfillment. Beyond that, he said he is
most concerned about preparing the customer service staff _
``especially in the early in the season, because there's a chance
for repeat purchase and good word-of-mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Bluefly's 10 full-time and three part-time customer
service representatives will be bolstered by employees from other
departments to cover the expected 400 daily inquiries by telephone
and e-mail during the holiday rush. ``Don't be surprised if you
call customer service and I pick up the phone,'' Morris said. ``I'm
not sure you want that, but it may happen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Within the realms of fulfillment, customer service and site
performance, there is an almost endless list of places where a site
can fail, said Cavallari, of Renaissance Worldwide. He cited at
least a dozen areas of vulnerability, including the failure of
systems to allow an order to be modified once it has been placed.
Another shortcoming is the inability of many sites to recognize
when a customer has typed a zip code that either does not exist or
does not correspond to the shipping address.
</P>
<P>
   Most alarming, perhaps, is the fact that in the age of
``fully-integrated, end-to-end software solutions,'' some sites are
still typing in customer orders by hand. ``You'd be surprised at
how many sites are rekeying data,'' said Cavallari. ``At least half
of all commerce sites are duct-taped and glued in a similar
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   While new e-commerce companies can expect to suffer from rookie
mistakes, traditional retailers are not invulnerable. ``A lot of
older retailers with 10-year-old warehouse database systems are
trying to link their Web pages to them, and they're using the duct
tape and glue approach,'' Cavallari said. Given that approach and
the difficulty of keeping up with every aspect of critical systems,
he said, ``It's scary when you think about all the places where a
site can break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Billings, chief executive of RedEnvelope.com, an online
gift retailer founded in 1997 and formerly known as 911Gifts.com,
said to gird against any last-minute failures the company recently
simulated a peak traffic day. She declined to provide specifics,
other than to say that the test went well. ``Now we just have to do
it when the real peak day comes,'' she said. Ms. Billings expects
that day to be Monday, Dec. 20, as last-minute shoppers try to beat
the express-delivery deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   To handle the strain, Ms. Billings said the company had sought
to inject as much flexibility into its systems as possible. ``We
can get more fulfillment space, more customer service reps, and
more inventory if we need to,'' she said, noting that the site can
serve 10 times the number of visitors it served last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, this is the scariest holiday season I've ever faced in
my history as a retailer,'' said Ms. Billings, who previously
worked seven years for Pottery Barn's catalog and retail operation.
``There are just so many unknowns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GIFT-BOOKS-REVIEW-2TA     11-28 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFT-BOOKS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFTS FOR CELEBRATING THE CENTURY OR JUST RELAXING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, they finally did it. The publisher Benedikt Taschen has
issued a book called ``Sumo,'' a collection of photographs by
Helmut Newton, edited by his wife, June Newton. Which may sound
innocent enough. But here's the thing: It's 465 pages long,
measures 20 by 28 by 4 inches, weighs 66 pounds and comes with its
own chromed stainless-steel folding table designed by Philippe
Starck. So the dream of Seinfeld's Kramer of a coffee-table book
that is actually a coffee table has been all but realized.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Sumo'' bears a price tag of $1,500, a review copy was
understandably not sent to this office. I therefore can't recommend
it as a gift this season. But the following books, arranged by
ascending price, will do very well in its place.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET COOL GUIDE, edited by Rula Razek. Designed by Tika
Buchanan and James Tung of Eric Baker Design Associates, N.Y. (187
pages. Te Neues Publishing Co. Paperback, $14.95.) OK, so this
guide to the 1,000 best Web sites will probably be obsolete by the
day after tomorrow. But in the meantime there's lots of useful
advice here on search engines and how to use them for everything
from buying a car online to playing chess against Gary Kasparov.
And you can get updates on www.internetcoolguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   HOME COMFORTS: The Art and Science of Keeping House, by Cheryl
Mendelson. Illustrations by Harry Bates. (884 pages. Scribner.
$35.) A guide to all the domestic arts _ from choosing fabrics to
folding sheets to mending book bindings to throwing out old
documents _ by an articulate, witty woman who is a philosopher,
lawyer, sometime professor and a homemaker, wife and mother all
rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   SAVEUR COOKS AUTHENTIC FRENCH, by the editors of Saveur
Magazine. Designed by Jill Armus, Michael Grossman and Amy
Henderson. (320 pages. Chronicle Books. $40.) This sequel to last
year's ``Saveur Cooks Authentic American'' explores the traditions
of French cuisine _ particularly those of Burgundy, Alsace, the
Southwest, Provence and a few others _ and is packed with
illustrations that look good enough to ... well, send you out
looking for truffles, duck's liver and frog's legs.
</P>
<P>
   FULL MOON, by Michael Light. Essay by Andrew Chaikin. (Unpaged.
Alfred A. Knopf. $50.) In case you haven't gone there yet, these
magnificent two-page (and occasionally four-page) spreads, newly
released by NASA, capture the visual sensation of landing on,
walking around and taking off from the mysteriously beautiful
landscape of the Moon. Published on the 30th anniversary of Apollo
II, the first moon voyage, it answers some of the questions posed
by Les Paul and Mary Ford in the song ``How High the Moon?''
</P>
<P>
   Looking in another direction, namely back over the last hundred
years, the following four volumes view the 20th century from
multiple perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The first _ CENTURY: One Hundred Years of Human Progress,
Regression, Suffering and Hope, conceived and edited by Bruce
Bernard (1,120 pages; Phaidon Press; $49.95) _ is a history told in
more than 1,100 photographs, many familiar, some never before
published. The juxtapositions are often shocking _ President
Kennedy at a street party in Ireland across from the moment of the
second Oswald shot _ and remind you that these truly have been the
best and worst of times.
</P>
<P>
   The next two _ THE AMERICAN CENTURY: Art and Culture 1900-1950;
by Barbara Haskell (408 pages; $60) and THE AMERICAN CENTURY: Art
and Culture 1950-2000, by Lisa Phillips (398 pages; $60; both
published by the Whitney Museum of American Art, New York, in
association with W.W. Norton) _ offer rich records of the recent
shows at the Whitney, considering American art as a response to
political, social and economics conditions, and tracing its
expression in painting, sculpture, photography, architecture, film,
literature, dance, theater, music and the decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, THE LOOK OF THE CENTURY, by Michael Tambini (288
pages; DK Publishing; $39.95), a striking visual record of how
changes in taste have been reflected in everything from furniture
to cereal boxes, from Coca-Cola bottles to the Porsche 911.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As always, the Bronx is up and the Battery's down in NEW YORK:
An Illustrated History; narrative by Ric Burns and James Sanders;
picture editor, Lisa Ades (575 pages; Alfred A. Knopf; $60) and NEW
YORK 1880: Architecture and Urbanism in the Gilded Age, by Robert
A.M. Stern, Thomas Mellins and David Fishman (1,164 pages;
Monacelli Press; $85). But the first, a companion to the PBS
television series, also shows the city from its beginnings to the
present, while the second concentrates on a period of great
technological change that transformed the city from a harbor town
to a world-class metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN. Photographs by Annie Leibovitz. Essay by Susan Sontag.
(239 pages. Random House. $75.) The haunting images in this
mesmerizing book show women in such astonishing variety that no
cliche or generalization about the sex will ever again suffice.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two volumes filled with waters so beautiful that one
finds it hard to understand how anyone could resist the sport of
fishing. The first, TROUT AND SALMON. Photography by R. Valentine
Atkinson (176 pages; Lyons Press; $39.95), sends you all over the
world: to Ireland, Chile, Norway and Russia, among other places
ridden with magnificent fish. The second, LAND OF LITTLE RIVERS: A
Story in Photos of Catskill Fly Fishing, by Austin McK. Francis;
photography by Enrico Ferorelli (279 pages; Beaverkill Press;
distributed by W.W. Norton. $100), zeroes in on the birthplace of
American fly fishing and shows you not only fish and waters but
also the people and equipment that helped to develop a great sport.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN CEREMONIES, by Carol Beckwith and Angela Fisher. (Two
volumes slip-cased: Vol. 1, 384 pages; Vol. 2, 360 pages. Harry N.
Abrams, $150.) A monumental survey in pictures and text of tribal
rituals, rites and ceremonies across the entire continent, spanning
the human life cycle, birth, puberty, courtship and marriage,
illness and death. Arresting views, often forbidden to outsiders,
into the heart of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST OF FLAIR. Edited by Fleur Cowles. Foreword by Dominick
Dunne. (337 pages. Rizzoli International Publications. Boxed,
$250.) Remember Flair magazine (which ran for 12 months, February
1950 to January 1951), with its elegant design and its accordion
foldouts once celebrated in a New Yorker cartoon showing a reader
with an extra arm and hand, and its reputation for being either too
lavish or too far ahead of its time? You don't? Well, here's the
best of it, with prose by Winston Churchill, George Bernard Shaw
and Tallulah Bankhead, among others, and with lots of pages to keep
your two hands busy. In a bright red folding box that will look
great on the coffee table even if you never crack it open.
</P>
<P>
   And a happy holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
