<P>
   GERMANY-STASI (Berlin) _ Files belonging to the old East German
secret police, the Stasi, continue to surface and make their mark
in a country where many people had served as informers during the
Cold War. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   URUGUAY-VOTE (Montevideo, Uruguay) _ The country votes in a
final round of presidential elections. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-CRUISESHIPS (Juneau, Alaska) _ The cruise ship industry,
once embraced as a savior for a lagging state economy, has worn out
its welcome here. Fed up with giant ships that discharge waste in
their pristine waterways and tourists who flood their downtown,
residents of Alaska's capital approved a $5 tax on every passenger
last month. The small town of Haines voted to limit the number of
cruise ships allowed at its dock. And several people have suggested
publicly that one cruise line be barred from the state's waters.
But in fighting to restrict the $12 billion cruise ship industry,
Alaskans also have a powerful opponent they may not have expected
-- their own representatives in the U.S. Congress. By Douglas
Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-MOMS (Ft. Lewis, Wash.) _ In the small world of senior
women officers, Lois Beard was considered a prime candidate for
General Mom. She was a veteran of the invasion of Panama and the
war in the Persian Gulf. She commanded a military police unit that
helped keep the peace in Bosnia. The Army promoted her to colonel
two years ahead of schedule. But just as the odds were great that
she would be chosen for a star, Colonel Beard called it quits. At
the age of 45, after holding every job and attending every school
required to be selected as general, she decided she could no longer
dismiss the pull of her family.
</P>
