<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-PROFILE-ART-     11-28 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-PROFILE-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN TRYING TO RAID `GERMANY INC.' IS DRIVEN AND UNFLAPPABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Germany)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ To a backdrop of glittery chandeliers and somber marble
pillars in a financial-district conference room, Christopher Gent,
the smooth-talking chief executive of the world's biggest mobile
phone company, was outlining his designs on German rival Mannesmann
the other day when, unusually, he seemed to stumble over a word.
</P>
<P>
   Gent, the chief executive of Vodafone AirTouch, was discussing
the web of deals that girds the globe's wireless networks, and he
was talking about companies already under his control. What
emerged, though, was not ``companies'' but ``countries'' _ as if,
in this era of corporate hubris and consolidation, boardrooms have
supplanted nations in creating the empires that will rule the
digital millennium.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem to be a lot of freight to load onto a simple slip
of the tongue, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But, considering that Gent (pronounced JENT) was discussing
global expansion and control, an observer might be forgiven for
sensing imperial overtones. As in the lands that Britain still
ruled when he was born 51 years ago, the sun never sets either on
Gent's realm of wireless networks from the United States to
Australia, or on his ambition to expand his empire.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, with dizzying speed, Gent has moved from the
$60 billion acquisition of AirTouch last January, through a summer
dominated by negotiating a joint venture with Bell Atlantic _ which
he outbid to secure AirTouch _ to create the biggest wireless
network in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, spurred by Mannesmann's own imperialistic effort to acquire
Britain's No. 3 wireless operator, Orange PLC, Gent has moved on to
history's largest takeover bid: a roughly $127 billion all-stock
mammoth of a hostile move on Mannesmann. Success by Vodafone would
give the combined companies stakes or control in 25 countries with
full or partial access to the mobile phone use of 73 million people
_ including the biggest cellular markets in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday evening, Mannesmann's supervisory board _ the equivalent
of a board of directors _ met in Duesseldorf, Germany, and, as
expected, voted to reject Vodafone's takeover offer. German news
reports indicated that several board members had wanted the company
to consider negotiations, but Mannesmann's chairman, Klaus Esser,
adamantly ruled that out.
</P>
<P>
   Gent declined to be interviewed. But in his recent
conference-room remarks he said that if the hostile bid succeeded,
``we will operate the largest wireless networks in the world This
combination puts us in pole position for the wireless data and
Internet future.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but a combination with Mannesmann would position
Vodafone to challenge oil giant BP Amoco as Britain's largest
company, with a market value of more than $250 billion _ quite a
rise for a company that began life less than a decade ago as a
fledgling contender in the untested mobile phone market. And most
of that expansion has come in the brief two years and 11 months
since Gent took over as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the man behind the imperial vision somehow remains elusive,
showing a regard for personal privacy as steely as the
determination of his deal making. The Vodafone official biography
of Gent simply skips from his appointment in 1985 as an executive
of Racal Electronics _ the parent of Vodafone before it was spun
off in 1988 _ to his becoming chief executive of Vodafone in 1997.
Initially, he secured the company's dominance in Britain's
rough-and-tumble mobile phone business before venturing into
megamergers. ``He put his own back yard in order before some of the
bigger deals,'' an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The official biography makes no allusion to his family or social
life, beyond his love of tennis and cricket. Publicly, at least,
Gent offers a seamless image of unflappability: Even barbed
questions comparing radiation from mobile phones to smoke from
cigarettes as a health hazard fail to ignite a spark of anger or
defensiveness and are rebuffed with well-rehearsed
counterarguments. Newspaper articles note that he drives an Aston
Martin sports car, but associates say playboy connotations or a
quest for ego-tripping celebrity are wide of the mark for a man
with a young son from a second marriage that he wishes to shield
from publicity's glare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does have a car like that, but I suspect it gathers dust in
the garage,'' said a business associate who spoke in return for
anonymity. ``It's not like he's driving it around all the time. He
works too hard. He's not a mega-ego kind of guy. He has a lot of
confidence, but he doesn't feel the need to show off.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does drive him? Of course, it could just be money,
although that does not seem to be the entire story. In a recent
ranking compiled by The Sunday Times of London, Gent emerged as
only Britain's seventh-best-paid chief executive with a basic
salary of $1.07 million, multiplied eightfold by stock incentives
and bonuses to $8.57 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his recent stock option disposals, his aides say, were
related to paying for his divorce from his first wife. He remarried
earlier this year and lives with his second wife, Kate, in a large
house on about two acres in the Lambourne Valley _ horse-rearing
country close to Vodafone's rambling corporate headquarters,
according to Mike Caldwell, Vodafone's head of corporate
communications. It is a token of Vodafone's helter-skelter growth
that the headquarters occupies a staggering 58 separate buildings
at Newbury, west of London.
</P>
<P>
   In class-ridden Britain, achievement is gauged not only in
pounds and pence, but in the ability to crash the barriers that _
certainly in Gent's formative years _ would have divided the upper
crust from the rest. ``His father died when he was quite young. He
didn't go to college and he's very driven to achieve a high
level,'' the business associate said. ``In Britain, people often
find it very difficult not being from a particular background. He's
cut through all that.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, that makes Gent rather similar to an old friend of
his, former Prime Minister John Major. Both left school to go to
work in their teens _ Gent as a trainee bank manager, Major as a
clerk at an insurance brokerage. Both sought a political niche in
the Young Conservatives, of which Gent was national chairman from
1977 to 1979. Both, too, project the manner of a new, meritocratic
elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beautiful white collars and striped shirts, the tailoring
_ he does have a slightly patrician air,'' said a financial analyst
who has observed Gent's presentations and who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Major, Gent deploys what is most kindly described as a
dry, even acerbic, wit. Asked at a recent news conference what
mechanism he would use to put his merger proposals to Mannesmann's
supervisory board, he snapped back, ``It's known as a letter.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Gent has said he believed that revenue from
voice, data and Internet uses was the key to unlocking profit from
technological advances that are supposed to give wireless devices
much greater speed and capacity. ``We believe that the future of
telecommunications is wireless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is only one belief that has put him at loggerheads with
Mannesmann, which aims to build its empire on a combination of
fixed-line and wireless technology. Protesting Mannesmann workers
last week publicly compared Gent's appetites for expansion to those
of a shark. Indeed, in plunging into the cosseted world of German
labor relations, he may well have underestimated the likely
resistance of Mannesmann's 130,000 workers to what protesters
called ``the wild predator'' from a company called ``Voodoofone.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that, in launching his bid, Gent has shown
himself willing to do battle across one of the great divides of
corporate Europe. It is an effort that calls not just for business
acumen but also for the diplomatic skills to persuade German
politicians, industrialists and workers to countenance the first
ever cross-border raid on Germany Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the German image of Gent as a predator, though, he has
been more reactive than active as an aggressor. In both big merger
battles this year, Gent was initially caught off balance. News that
Bell Atlantic was competing for AirTouch came through last January
when he was away in Australia watching a match by his beloved
English cricket team, which Vodafone sponsors. And, last month, he
was at dinner when word reached him that Mannesmann was close to a
deal with Orange _ a move that would turn Mannesmann from being
Vodafone's most important European partner into a direct competitor
on its British home turf and a challenger for European domination.
</P>
<P>
   So how did he react?
</P>
<P>
   ``Furious would be too strong a statement,'' said Vodafone's
Mike Caldwell. ``Nonplused would be more like it because he thought
we were in the friendly camp with Mannesmann.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when Gent resolved to make his hostile bid, ``most people
accept that as far as he's concerned it was a very difficult
decision to make,'' said Nigel Hawkins, a telecommunications
analyst with Williams de Broe brokerage. ``He didn't choose the
battleground or the timing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
