<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COVENT-GARDEN-ART-119     11-28 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVENT-GARDEN-ART-1195(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX RISES AT COVENT GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It makes for a dull ending to a long-running soap opera
that once entertained with spats, insults, scandals, brinkmanship
and frequent warnings of imminent disaster. But after four years of
unremitting melodrama, the Royal Opera House at Covent Garden has
completed a $360 million redevelopment and will reopen on schedule
on Dec. 1 with a gala of song and dance attended by Queen
Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   So all's well that ends well? Perhaps. The new opera house
should make life decidedly more pleasant for performers and
audiences: It includes a new studio theater, additional rehearsal
and dressing rooms, an expanded back stage and a large public foyer
to replace the aptly named Crush Bar. The auditorium, the only part
of the 19th-century theater that was not torn down and rebuilt
during the 30-month makeover, has even been given air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   After the likes of Placido Domingo and Sylvie Guillem reprise
the opening gala on Dec. 4, Covent Garden can at last return to its
proper business of presenting its divertissements on stage. The new
season begins Dec. 6 with six performances of a new production of
Verdi's ``Falstaff,'' with Bryn Terfel in the lead role, and five
evenings of international choreography, including a world premiere
by Siobhan Davies, presented by the Royal Ballet on Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the Royal Opera and the Royal Ballet can now boast a
home fit for the 21st century, the price has been high, and not
simply in monetary terms. By seeking a $125 million grant from
National Lottery profits to add to its annual subsidy from the
government, the opera house invited scrutiny by press, Parliament
and public. The resulting verdict was ferocious: that Covent Garden
was overstaffed, badly managed and elitist.
</P>
<P>
   Once the spotlight was on the house, worse followed. With London
tabloids gleefully reporting every twist and turn, two directors
came and went; senior staff members were fired; the director of
opera, Nicholas Payne, found a new job; the music director, Bernard
Haitink, resigned; and the government forced most board members to
step down.
</P>
<P>
   As the house's deficit mounted, opera and ballet shows planned
in other theaters during the closing were cut to a minimum. ``If
you asked people who hated the arts why they were so hostile, they
would reply, `Look at Covent Garden,''' the arts critic Richard
Morrison recalled recently in The Times of London. ``And if you
asked arts lovers why they were so gloomy, they would say exactly
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then last fall, with construction on the new theater advancing
steadily despite the turmoil, the new board chairman, Sir Colin
Southgate, chairman of EMI Records, took a gamble: He asked an
American, Michael Kaiser, executive director of the American Ballet
Theater at the time, to take over management of the Royal Opera
House. One year later Kaiser, a 46-year-old New Yorker, has lived
up to his reputation for turning troubled arts organizations
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what has been achieved,'' he said in an interview
in his office in one of the new buildings now attached to the old
opera house. ``There was this mantra that the Royal Opera House has
good art and bad staff. It's not true. We have a superlative staff,
and they're putting the new building to work without a hiccup.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived last November, though, the battered morale of
Covent Garden's orchestra, chorus, dancers and staff was his first
problem. Unlike his immediate predecessors, however, he did not set
out to find scapegoats for the mess. Rather he focused attention on
the future and, reassuringly, Haitink rescinded his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser then restored some canceled productions outside the house
in 1999 and spent time getting to know dancers and musicians. Above
all he gave the impression of knowing what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   On crucial money matters he soon demonstrated that he did know.
Coincidentally, as he was taking over, the Arts Council of England,
which funnels government money into the arts, reluctantly raised
its annual grant by $3 million to $32 million for 1999 and promised
an additional $6.4 million for 2000 and 2001. He nonetheless
inherited a $32 million deficit that thanks to staff cuts and fund
raising he now says will be eliminated by next March.
</P>
<P>
   Further, with $42 million in fresh private and corporate
donations in the last year, the house can now cover its $162
million share of the cost of the new building. (A further $73
million is assured by long-term rental of commercial street-front
space on a plaza behind the opera house.)
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser has also increased the number of Friends of Covent Garden
to 19,000 from 15,000, while, with an eye to the future, he has
instituted an Endowment Fund, with the target of raising $48
million within two years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Royal Opera House is not yet home free. British
newspapers have credited Kaiser with restoring some dignity to
Covent Garden, but memories of the fiasco of recent years continue
to feed skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the raw facts about Covent Garden are now well known:
that large amounts of public money _ whether lottery profits or tax
income _ benefit a small number of privileged opera and ballet
lovers, but that without that money Covent Garden would close.
</P>
<P>
   Put differently, while in the United States private donors
sustain major opera houses the way government subsidies do in
continental Europe, the Royal Opera House has floated uncomfortably
between these two models: It receives both public and private
funds, but it has had to charge high prices for most of its 2,300
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Labor government, which took office in the middle of
Covent Garden's crisis, demanded that the ``new'' house lower its
prices. The house management replied: Fine, if the government picks
up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Now some sort of compromise appears to have been worked out. The
government has raised its subsidy, and Kaiser has lowered the top
seat price for ``premium'' operas to $240 from $370. For many other
operas and ballets the top price will be $162. ``For a `standard'
opera,'' he said, ``more than half the seats will be less than $65
and more than half the seats for ballet will be less than $40.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of who gets these seats has not gone away. Along
with major donors the 19,000 Friends of Covent Garden, who pay $90
annually, can buy tickets earlier than the public, which prompted
one tabloid to shout, ``Rich grab 80 percent of Royal Opera
seats.'' But Kaiser said that this was already an improvement on
the past, when on occasion all but a handful of tickets were sold
before the box office opened.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the new house is developing other ways of wooing
public opinion. The building will be open much of the day to
visitors, with free concerts organized in the Vilar Floral Hall,
the new foyer that now carries the name of Alberto Vilar, the
American philanthropist who donated $16 million to Covent Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Additional concerts and performances by outside companies will
be held in the 420-seat Linbury Studio Theater, while the public
will be invited to watch some Royal Ballet rehearsals in the new
Clore Studio Upstairs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inevitably, given all the new backstage machinery, some
teething problems have occurred, aggravated by Covent Garden's
decision to squeeze six different productions into the new house's
first six weeks. As a result 10 days before the reopening, six
performances of Ligeti's opera ``Le Grand Macabre,'' were canceled
to release stage time to rehearse the other productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's brilliant, but he doesn't actually walk on water,''
Amanda Jones, Covent Garden's press chief, explained.
</P>
<P>
   The true rebuilding of the Royal Opera House, however, will be
gauged by the quality of the productions in its main auditorium.
``In the end I won't feel it is a success if the art is not strong
and the balance sheet is good,'' Kaiser said. And here, after the
uncertainty of recent years, much work has still to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Ballet, which suffered serious desertions during the
closure, is at least now installed in Covent Garden for the first
time; until now, its dancers had to commute across London between
their rehearsal studios and their performance stage. They also now
have what Kaiser calls ``the most beautiful ballet studios in the
world.'' But their transition may not end until a successor is
found to the ballet director, Sir Anthony Dowell, who retires in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   On the opera side Anthony Pappano has been chosen to succeed
Haitink as music director in 2002. And unlike Haitink, Pappano, a
London-born American conductor who is currently at the Theatre de
la Monnaie in Brussels, Belgium, will play an active role as
artistic director as well as permanent conductor; he reportedly
plans to spend seven months of every year in London.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that Covent Garden is starting afresh comes through
all too clearly in its 1999-2000 opera season. Only ``Falstaff'' is
a new production; Harrison Birtwistle's ``Gawain,'' Wagner's
``Fliegende Hollaender'' and ``Meistersinger,'' Strauss'
``Rosenkavalier'' and Puccini's ``Boheme'' are revivals of Covent
Garden productions; and Mozart's ``Clemenza di Tito,'' Rossini's
``Otello,'' Gounod's ``Romeo et Juliette'' and Bohuslav Martinu's
``Greek Passion'' are co-productions that have already been
presented elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the optimist, though, Kaiser sees a silver lining even in
this lineup. ``We will shatter the elitist image by getting people
into the house at reasonable prices,'' he said. ``But if you look
at what we're offering this season, no one can say that we're
dumbing down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
