<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPERS CRITICIZE CIRCULATION AUDITOR  
 LESS ENTHUSIASM FOR NETWORKS' MUSIC PROJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop quiz on the ABCs of the Audit Bureau of Circulations. Which
of the following counts as paid circulation, by the bureau's rules?
</P>
<P>
   (a) A copy of The Wall Street Journal, delivered to college
dormitory rooms and paid for in bulk by the college.
</P>
<P>
   (b) A home-delivered copy of The Rocky Mountain News, costing a
penny.
</P>
<P>
   (c) A copy of USA Today delivered to a hotel-room guest who did
not ask for it but did not tell the front desk not to deliver or
charge for it.
</P>
<P>
   (d) A copy of any local newspaper paid for in the ticket price
of participants in a convention.
</P>
<P>
   (e) The New York Times bought for the full price of 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Trick question: ``b,'' ``c,'' ``d'' and ``e'' count, and ``a''
does sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Make sense? Not to a rump caucus of dissatisfied publishers. In
an era of eroding newspaper circulation, they see the audit
bureau's rules as capricious and the results irrational. This, in
turn, is straining the alliance of newspaper executives and
advertisers that governs ABC, which has been the final arbiter of
circulation claims for 85 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, (paid circulation 1,753,000) was just
overtaken by USA Today (paid circulation 1,758,000). Dow Jones
executives, long irritated by the Gannett flagship's ability to
count hotel circulation, months ago started putting out a statement
of total circulation that reflects the ABC-approved figures and
adds bulk sales that may not count as paid circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times and one of its competitors, The Orange
County Register, are upset that some discount plans, like Denver's,
count, while theirs may not. This month they have raised the ante
by finding an auditor, PricewaterhouseCoopers, to prepare a
circulation report in addition to the one they provide for the
audit bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still members of ABC,'' said Ronald Redfern, the
president and chief operating officer of The Register. But he
added, ``We are growing weary of dealing with the ABC and these
onerous rules. Standard measurements for everyone are important.''
So is ``gaining more readers for our advertisers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at other newspapers are watching the two newspapers
bid for independent review with interest and concern. The concern
is that circulation claims will no longer be comparable or
credible, and advertisers who have plenty of other media to choose
from may bolt rather than try to sort out truth from hype.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lavery, the president and managing director of the audit
bureau, said ``ABC's standards are such that they do provide
comparability in reporting.'' He added, ``This all goes back to
satisfying advertisers' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Less Enthusiasm for Networks' Music Projects
</P>
<P>
   It was only a year ago that network movie executives were
speaking optimistically about commissioning music-based television
miniseries to cash in on the sales of related compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest television event last November, an NBC miniseries on
the Temptations, helped create momentum for the music-based idea by
generating big ratings and big sales for a CD, sold through an
``800'' telephone number. The momentum increased in February when a
second NBC music-oriented movie, ``The '60s,'' was such a hit that
its CD became the best-selling movie soundtrack on the Billboard
chart.
</P>
<P>
   That enthusiasm is starting to cool, at least at one network,
largely because the most ambitious music project this fall was
undone by ABC's rampaging _ and inexpensive _ ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' game show.
</P>
<P>
   The victim: a two-part CBS movie called ``Shake, Rattle and
Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   A fictionalized journey through the early rock 'n' roll years,
``Shake, Rattle and Roll'' included a list of ambitious songs, some
original (including songs by Bob Dylan, Lamont Dozier and Graham
Nash) and some covers of '50s hits by contemporary artists. CBS
promoted the film heavily and scheduled it on the first Sunday in
November.
</P>
<P>
   But that night Millionaire pushed ``Shake, Rattle and Roll'' to
a poor first-hour rating, and the show never recovered. Sales of
the CD have been similarly disappointing, though CBS declined to
cite specific figures. NBC itself helped undercut the CBS effort by
putting on its own rock 'n' roll movie, a biography of the disc
jockey Alan Freed, just a week earlier. Though its ratings were
less than stellar, the NBC movie may have helped sate viewers.
</P>
<P>
   One network did have a musical hit this November: ABC, in the
remake of ``Annie.'' But ABC did not make an effort to sell CDs of
the show through an ``800'' number, though it is selling the film
on video. ABC is planning more adaptations of big Broadway
musicals, with ``Mame'' and ``Music Man'' both in the works.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, meanwhile, still has ``The '70s'' from the same producers
as ``The '60s,'' ready for May. And it may commission a film on the
'50s rocker Little Richard.
</P>
<P>
   The network does plan to keep trying to sell CDs connected with
these projects. But the most ambitious talk of a regular
second-revenue stream has diminished.
</P>
<P>
   As for CBS, it has no music-based movie projects on its current
development slate, a network executive said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
