<HEADER>
A3259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CYNTHIA-NIXON-PROFILE     11-28 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYNTHIA-NIXON-PROFILE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE A DASH OF HBO FAME, THE LURE IS STILL THE STAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cynthia Nixon is only 33, but she has been called a
perennial of the New York theater. It's all right with her, she
says, especially the New York part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that at my funeral I want them to play Judy
Garland singing `I Happen to Like New York,''' Ms. Nixon said over
lunch at an Upper West Side restaurant, a block or so from her
apartment and only a little farther from her childhood home.
``Because I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon grew up a Broadway baby, making her debut in 1980 as
Blythe Danner's kid sister in ``The Philadelphia Story'' at the
Vivian Beaumont Theater. In the last 19 years she has appeared in
25 plays on and off Broadway. She is starring right now in the
Drama Dept.'s production of ``The Country Club'' at the Greenwich
House Theater. And she has achieved her biggest success as the
corporate lawyer Miranda on the hit HBO comedy series ``Sex and the
City'' _ the city, of course, being New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really great that it's a show about Manhattan,'' Ms.
Nixon said. ``I was born in New York. I've always lived in New
York. I always want to live in New York. It's such a part of who I
am. I always say that New York is my ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon, resplendent in a russet brown blouse and pants that
perfectly complemented her short bright-red hair and vibrant blue
eyes, also expresses the proper Manhattanite's attitude toward
fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that `Sex and the City' is on cable,'' she said,
``so it's not everyone walking down the street that recognizes me.
It's more like three people out of 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon is a founding member of the Drama Dept., a highly
praised Off Off Broadway company, and has appeared in five of its
productions, among them ``June Moon'' and ``As Bees in Honey
Drown.'' In ``The Country Club,'' a comedy by Douglas Carter Beane,
the company's artistic director, she portrays Soos, an unhappy
divorcee who returns from California to the place where she grew
up: Wyomissing, Pa., a wealthy, sheltered town of privilege and
ennui. Ben Brantley wrote in The New York Times that Ms. Nixon
``tends to work from the inside out, with an intensity that
suggests she truly feels her characters' pain.''
</P>
<P>
   She may feel that pain as an actress, she said, but as far as
she can see, neither Soos nor Miranda is very much like Cynthia
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soos is really lost,'' she said. ``She's a victim of her
world's values. The only things she has going for her are her
intelligence and her fairly good sense of irony, but they're not
enough. She thinks that because of her irony she can live in this
insular world and not be victimized by it. But she's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to intimacy, Ms. Nixon said, ``Soos is worried she
won't be good at a relationship, that if she gets too close to
somebody, he'll find out there's nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Sex and the City,'' Sarah Jessica Parker, Kristin Davis,
Kim Cattrall and Ms. Nixon portray four New York professionals in
pursuit of relationships; they often seem to have more success
discussing intimate details than achieving intimacy. The show's
second season is in reruns; the third season is to begin in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to men, Miranda has a big chip on her
shoulder,'' Ms. Nixon said. ``She's very confrontational. I think
she's also scared of intimacy. She's had lousy experiences with
men. But she's also looking for reasons for things not to work out.
She's worried that a man will find out how really insecure she is,
no matter how much her accomplishments make her seem impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon, on the other hand, has been in a relationship with
one man for 11 years _ Danny Mozes, who teaches English at Lehman
College in the Bronx. They have known each other since junior high
school and went to Hunter College High School together. When Ms.
Nixon went to Barnard College, Mozes attended Columbia, across the
street. They have a 3-year-old daughter, Samantha Mozes. But they
are not married, and Ms. Nixon said they had no plans to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in marriage,'' she said without hesitation.
``There are a lot of reasons. I think it's all about what will help
you, and I don't think marriage would help me. I think it's so
difficult in a relationship to keep trying not to take the other
person for granted, and I think it would just be another step down
the road to taking him for granted. I always say I love him too
much to marry him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon was interested in theater even before junior high
school. Her mother, Ann Nixon, studied acting at the Yale Drama
School with Stella Adler and Uta Hagen and started taking her
daughter to the theater at an early age. Her father, Walter Nixon,
was for a time a radio journalist in New York who won awards for a
series of civil rights broadcasts in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother tried acting for a while, but it didn't work out, so
she stopped and decided to have a baby,'' Ms. Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon began auditioning in earnest when she was 12, she
said, ``and I started getting jobs right away.'' There was an
after-school television special, a role in the movie ``Little
Darlings'' with Kristy McNichol and Tatum O'Neal, and then ``The
Philadelphia Story'' at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, after starting at Barnard, she won roles in two
Broadway plays and performed in them simultaneously, going from one
theater to the other _ as the bright British daughter in ``The Real
Thing'' by Tom Stoppard and as a teen-age Midwestern drifter in
David Rabe's ``Hurlyburly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought of acting as a moneymaking venture,'' she
said. ``I thought I would do commercials and put money away for
college. But I was just not good at commercials. When I entered
Barnard, I tried to figure out what I would do for a career. I was
very pessimistic about being an adult actor. So very few youngsters
make that transition. But then I just kept on working. So I decided
I didn't have to find anything else to do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon has also appeared on television, in regional theaters
coast to coast and in movies, among them ``Marvin's Room'' ``The
Manhattan Project,'' ``Amadeus'' and ``Addams Family Values.'' But
over the years she has always returned to the New York stage.
</P>
<P>
   Her Broadway credits include ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' ``Angels
in America'' and ``Last Night of Ballyhoo.'' In 1995 she won a Tony
nomination as best featured actress as the innocent bookbinder
Madeleine in Jean Cocteau's ``Indiscretions.'' But in recent years
her New York theater focus has been the Drama Dept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all came about through `The Country Club,''' she said.
``About seven years ago I was performing it at the Dorset Theater
Festival in Vermont. I met Doug Beane, and a while later we did
readings at various theaters in Manhattan trying to get somebody to
do it. But nobody did. Finally, Doug said, `Why don't we start a
theater company?' And I agreed. Because I figured that people say
that all the time and it never happens. But then he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the future? Ms. Nixon said she had no real goals. ``I'm not
a goal person,'' she said. ``I expect nothing, and then I'm usually
pleasantly surprised.'' There are some roles she would enjoy.
``It'd be great to do all those fun Shakespeare young ladies,'' she
said. ``But I also look forward to being 50 or 60 and trying to do
a Cleopatra. Or a Martha in `Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'''
</P>
<P>
   Of one thing, though, she is sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope `Sex and the City' runs for 20 years,'' she said.
``Everybody I know keeps saying to me that three years down the
line I may be kind of bored. But I can't imagine it. It's so
exciting to have a character you know and get a new script every
week and find out what's happening to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very big on continuity. I'm not very imaginative. My idea
is more of the same. That's what I feel about my life: just more of
the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
