<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTCRACKER-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NUTCRACKER': NEW YORK CITY BALLET IN FINE FORM, TO TAPED
TCHAIKOVSKY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The Nutcracker'' opened on Friday night at the New
York State Theater with the New York City Ballet's bright
performance of George Balanchine's version of the choreographic
fairy tale, which has become a holiday tradition. This year,
however, there was a break in tradition. The New York City Ballet
Orchestra was on strike, and Tchaikovsky's score was heard on tape
for the first time since the production's premiere in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Many ballet companies across the United States regularly use
taped accompaniments, as do some foreign companies visiting New
York. But City Ballet has always been associated with live music. A
company spokeswoman said the ``Nutcracker'' tape had been compiled
from a variety of recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra voted to strike on Tuesday, forcing the
cancellation of a gala. No performances at the State Theater were
scheduled Wednesday and Thursday because of Thanksgiving.
Negotiations over a new contract continued on Friday, without
reaching a settlement. No new talks were scheduled until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Protesting musicians gathered on Lincoln Center Plaza on Friday
night, distributing statements declaring that the ballet company's
management ``flatly rejected our proposal to extend the contract''
while issues were being discussed. A statement by the City Ballet
management made available inside the theater said, ``We had already
offered our musicians a comprehensive compensation package that
would continue their status as one of the highest-paid pit
orchestras in America.''
</P>
<P>
   An announcement taped to the theater's doors informed dancegoers
that if they wished to turn in their tickets, refunds would be
granted. The auditorium appeared to be largely full, with scattered
empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before the performance, Peter Martins, the company's
ballet master in chief, said: ``I have the utmost confidence in
what you are about to see, and that these are the greatest dancers
anywhere in the world. They are the best, and they will give you
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   They did. As if aware that the audience craved magic, everyone
danced wholeheartedly. The children in the cast _ students from the
School of American Ballet _ were delightful, including Kara
Buckley, as a sweet Marie; Tyler Gurfein, as a prankish but never
nasty Fritz; and Ezra Hurwitz, who was especially gallant as the
little boy who becomes the Nutcracker.
</P>
<P>
   The grown-ups were in fine form. As the Sugarplum Fairy, Wendy
Whelan looked slightly brittle in her opening solo. But when she
and Damian Woetzel were together in the pas de deux, they offered a
grandly scaled and unusually spacious duet that built to a
brilliant coda. Maria Kowroski was a sparkling Dewdrop. And
Benjamin Millepied and Tom Gold leaped merrily through the Tea and
Candy Cane divertissements.
</P>
<P>
   Robert La Fosse suggests he enjoys portraying Drosselmeier, the
toy maker. Season after season, he experiments with the
interpretative possibilities of the role. One can never predict
what his characterization will be like. On this occasion, his
Drosselmeier was an eccentric old codger, but one who clearly loved
both magic and children. One could imagine him teaching at the
wizards' school in the Harry Potter books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutcracker'' performances are scheduled through Jan. 2 at the
New York State Theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
