<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3267 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-RDP-1105(2TA     11-28 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-RDP-1105(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: IOWA, N.H., MASS., CALIF.)  
 IOWA AND NEW HAMPSHIRE STILL PLAY CRUCIAL ROLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The presidential primary season this week enters a
frantic two-month sprint to the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire
primary as the contenders deliver their pitches in a blast of
speeches, debates and television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the activity until February will be concentrated
in those two states, which for years have held outsized influence
in the nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians and analysts had predicted that Iowa and New
Hampshire would play less of a role in the 2000 campaign because
several larger states, notably California and New York, had moved
up their primaries so they would gain more influence.
</P>
<P>
   But candidates have not dared to shortchange Iowa or New
Hampshire, though many have continued the custom of tromping
through California to replenish their campaign coffers. If
anything, New Hampshire and Iowa have taken on greater consequence
because of a sense among the campaigns that if they do not survive
those states it will not matter how well they are positioned
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, voters in both states have been besieged with
mailings, television and radio advertisements, and visits by
candidate. Except for a respite over Christmas and New Year's _ and
some candidates plan to break political custom and stump heavily
during the holidays _ the motion is not expected to let up until
the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24 and the New Hampshire primary eight
days later on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is countdown time, the 24-hour-a-day, seven-days-a-week
campaign,'' said Michael Whouley, Vice President Al Gore's chief
strategist in Iowa and New Hampshire. ``It's only going to get more
intense. You hope at this point that your state organization can
take advantage of opportunities where your guy puts himself in an
advantageous position _ or your opponent makes a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best evidence of the fierce competition in New
Hampshire could be found on television on Sunday in, of all places,
Boston, where viewers were swamped with commercials extolling Sen.
John McCain of Arizona as a war hero, George W. Bush as an
accomplished governor of Texas and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey as a gifted legislator.
</P>
<P>
   The primary in Massachusetts is not until March 7, but campaigns
are pouring money into Boston television in a drive to reach voters
in southern New Hampshire who watch the Boston stations. While
advertising here is more costly than in Manchester, N.H., it saves
the campaigns that accept federal money from eating up the limit on
how much they can spend in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, Bradley has pumped by far the most money into
Massachusetts television; the campaign put the figure at $252,000,
plus another $73,600 in New Hampshire. Strategists here said they
had never seen one candidate spend so much on Boston television so
early, and the blitz is not expected to slow anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, viewers again and again were bombarded with a
commercial on Bradley's sponsorship of a law requiring
health-insurance companies to cover at least 48 hours of hospital
care for new mothers. At one point Sunday morning, the commercial
appeared simultaneously on the ABC and NBC affiliates in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not spending nearly as much now on television but,
unlike Bradley, the vice president has been broadcasting
commercials in Iowa and New Hampshire for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two months ago everybody was feeling we should walk around
with black armbands and kiss the last presidential candidates
goodbye,'' said Arnie Arnesen, a former Democratic candidate for
governor of New Hampshire who now moderates a radio talk show in
Nashua, N.H. ``Now we're stepping back and saying, `Holy mackerel,
it is real!' We do do something that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican sweepstakes will become fully engaged on
Thursday, when Bush for the first time steps out of his
front-runner's cocoon and takes part in a nationally televised
debate in New Hampshire alongside his rivals. Adding to the
intensity, not to say the drama, is that polls are so tight in New
Hampshire that no one knows who will win the unexpectedly
competitive races on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had dominated the polls in New Hampshire, only to find that
several of his rivals dropped out. That has left him facing a
challenge from McCain, who has come on particularly forcefully in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/Time poll made public two days ago found that McCain was
supported by 37 percent of those likely to vote in the New
Hampshire primary; Bush was backed by 35 percent. The margin of
sampling error was plus or minus four percentage points
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are so high, and I believe both front-runners have
the potential to put it away with wins here,'' said Tom Rath, a
veteran strategist in New Hampshire who is backing Bush. ``This
primary has never had the importance that this one has.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls in the state also show that Al Gore, who had been
considered the overwhelming early favorite, also faces an
unforeseen and powerful challenge from Bradley. For weeks, Bradley
was ahead of Gore in the polls, but now _ after Gore's almost daily
attacks on Bradley on Medicare and other issues _ the vice
president has climbed back to an even position.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Gore campaign is bracing for Bradley to begin
retaliating _ a move that would bring a more negative tone to the
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Bradley and McCain in New Hampshire is particularly
striking because in national surveys Gore and Bush hold towering
leads. It may be because voters in New Hampshire have long prided
themselves on their flinty independence.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, Bush and Gore continue to dominate, at least in the
early polls. McCain, in fact, is eschewing conventional political
wisdom and bypassing the state to concentrate on New Hampshire.
Even so, Steve Forbes, the publisher, is mounting a disciplined
race against Bush in the state, as is Bradley against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   If either of those candidates scores an upset _ or if McCain
performs unexpectedly well without appearing to be even contesting
the state _ that could seriously affect who has the vaunted
political momentum going in to New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa and New Hampshire are perhaps more important than ever
before,'' said Dee Stewart, executive director of the Iowa
Republican Party. Citing the drastically truncated schedule of
contests, he added, ``If a candidate doesn't do well here, there's
not going to be a lot of time after Iowa and New Hampshire to
recover and to be able to put the pieces back together again. The
process is going to be over so quickly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hackley, the owner of an Internet company who held a
meet-and-greet at his house in Des Moines, Iowa, on Sunday evening
for one of the Republican candidates, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah,
said the pace of campaigning has picked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably in the next 10 days this is going to be huge,''
Hackley said. ``Everybody's coming here except McCain.'' Noting the
acceleration of commercials, he added, ``I see Bush two or three
times a night.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the year, many strategists had expected the
candidates to pay less attention to Iowa and New Hampshire and
spend more time in California, which moved its primary to March 7,
and in other states holding early contests. But most of the
campaigns found they did not have the money to wage national
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians elsewhere have long been envious of the influence of
Iowa and New Hampshire, saying it skews the substantive debate
because candidates tailor their message to voters whose
demographics are not representative of the national electorate. For
example, residents of those states tend to be older than the
national median age; those states also have fewer minorities than
many other states do.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates found that the news media did not appear willing
to bestow new prominence on states that had not been as influential
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the ones who drive this, and the candidates know they'll
get credit for doing well in Iowa and New Hampshire,'' said Mark
Halperin, the political director for ABC News. ``We can't chase
these guys everywhere, because Iowa and New Hampshire are reliable
historical benchmarks _ we don't know what winning the Ohio primary
really means. It's safe for the candidate and safe for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists spin an assortment of scenarios about what it would
mean to win or lose Iowa and New Hampshire, given the compressed
calendar of contests that will result in most convention delegates
being selected before the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Many strategists argue that it would be difficult for candidates
who do not win Iowa or New Hampshire to capture their party's
nomination, because the other contests pop up so quickly. ``Even if
the front-runner makes a mistake, there's no time to regroup,''
said David Carney, a longtime Republican strategist in New
Hampshire who is neutral in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Whouley, the Gore aide, put it this way: ``Bradley has to have a
clear knockout early in the process. That's why they're spending
all this money on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even if McCain and Bradley score upsets in New
Hampshire, they could have difficulty capitalizing on their
victories, because of the limited timetable _ and because they lack
the vast national infrastructure of Bush and Gore. On the other
hand, a victory by either of the underdogs in New Hampshire could
lead to nomination battles that would not be settled by the end of
March.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, a spokesman for the Bradley campaign, sought to
tamp down expectations. ``Given the vice president's assumption
that the nomination was a given, the suggestion now that we have to
score a knockout in the first two states is preposterous,'' he
said. ``Our imperative in Iowa and New Hampshire is to do well
against the many advantages the vice president has.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked then if Bradley had to win Iowa or New Hampshire to
ultimately prevail, Hauser said, ``I don't know the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition is so fluid that strategists are preparing for
almost any eventuality in the 57 days leading up to the Iowa
caucuses. ``Iowa seems to be more stable in terms of the
front-runners,'' said James Carville, a top strategist for Bill
Clinton in 1992. ``But that could change pretty quick. And if Gore
or Bush were to lose Iowa, you'd have a huge story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
