<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3278 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     11-28 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALPHA WOLF ON THE JOY OF GROWLING  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The latest Rolling Stone calls the San Francisco Symphony's
 &UR; Michael Tilson Thomas &LR;  ``America's most innovative maestro,''
saying ``he is as well known as a rock star'' in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Upon taking the job in 1995, says the magazine, MTT ``turned a
conservative and slightly fusty orchestra into the most
adventurous, inspiring musical organization in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The conductor praises modern influences _ among them  &UR; Sarah &LR; 
 &UR; Vaughan &LR; ,  &UR; Smokey Robinson &LR; ,  &UR; Sinead O'Connor &LR;  singing  &UR; Prince &LR; 's
``Nothing Compares 2 U'' _ and then provides his favorite metaphor
for the Symphony:
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain orchestras are thought of as athletic teams. But I
like to think about my orchestra as a kind of loving, loyal wolf
pack: When we see one another, we growl. Our musicians happily
growl at one another, because things are good. When the orchestra
plays well, I just lower my head and look at and growl at them. I'm
so proud of them.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. ``S&AMP;M,'' the orchestra's first album with a parental
advisory sticker, was released by Elektra last week. The S refers
to Symphony, the M to Metallica, a group that gets an automatic
warning sticker. The album is a result of the groups' collaboration
last spring at the Berkeley Community Theater.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEATS ON THE VERGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kaffe Fassett &LR; , the painter of the exuberant Old Spaghetti
Factory murals recently re-unveiled at Enrico's, was in town last
week promoting his new book, ``Mosaics: Inspiration and Original
Projects for Interiors and Exteriors'' (Taunton; $35). Fassett, who
lives in London nowadays, described his recollection of the milieu
and the year, 1963:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there, at the end of the B &LR; beatnik era. We were all in
black and talking about existentialism, but I had in my head a
circus playing. When I came in (to see the murals again) and saw
the color, it was joyous and celebratory and thumbing its nose at
all this seriousness.'' With nary a glance to the dark bohemians of
the '60s, the murals seemed to forecast the Summer of Love, said
Fassett, as though to suggest, ``Let's loosen up and enjoy color,
and drape ourselves in Indian bedspreads.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - If you're not stressed enough, contemplate mastering ``The
Complete Idiot's Guide to Power Yoga'' (Macmillan; $18.95), which
aims to ``help individuals gain control over their over-worked,
over-stressed bodies and minds.''
</P>
<P>
   - An emerging problem, as expressed in a press release received
recently, is enough to make one nostalgic for the Stone Age:
``Where can I get Pokemon stuff? The Internet emerges as the only
logical choice.'' Meanwhile,  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  overheard a customer
ask Cody's Books in Berkeley, ``Do you sell Pokemon cards here?'' _
an inquiry he likened to ``asking for a Big Mac at Chez Panisse.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; 's collection of Arts and Crafts furniture
will be auctioned at Christie's today, November 29. The furniture
includes two Gustav Stickley cabinets that will fetch an estimated
$25,000 to $34,000 each. Art &AMP; Auction magazine explainsthis low
price: ``Streisand may have drilled holes in the back to install
stereo equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIFT IDEA NO. 7 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jeni Paltiel  &LR; is thrilled by the porcelain reproductions of
plastic Pez dispensers available in the Wireless catalog. These $20
gifts are ``as sweet and enjoyable as the vintage originals,'' says
the catalog, and come with a porcelain package of Pez candy.
</P>
<P>
   The porcelain Pez dispenser gives out candy that is not edible
and, warns the catalog, is ``not intended as a toy.''
Metaphysicians may be left pondering its use.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Do you think (George) Washington was gay?'' A: ``I don't
think anybody is. I mean, I don't even know what the word means.
Sex is a continuum. There is same sex, there is other sex, there is
vegetable sex, there is bestiality. ... And if you have a lot of
energy, you may go through an awful lot of adventures along life's
way.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Gore Vidal &LR;  being interviewed recently at City Arts &AMP;
Lectures by  &UR; Scott Shafer &LR;  of KQED radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0075 </DOCNO>
