<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-HOMELESS-SHELTERS-     11-28 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-SHELTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 A HUMAN TOLL WHEN HOMELESS SHELTERS GET TOUGH
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One night the Long Island family slept in a church.
For two weeks the superintendent of an apartment building put them
up in his storage space, shifting sheetrock and plywood to make
room for all eight: husband, wife and six children, ages 5 to 13.
Later a widow who shared the family's Pentecostal faith let them
bed down on a comforter spread across her linoleum floor.
</P>
<P>
   During eight weeks of such arrangements this fall, people asked
the parents, Jose Torres and Elizabeth Laboy-Santiago, why they
didn't go to a shelter. They explained that Suffolk County's
Department of Social Services had expelled them because of a missed
workfare appointment, incomplete paperwork and other regulation
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter expulsions have become almost routine in Suffolk, which
for four years has strictly applied the rules that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani intends to enforce in New York City for the first time in
December. Each month, Suffolk County officials say, half a dozen
homeless families are expelled from the shelter motel rooms and
nonprofit agency programs where about 270 families now live.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Nowak, a Suffolk social services spokesman, said families
brought expulsion on themselves, by ignoring the rules and refusing
ample social service help. The regulations, which restrict shelter
to those who meet public assistance requirements, including
workfare, have helped reduce the shelter population by 40 percent
since 1994. While the county does not check what happens to those
expelled, officials say they see no ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   Now, New York City homeless services providers face putting the
regulations into effect for the 5,136 families and 9,096 children
in the city's public shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations make shelter dwellers contribute to the cost of
shelter if they can, to seek and accept permanent housing and to
take other reasonable steps toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   But in practice, county records, state hearing decisions and
interviews illustrate, enforcing the law means some families are
expelled for bureaucratic missteps. Some have been ordered to leave
because they owe small amounts of shelter rent.
</P>
<P>
   And, enforcement sometimes requires families to split up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffolk County doesn't make up the rules,'' Nowak said. ``we
abide by the regulations set forth by the state and federal
governments.'' He added that staff members make every effort to
help families avoid expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   That was not enough for the Torres-Laboy family, however. On
July 1, Torres was ordered from his family's shelter apartment for
six months for missing a March workfare appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who brought his family back to Suffolk from Puerto Rico
in 1995 because the youngest child needed heart operations, had two
earlier welfare sanctions. But he also had a long work history,
including landscaping, and had recently started working full time
in a plastics factory for $5.75 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, he said, he slept in his car or the closet of the
shelter apartment. Once, the couple's 13-year-old daughter Xiomarah
recalled, caseworkers dropped by unannounced while he was asleep in
the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Signer, the social work supervisor at the shelter
agency, Suburban Housing Development and Research, confirmed that
the shelter had Torres' wife sign a contract promising not to let
him in at night, or face expulsion. Under the rules, this was
necessary to preserve shelter for the rest of the family, Ms.
Signer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to house the homeless,'' she said, ``not to make
the homeless homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   But in September, Ms. Laboy Santiago was ordered out, too, over
uncompleted housing logs and $443 in overdue shelter rent.
</P>
<P>
   If their mother had nowhere to take the children, officials
warned, child protective services would be notified.
</P>
<P>
   After eight weeks without housing, unable to keep the children
in school and hard pressed to feed them, the parents took the
county up on an earlier offer: one-way plane tickets back to Puerto
Rico, where relatives in a one-bedroom apartment could take the
family in temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't understand the system,'' Torres said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
