<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ATP-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS BEATS AGASSI IN SEASON-ENDING ATP FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany _ Pete Sampras wondered aloud whether his
tender back could withstand a five-set match against Andre Agassi
in the final of the ATP World Championship on Sunday. Fortunately
for Sampras, he never had to find out. Sampras routed Agassi, 6-1,
7-5, 6-4, to win the season-ending tournament for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   The focus all week had been on the fifth-ranked Sampras, who was
playing in his first tournament since August, and Agassi, the man
who has replaced him at the top of the ranking. Other participants
in the $3.6 million tournament featuring the world's top eight
players had complained that the two Americans were hogging the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should recognize that this isn't just about Andre and
Pete,'' said Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the No. 2-ranked Russian.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was about Agassi and Sampras, but with a result
that few could have foreseen. Agassi had breezed through the
round-robin matches during the week without dropping a set, scoring
a 6-2, 6-2 victory against Sampras on Wednesday. A bit shaky in his
semifinal victory against Kafelnikov on Saturday, Agassi
nonetheless seemed destined to add the championship title to his
French and U.S. Open crowns.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, however, was out to show that while he would not end
the year No. 1 for the first time since 1992 _ Agassi will keep his
ranking for now _ he was intent on reclaiming the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras took control of the match from the start, dispelling any
doubts about the condition of his back by lithely tracking down
whatever Agassi could offer up. Sampras dominated the first set
with an impressive combination of power and finesse, alternately
winning points with decisive slams and freezing Agassi in his
tracks with well-placed forehands. Sampras breezed to a 6-1
victory, a love set averted only by a 14-point fourth game in which
Agassi held serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The start against Pete is so important,'' Agassi said. ``After
I started badly, he took chances on his serve that worked.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, the crowd of 13,500 tried to rouse Agassi
back to life, giving him the support usually reserved for hometown
players. Agassi came out fighting, serving a love game to open the
set and then breaking Sampras' serve, aided by two double faults.
But the crucial mistakes Agassi had avoided all week surfaced at
the worst possible time. Leading by 4-2, he double-faulted en route
to losing his serve. At 5-5, Sampras broke him again, aided by a
crucial unforced error. Sensing an imminent two-set lead, Sampras
closed out the set with two aces.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who had 47 winners to Agassi's 14, slammed his 15th ace
to close out the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to see how I was doing physically,'' Sampras said,
his back heavily iced after the match. ``Winning was a bonus. I got
better as the week progressed and saved the best for last.''
</P>
<P>
   So the year ends with Agassi at No. 1 but with Sampras returning
to the form he showed at this year's Wimbledon when he dealt Agassi
a straight-set loss in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big match today and I didn't rise to the occasion,''
Agassi said. ``But it's tough to beat five of the world's eight
best players in six days.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who will move to No. 3 in the year-end ranking behind
Agassi and Kafelnikov, defeated Agassi in four out of five matches
this year and leads him for their careers, 17-11. After Sunday's
match, he said Agassi deserved the top ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel like No. 1?'' asked Sampras, who won $1.4 million
for his victory. ``Not necessarily. You have to look at the year
he's had with winning the French Open, the U.S. Open, and reaching
the finals at Wimbledon. That's pretty significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras believes, however, that he is healthy enough to make a
run for No. 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it sent him a message today,'' Sampras said. ``But I
don't look at it like it's a personal thing with Andre.''
</P>
<P>
   With the last major tournament of 1999 over, attention turned to
future duels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unhappy with how I played,'' Agassi said. ``But it is
good to see Pete play like this. There's a lot to look forward to
at the Australian Open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
