<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Monday, Nov. 29 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-ENVIRONMENT (Seattle) _ The environmental issues at stake
for the WTO. Free-traders say that the best way to encourage
environment-friendly policies around the globe is to boost world
trade, enriching even the poorest nations enough to afford basic
environmental protections. Environmentalists predict a ``race to
the bottom'' in which all eco-friendly regulations are toppled.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert McClure. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WTO-LOGS (sidebar for WTO-Environment) (Seattle) _ Somewhere
behind the posturing and speechifying of the World Trade
Organization conference this week, the ministers might actually
agree on something: abolishing border taxes on logs, wood products
and paper. Depending on whom you believe, such an agreement could
mean more jobs for U.S. workers, cheaper housing worldwide and
increased environmental protections; or it could mean more
endangered species, fewer jobs for U.S. workers and, in the Third
World, flooding, landslides, hobbled agriculture and ruined
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert McClure. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WTO-ILO29 _ Interview with head of the International Labor
Organization, Juan Somavila.
</P>
<P>
