u i BC-CHECHNYA-RDP-NYT &LR;      11-28 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TO ALLOW CHECHEN CIVILIANS TO FLEE BESIEGED CAPITAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a fresh sign that the Russian military plans to
bombard Grozny into submission, the Russian government said Sunday
that it would open a safe passage for desperate civilians to flee
the Chechen capital, which has been under a withering assault for
days.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian officials said the move was intended to reduce
civilian casualties, it also appeared designed to mute Western
criticism that Russia was harming its own citizens in Chechnya more
than the Islamic militants against whom it has been waging a war in
the renegade republic for nine weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It will also give the Russian military an even freer hand to
conduct air and artillery strikes against the city after Russian
authorities conclude that the civilians there have had their chance
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Since last week, Russian forces have gradually tightened the
noose around Grozny, pummeling the city from the air with fighter
jets as well as on the ground with rockets launched from
helicopters or artillery batteries. The attacks have been the worst
on the Chechen capital since the campaign began, with Grozny's
mayor asserting that at least 260 people had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev has repeatedly said that
his forces have no intention to ``storm'' the city. That pledge is
meant to reassure the Russian public that the military will try to
avoid the sort of deadly street-to-street fighting that resulted in
thousands of Russian casualties during the 1994-96 war in Chechnya,
which ended with the republic's de facto secession.
</P>
<P>
   But such statements do not mean that Russia is not planning to
retake the city. The ferocity of the attacks in recent days has
made clear that the military's strategy is to bludgeon and squeeze
the city into submission. Grozny is a symbol of the Russian
military's humiliation during the 1994-1996 war, and Russia's
generals show every sign of wanting it back.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of clear skies, the Russian forces stepped up
their attacks on Grozny and the surrounding area Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Nikolai Koshman, the senior Russian
representative to Chechnya, said that Russian aircraft had dropped
leaflets in Grozny telling civilians that a special route has been
set up so that they can safely leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are still people there,'' Koshman told a Russian
television interviewer. ``But it is not a large number, and for
these people a corridor has been left in agreement with federal
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   But the establishment of a humanitarian corridor will not end
the risk civilians face from Russia's grinding military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how elderly, infirm or wounded civilians still
trapped in the capital will be able to leave. Nor is it clear how
many civilians are holed up in basements and apartment houses
there.
</P>
<P>
   Television pictures from last week show that the streets are
virtually empty, but reports from the region also said that
hundreds of people had streamed out of the city in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, not all of the latest fighting was aimed at Grozny.
Russian artillery pounded Argun, Urus-Martan and several other
Chechen towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   The news agency Interfax reported Sunday that its correspondent
has seen burnt out cars and tractors along the roads leading from
Urus-Martan, the scene of fierce fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of those strikes seemed to be to destroy Islamic rebels
fleeing Uras-Martin. But desperate civilians are also on the road,
trying to make their way to Ingushetia or, at least, to a Chechen
village that has not became a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 civilians crossed into Ingushetia on Saturday alone,
pushing the total number of refugees there to well over 200,000.
Trucks were lined up at the border, carrying white flags so they
would not be fired at.
</P>
<P>
   Such markings are sometimes not enough. The Russian military
does not have the mandate, training or munitions to wage the sort
of precision warfare NATO conducted in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In late October, a Russian plane bombed a truck bearing the logo
of the Red Cross, according to officials with the International
Committee of the Red Cross. And on at least two occasions, Russian
aircraft appear to have bombed the wrong country: neighboring
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been several reported cases of friendly fire in
which the Russian military has bombed its own troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not take a genius to understand that if bombs are
dropped on friendly troops every now and then they must be dropping
on civilians much more frequently,'' observed the newspaper
Vechernaya Moskva.
</P>
<P>
   As the Russian military continued its assault, there was little
concern in Moscow about the plight of civilians there.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sunday evening the NTV network, which is owned by the
media mogul Vladimir Gusinsky, and the ORT network, which is
controlled by the tycoon Boris Berezovsky, broadcast lengthy news
interview programs. But neither concentrated on the Chechen war
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian campaign has drawn mounting criticism from
Western nations, who have complained that Moscow has not taken
proper precautions to minimize civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Michel Camdessus, the managing director of the
International Monetary Fund, added his voice to the chorus and
suggested that the IMF might suspend its loans to Russia if the
Kremlin continued with its war.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Sergei Stephashin, the former prime minister,
Sunday denounced the IMF for engaging in political blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the fund's threat to withhold its next $640 million
disbursement will have little affect on the Russians. The Russian
economy has been buoyed by the rise in world oil prices and the
relatively modest disbursement would not have gone into the
government's coffers. It would have been used to pay old Russian
debts to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Withholding the money would also mark a shift for the fund,
which gave Russia billions of dollars during the last Chechen war.
But then the IMF's goal was to help President Boris Yeltsin fend
off a challenge by the Communists, not to quell the violence in
Chechnya.
</P>
</TEXT>
