<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-HITS-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE TOYS ARE LEADERS IN BOX-OFFICE STAMPEDE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ The movie box-office total for the five-day
Thanksgiving weekend, paced by an astonishing $80.8 million opening
for ``Toy Story 2,'' was strong enough to shatter several records
and confirm Thanksgiving's position as an increasingly important
time to release new films.
</P>
<P>
   In a year that has seen experiments with rapid-editing
techniques and bizarre story lines, the holiday box-office
performance reinforced the idea that familiar characters played by
popular stars and a more mainstream, traditional approach to
storytelling are the things that draw the mass audience to
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems that what the audience is out looking for
are very comfortable, familiar kinds of movies,'' Larry Gleason,
president for worldwide distribution for MGM, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Every Sunday, Exhibitor Relations, a company that monitors
box-office performance, releases an estimate of weekend ticket
sales for the 12 top current films, with more complete figures
coming out on Mondays. Sunday's estimate was that this weekend's
top dozen movies would earn $209.9 million in the five days that
began Wednesday, a figure exceeding by 28 percent the Thanksgiving
record of $163.2 million set last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of that money came from the weekend's four most popular
films. Behind ``Toy Story 2'' was ``The World Is Not Enough,'' the
19th James Bond adventure, which earned $35 million; ``End of
Days,'' a spiritual thriller in which Arnold Schwarzenegger battles
Satan, which made $31 million; and ``Sleepy Hollow,'' a reimagining
of the Washington Irving tale directed by Tim Burton, which earned
$27.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Bond film and ``Sleepy Hollow'' were in their second
week of release. ``End of Days'' opened on Wednesday. ``Toy Story
2'' went into wide national distribution on Wednesday but had been
playing for a week at the Disney-owned El Capitan Theater in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically `Toy Story' shattered all predictions, well beyond
what anybody expected,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of
Exhibitor Relations. ``It's just driving the marketplace right now.
With strong holdovers from `World Is Not Enough' and `Sleepy
Hollow,' and additional boost from `End of Days,' the box office
was just sent into the stratosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Viane, Disney's president for distribution, described the
``Toy Story 2'' opening as ``the most mind-boggling thing that's
ever happened'' and said it was powered by the film's attraction
not only for youngsters and their parents but also for other adults
and a vast teen-age audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the original `Toy Story,' it took two or three weeks for
it to become a movie for everyone,'' Viane said. ``This time they
all came right away. We're seeing 9 p.m., even 10:30 p.m. showings
that are selling out. We all knew we were going to set a record. We
knew that. We could read the numbers. But I don't think we'd ever
have predicted $80 million.''
</P>
<P>
   It marks the sixth year in a row that Disney has had the
highest-grossing film of the Thanksgiving weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2,'' directed by John Lasseter and produced by
Pixar, a computer-generated-animation studio, continues the story
of toys that spring to life when humans aren't watching and
features Tom Hanks as the voice of Woody, a cowboy doll who learns
he's a valuable collectible, and Tim Allen as the voice of Buzz
Lightyear, a formerly deluded space ranger who must save Woody from
an evil collector.
</P>
<P>
   The film drew some of the best reviews of the year. Even so, the
box-office numbers were amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' was playing in 3,236 theaters, the most of any
film this weekend, but still earned $24,969 per theater, compared
with $11,065 per theater for the Bond film and $11,960 per theater
for the Schwarzenegger movie.
</P>
<P>
   If the $80.8 million estimate holds up, it not only will break
the all-time opening for any Thanksgiving film (set last year by
``A Bug's Life,'' also from Disney and Pixar), but it also will be
the third-highest five-day opening for any kind of film at any time
of year, behind ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' at
$105.6 million, and ``Independence Day,'' at $85, both released in
the more lucrative summer season. (``The Lost World,'' Steven
Spielberg's sequel to ``Jurassic Park,'' earned $90.2 million over
a four-day opening weekend in May 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   ``According to our exit research, audiences actually like this
`Toy Story' better than the original one,'' Viane said. ``We
thought we'd have some pretty nice records, but this movie is going
to be around for a long time. We're looking forward to long, long
shelf life.''
</P>
<P>
   Slightly overshadowed by the huge opening of ``Toy Story 2'' was
the continued strong performance of the new James Bond film, which
has earned more than $76 million in its first 10 days of release
and is all but guaranteed to be the most lucrative 007 adventure in
the series' 30-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the last three Bond movies, the ones starring Pierce
Brosnan, have gotten a little bit better and been able to expand
the audience,'' Gleason said. ``They just seem to be building,
developing new fans each time. And I think we've been successful in
making Bond attractive to a younger and younger audience.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A bit flattened by the juggernaut of the top four films was
``Flawless,'' a drama directed by Joel Schumacher and starring
Robert De Niro about a conservative man's encounters with a drag
queen neighbor. Its national release on Wednesday was much more
limited than the other films, just 478 theaters, and it landed in
12th place for the weekend, earning an estimated $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest has been the performance of ``Being John
Malkovich,'' directed by Spike Jonze, an utterly strange story of a
secret portal that leads into the actor John Malkovich's
consciousness. Even though it played this weekend on fewer screens
than the previous weekend, the audience word of mouth was strong
enough to increase its box-office take by 18 percent, up to $2.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   That was the anomaly, though. Mostly, audiences seemed to want
to see the same kinds of films they have wanted throughout the
year, traditional mainstream fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every `Sixth Sense' or `Blair Witch Project' and other
anomalies, there are many more traditional films making up the top
of the box office,'' Dergarabedian said. ``The key to success turns
out to be giving people what they want, which turns out to be the
same thing they've always wanted. They want to be entertained.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
