<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MILLENNIUM-ON-STAGE-A     11-28 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-ON-STAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONS: ADVANCING TOWARD THE MILLENNIUM IN GOOD COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Voices and bodies, as tuned and trained, as quick to respond to
commands as any piece of glittering technology, and alive to
impulse, too: This is what gives one hope for a millennium theater
we may bask, even glory, in.
</P>
<P>
   My good spirits began on Sunday, Nov. 14, with a staged reading
of Edward Albee's master play ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf,'' a
one-time-only birthday gala for that once-in-a-lifetime actress,
Uta Hagen. Ms. Hagen was turning 80 and returning to a role she
originated when the play opened in 1961. There was a photograph of
her from that time on the Playbill. Slouched on a sofa, she holds a
full liquor glass in one hand as if about to wave a flag. The other
arm lies boozily at ease. The head is slightly cocked (``I'm too
clever to be just another drunk,'' it says), and the face belongs
to a woman as coarse as she is highhanded.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous. The play is a night, a season in hell with two
couples; faculty husbands and wives at a small New England college.
Martha and George are middle-aged and bitter enough to turn every
social occasion into a bout of marital flagellation. Nick and Honey
are young, ambitious and self-conscious enough to still pretend
they're happy together, at least until Martha and George take them
in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Because the actors were seated most of the time, the prose
(elegant, brutish, guarded and hilarious) gave us the sense a book
does, of being alone with a story. But because of the actors'
voices, their concentration, the dynamics of their bodies even
sitting down, we got the emotional shock that only performance
delivers: flesh and blood lives being mangled right there in front
of us.
</P>
<P>
   As the embarrassed, miserable Nick and Honey, Matthew Broderick
and especially Mia Farrow were very good. Ms. Hagen was
astonishing, and so was Jonathan Pryce as George, the husband whose
humiliation becomes desperation and then treachery. The performance
took place in the Majestic Theater, which normally houses ``The
Phantom of the Opera.'' Who needed fussed-over sets and costumes?
For a night at least there was real majesty on that stage.
</P>
<P>
   The next Friday I went down to the Performing Garage in SoHo to
see the Wooster Group's revival of its 1984 piece ``North
Atlantic.'' (It will reopen in January.) The Group, under the
direction of Elizabeth LeCompte, is a fierce, iconoclastic
repertory company. What would it do with ``Virginia Woolf'' one
wonders, for they often take up, take apart then build radical new
models of classics. (``The Three Sisters,'' ``Our Town,'' ``The
Hairy Ape'' and ``The Emperor Jones,'' for instance.)
</P>
<P>
   They also build works from an uncanny layering of nonfiction
texts and performance fantasies. These can be brutal, funny and
sometimes brutally funny. Or do I mean funnily brutal?
</P>
<P>
   ``North Atlantic'' is set in the Reagan 1980s on an aircraft
carrier, so the feel is strictly Evil Empire, 1950s-style. There's
the ``we're in uniform here'' posture, the rat-a-tat talk about
espionage and missions so secret you're not sure you're on them;
the blasts of dirty jokes delivered with tight-jawed manliness or
rancid girlishness; the chain of competition and command among the
men. And the round of gossip, spite, ingratiation and degradation
from the enlisted women that, like the coding machines they type
on, never stops.
</P>
<P>
   Everything gets to near-breaking point while staying in complete
control. It's exhilarating to watch performers who can do this. And
to watch something that's a satire, a hallucination and a musical.
</P>
<P>
   The Wooster Group treats texts like musical scores. It's in the
multiple rhythms of the dialogue, the microphones and tapes that
help create dynamics; all the pitches the actors employ, from the
maniacally fixed voices of the five men (led by Willem Dafoe and
Steve Buscemi) to the women's calculating changes of tone and
texture led by the amazing Kate Valk. Country and western songs
delivered with garish sincerity punctuate the action; the movement
is so intricately paced and proportioned it is a kind of
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   The group's past works have drawn from the McCarthy hearings,
autobiographical monologues and the blackface vaudeville routines
of Pigmeat Markham, all played out amid video screens, industrial
sets and the constant sampling of dance and music styles. (Japanese
Butoh? Viennese waltzes? Jitterbugging or a little pointe work?)
</P>
<P>
   These aren't just more examples of postmodern pastiche. They're
organic to a theater that is about how the internal riot inside us
meets the external riot of language and the chaos of the structures
(social, sexual, theatrical, technological) that confine us.
</P>
<P>
   My weekend ended with a ballet performance at the New Victory
Theater. Having refused to believe that what is first-rate for
children cannot also be first-rate for adults, the New Victory now
refuses to honor the dreary conventional wisdom that divides
audiences into those who prefer ballet and those who prefer
theater. So for 10 days we got to see a group of young dancers from
other companies and countries performing under the tutelage of
Suzanne Farrell, one of the greatest ballet dancers of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to be quoting Yeats right now, and certainly the
lines ``I knew a phoenix in my youth,/So let them have their day''
tend to sum up the feelings of those who saw her dance. But there
is nothing elegiac about her project, ``Suzanne Farrell Stages the
Masters of 20th-Century Ballet.'' Backstage now, coaching and
rehearsing the ballets of George Balanchine, Jerome Robbins and
Maurice Bejart (some created just for her), Ms. Farrell gave fresh
life to classic art and new possibilities to gifted young dancers
and eager, needy audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the excitement came from an individual. In Robbins'
languorous, cheeky ``Afternoon of a Faun,'' the New York City
Ballet dancer Phillip Neal was focused now, thrillingly alive to
what a young body can do in art or love, then subsiding into
Debussy chords as Christina Fagundes left him, sweetly but
inevitably.
</P>
<P>
   A duet from Bejart's ``Romeo and Juliet'' wasn't the greatest
choreography (call it flash-dance ballet), but because Ms. Farrell
taught the dancers, Ben Huys and Veronica Lynn, to give themselves
to its physical and musical logic, real emotion followed. They gave
it dignity, so it gave them grace.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there was Balanchine. Ms. Farrell was his muse for 22
years. The things he used to say, like: ``You cannot dance
psychology. We move. We use images.'' ``Dance has to look like the
music.'' And ``See the music and hear the dancing.'' They are part
of her, body and soul. And we see them in her staging of his
``Divertimento No. 15.'' Mozart's music is meant to lift the
curtain onto a kind of blissful order that is part of daily life.
Balanchine does Mozart the honor of not just partnering him, he
betters him. The ballet is one glorious unfolding phrase with room
for endless rhythms, accents and tonal shadings.
</P>
<P>
   Uta Hagen helped found a studio to train actors and playwrights.
Elizabeth LeCompte helped start the group she now directs. Suzanne
Farrell needs her own permanent company, and we need it, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TAFEL-PROFILE-ART-840     11-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAFEL-PROFILE-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY REPUBLICAN FIERCELY LOYAL DESPITE BUSH'S SNUB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As an outspokenly gay Republican, Richard Tafel is
accustomed to critiques from the left and the right. He recently
wrote a book, ``Party Crasher: A Gay Republican Challenges Politics
as Usual,'' that essentially tries to defend his place on the
political map _ or, as he puts it somewhat more grandly, to answer
the question ``How did a nice guy like me find myself in the
crossfire of American politics?''
</P>
<P>
   Tafel, who is executive director of the Log Cabin Republicans, a
gay political group, writes that he was once compared to an abused
wife who goes back to her husband, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   But Tafel sees his steadfast Republicanism as a matter of
stubborn principle, not pathology. He grew up as one of six
children in Bucks County, Pa., with a set of Republican beliefs.
``It didn't make sense that I should jettison everything that I was
_ my family, my faith, my political principles _ because I was
gay,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was one of those weeks for Tafel. A week ago, the
Republican front-runner in the presidential race, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, appeared on the NBC News program ``Meet the Press''
and was asked, in a wide-ranging interview, whether he would meet
with the Log Cabin Republicans. Bush answered, ``Oh, probably
not,'' explaining that ``it creates a huge political scene.'' Tafel
was on his way to church when his cell phone started ringing with
reports of what Bush had said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, in his office near DuPont Circle, Tafel still
seemed slightly surprised by the whole affair, which struck him as
strangely ``passe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, what a dumb mistake,'' he said. ``Ten years
ago his father met with gays in the White House. Pat Buchanan
announced he's welcoming gays to support his campaign in the Reform
Party. Jerry Falwell met with gays down in Lynchburg, Va. It's just
not a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are way beyond meetings,'' Tafel insisted.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, the kind of episode that makes Democrats ask:
Why do gay Republicans stay?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay Republicans are in the Republican Party primarily because
they agree with most of the Republican agenda _ less government,
free markets, a strong defense, a tradition of individual rights
that has been in debate this whole decade,'' Tafel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the gay Republican says, I would rather change the
Republican Party to make it more inclusive, which will benefit
every gay person in the long run, than flee to the Democratic
Party, get placed under the umbrella of identity politics and then
be put in a position, strategically as a community, where we get
written off by the Republicans and taken for granted by the
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Tafel, 37, takes the long view. Already, he
says, Republicans are competing for gay voters in many states.
Moreover, he argues, ``It's not like we're asking them to do
something courageous that's going to lose for them.'' Republicans
do better in elections when they are perceived to be tolerant, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And what do gay Republicans want from their party? ``Our goal is
for this to be a neutralized issue,'' he said. Yes, he added, his
members are concerned about issues like adoption and gay marriage,
but he said: ``The short-term goal is to neutralize the rhetoric
and the fear. And when George W. Bush says he can't meet, you know,
there's only one group in the Republican Party that he can't meet
with, we have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   How did Tafel end up here, living on his party's uneasy fault
line between economic and social conservatism? He intended to
become a minister; he was raised in the American Baptist Church,
and his grandfather and a great-uncle were ministers in the
Swedenborgian church, a small Protestant denomination whose
theology reflects the work of the 18th-century philosopher and
scientist Emmanuel Swedenborg.
</P>
<P>
   Tafel majored in philosophy at East Stroudsburg University in
Pennsylvania, and then went to Harvard Divinity School. He
acknowledged that he was gay after he moved to Cambridge. ``The
word wasn't even mentioned where I grew up,'' he said. He received
his Master of Divinity degree and became an ordained minister, but
was pulled ever deeper into politics, eventually working in the
administration of Gov. William Weld of Massachusetts, the moderate
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Republican National Convention in Houston, and in
particular Pat Buchanan's declaration that a ``cultural war'' was
breaking out in America, made Tafel determined to stay and fight in
the Republican Party. For the last six years he has been executive
director of the Log Cabin Republicans, which has its roots in
California and is named for Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Tafel said, the Bush flap will build support
among gay Republicans for Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Bush's
rival, who has met with the group. ``Our people are much more
excited about raising money for McCain,'' Tafel said, adding that
his goal is to raise $50,000 for him by the end of the year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A Log Cabin strategy meeting is planned for this week, and in
the meantime, Tafel was making the rounds of the talk shows,
arguing that Bush's move was not only wrong, but bad politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Tafel said last week, ``Our battle in the Republican
Party is to make it what it should be _ a party of Lincoln, a party
of inclusion.'' He acknowledged that it was not a job for the
thin-skinned, but, as he put it in his book, ``I didn't get
involved in politics to be liked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
