<HEADER>
A3313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-URUGUAY-VOTE-NYT &LR;      11-28 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URUGUAY-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING PARTY CANDIDATE WINS PRESIDENCY IN URUGUAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay _ The candidate of the governing Colorado
Party won the Uruguayan presidency in his fifth try Sunday by
beating back a strong challenge from a leftist coalition that
included Socialists, Communists and former guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Batlle, the governing party candidate, promised in his
campaign to pursue a vigorous foreign policy that would open
markets for Uruguay's dairy and wool products and to improve
educational opportunities by broadly expanding computer and
internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But what caught the attention of analysts throughout Latin
America was the impressive showing by Batlle's challenger, Tabare
Vazquez, the former mayor of Montevideo, the capital. Vazquez, an
oncologist, challenged the free-enterprise policies that are now
fashionable around the region and pledged an aggressive campaign
against poverty.
</P>
<P>
   All four television channels announced at 8:30 p.m. that Battle,
a 72-year-old former senator known for bluntly speaking his mind,
seemed to have won the election based on separate exit polls. With
only minor differences, the polls showed Battle winning 52 percent
of the vote, while Vazquez, 59, won 45 percent. Nevertheless,
Vazquez's Frente Amplio could claim a victory of sorts since it won
the largest bloc of votes in the Uruguayan Congress in the October
31 first-round balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Batlle was able to defeat Vazquez by forming an alliance with
the center-right National Party three weeks ago, so the two
traditional parties that have dominated this tiny country of 3.2
million people for most of the last 150 years will now form a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Batlle (pronounced BAH-jay) has been a candidate four times
before, in 1966, 1971, 1989 and 1994, but under a previous system
that combined primary votes with the general election, lost to
other Colorado or opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Batlle is likely to follow the policies of the current
president, Julio Maria Sanguinetti, of seeking out more foreign
investment for the tourism industry and cautiously privatizing some
government services to cut a bloated bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Uruguay is well behind neighboring Argentina and most other
Latin American countries in privatizing industry because its voters
continue their strong support for welfare-state policies that go
back to the presidency of Batlle's granduncle at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   In a historical twist, it is the Tupamaros, the former
guerrillas, and other left-wing groups that once attacked Uruguay's
social democracy as a liberal trick to subdue the masses that now
most strongly defend the cradle-to-grave welfare state. The
government provides insurance against catastrophic health problems,
operates the electricity system, gas stations and casinos and even
produces whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez led in the polls for most of the last year, but
previously undecided voters appeared to be swayed by a Batlle media
blitz in the final weeks of the campaign suggesting that a leftist
victory would mean higher income taxes and economic and political
instability. But Vazquez's strong showing, combined with his
winning a plurality in the first round of voting, has put the two
traditional parties on notice that voters are growing restless with
what is widely perceived as their uncreative leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The Broad Front has become increasingly popular since it was
founded 30 years ago; it won only 18 percent of the national vote
in 1971. After more than a decade of military rule, the alliance
won 21 percent in the 1984 presidential balloting, then 24 percent
in 1989, 30 percent in 1994 and 39 percent in the first-round
presidential vote last month.
</P>
<P>
   A charismatic speaker, Vazquez was able to tap into growing
popular frustration with a recession that has left 11 percent of
the work force unemployed and an economy that shrank this year,
instead of growing.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, as he closed his campaign, Vazquez told a
television interviewer that no matter the results, the left had
won. ``We've reached a quiet revolution, breaking old structures,''
he said. ``The Uruguayan people have transformed us into the first
political force in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As Battle closed his campaign with a television message to the
country, he said, ``The first thing we need is institutional
stability, next economic stability and finally social stability.''
He added, ``What we don't need is more taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   As Uruguayans voted Sunday, Montevideo's streets were full of
cars flying Uruguayan and party flags. Drivers of competing
caravans honked horns and cheerfully debated with one another from
their car windows in what amounted to a civic fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   At a polling place in the middle-class neighborhood of Pocitos,
Marta Arigoni, a 56-year-old French teacher, said she had voted for
Vazquez because the country ``needs fundamental change'' to improve
public health and education. ``As Jose Artigas once said,'' she
noted, quoting the 19th-century general who fought for independence
from Spain, ``the least favored should be the most privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria del Carmen Saccone, a 57-year-old plastics factory owner,
said she had voted for Battle because the country is doing well.
``The left would take us backward,'' she said, ``and their view of
taking this society in the direction of Cuba doesn't make sense
given how Cuba is functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Such diverse political opinions heard at the same voting place
is becoming unusual in most Latin American countries, where voters
increasingly vote for centrist candidates and disagree on
personalities more than on policies. But Uruguay remains
surprisingly ideological compared with its neighbors, although
political violence is still exceptionally rare.
</P>
<P>
   Agustin Canzani, a leading political pollster, said on a
television talk show the other night that Uruguay ``is a very
divided country, whoever wins the election,'' adding, ``That's
something we'll have to think about for a long time to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
