<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TALK-MAGAZINE-MEDIA-A     11-28 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALK-MAGAZINE-MEDIA-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE FACING TALK: REGENERATE THE BUZZ
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After four issues, Tina Brown's Talk magazine is no
longer the talk of the town. After the burst of attention that
accompanied the first issue _ which featured an arguably revealing
profile of the First Lady _ the magazine has hardly stirred a
whisper.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation it has prompted has consisted mostly of the
curious musings of media watchers: Why has the magazine featured
cover stories on Elizabeth Taylor and Farrah Fawcett and Ava
Gardner, movie stars who have been out of the loop _ if not
actually deceased, as in Ms. Gardner's case _ for some time?
</P>
<P>
   This is a critical time for Talk. In a unusual arrangement,
advertisers were required to buy ads in the first four issues or
not at all; now, they are facing the crucial fifth issue. And Ms.
Brown _ the editor who made ``buzz'' and celebrity ``wrangling''
the watchwords of the magazine industry _ is now at the mercy of
the very forces she created, facing a wall of silence. Perhaps this
is an overly harsh judgment to make of a magazine so new, but it is
made on Ms. Brown's own terms. After all, Talk advertisements
promised it would spur ``national debate.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is time for a change. Three key editors have resigned, and
Ms. Brown recently hired Robert B. Wallace, the former editor in
chief of St. Martin's Press, to be editorial director. Oliviero
Toscani, the designer who fashioned Benetton's advertising
campaigns, has signed on to be creative director and retool the
magazine's look.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a deeper question, bound to be raised at a
celebritycentric magazine half-owned by a movie studio: Who is in
control of the editorial mix? Ms. Brown, the editor in chief, or
Harvey Weinstein, the co-chairman of Miramax Films?
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is published in partnership by Hearst Magazines and
Miramax, a division of the Walt Disney company. And, though Miramax
and Disney movies make up only a small portion of the 1999 market
share of the film industry _ 20 percent in terms of revenues
through the month of October, according to The Hollywood Reporter _
about half of the features in Talk by or about people in the movie
industry are about people involved in Miramax or Disney projects.
</P>
<P>
   Of 22 articles in the first four issues written by people in the
film industry or about people or characters in the film industry,
11 featured people recently or currently affiliated with Miramax or
Disney projects.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the first four covers featured an actor or actress who
was in either a Miramax or Disney film in the last year: Gwyneth
Paltrow on the September issue, whom Weinstein refers to as ``the
first lady of Miramax''; Charlize Theron, on the October issue,
appears next month in ``Deception,'' which is produced by Dimension
Films, a Disney unit of which Weinstein is co-chairman; and
Julianne Moore, who starred in the Miramax film ``An Ideal
Husband'' this year, on the November issue.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Williams, who stars in the coming Disney film
``Bicentennial Man,'' appears on the December/January issue, posed
with the robot character from the movie, accompanied by an adoring
profile by Paul Theroux.
</P>
<P>
   Because Weinstein is a true Hollywood schmoozer, one of the few
people in New York who can actually refer to Leonardo DiCaprio as
``Leo'' with a straight face, he is emerging as a player _ a sort
of uber-celebrity wrangler _ at the magazine. It was he who called
Ms. Theron and asked her to appear on the cover of Talk.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Theron, who had a previous agreement with Esquire magazine,
said she would not appear on the cover and wrote a letter to Ms.
Brown asking not to be on the cover, said an executive involved in
the negotiations. But Johnny Depp, who had been promised a cover
spot, was replaced with Ms. Theron, the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Depp's new movie, ``Sleepy Hollow,'' is released by the
Paramount Pictures unit of Viacom, while Ms. Theron's is a favored
project of Weinstein, Miramax staff members said.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said that he did call Ms. Theron, but that his
involvement was merely secretarial. ``Tina called me and said, `We
want Charlize. Charlize has a scheduling conflict. Can you help
us?''' he recalled. ``I called Charlize, and she moved something
around. So there was no scheduling conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said that he was available to Ms. Brown, but that
``Talk is Tina's magazine.'' He added: ``If there's a hot Miramax
movie, I hope they'll cover it. But that's up to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Talk is not the only American magazine part of a
larger corporate structure with an interest in film studios. Two
weeks ago, Time magazine, owned by Time Warner, ran a cover story
about the Pokemon craze, just as ``Pokemon: The First Movie'' was
about to be distributed in the United States by Warner Brothers,
which is also owned by Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   But Talk's situation is different from that of Time, which
depends far less on celebrity faces to sell its product each month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the large Disney presence in Talk, Ms. Brown says the
magazine is not playing favorites. And she sees nothing wrong with
letting Weinstein run a little interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time for a magazine to establish its identity,'' she
said, ``and when you're in the early stages, the first six months
of a product's life, you need all the help you can get. Harvey has
been generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken time to organize our approach to Hollywood, which
is very much organized around the world of celebrities. I am afraid
I am partly to blame for that because I kind of invented the
concept of the celebrity wrangler and now everybody is wrangling
away.''
</P>
<P>
   But she emphasized that Weinstein was not dictating the
editorial scope of the magazine. ``Harvey is as involved as I want
him to be,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She defended her mix of Disney versus non-Disney celebrities.
About the attention she is giving to the new Miramax movie, ``The
Talented Ripley,'' starring Ms. Paltrow and Matt Damon, Ms. Brown
said that the film ``is very much a Talk audience movie and we
would be cheating our audience if we didn't have stories about
it.'' The current issue of the magazine includes two articles about
the movie, which is distributed and produced by Miramax in
partnership with other film companies, and another article is
scheduled for the February issue.
</P>
<P>
   But what of Elizabeth Hurley, the actress who appears in an
other-worldly fashion shoot in the December/January issue? Ms.
Hurley appeared in a Disney movie, ``My Favorite Martian,''
released earlier this year. No mention of that was made in her
fashion spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea she was in a Martian movie,'' Ms. Brown said,
adding that she did not find out Ms. Hurley was in ``My Favorite
Martian'' until the magazine was going to press.
</P>
<P>
   After four issues, Ms. Brown said she now planned to pull back a
bit and devote more time to running the entire Talk enterprise,
which also includes a book and fledgling Internet division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should not be absorbed in reading six drafts of an article,
which is what I have been doing, which has been my dilemma,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said that she was working out the significant initial
problems of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the success of the first issue, it was a crazy,
wonderful thing, but I knew our staff was too small,'' she said,
adding that she had expanded the staff.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she would consider changing the paper quality of
the magazine, which is now printed on thin paper that does not
reproduce photographs well. ``Pocket Fashion,'' a feature at the
front of the magazine that showcases high-priced fashion items and
services, like $700 boots and $200 pedicures, will go.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the magazine needed to break more news.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's about bringing in more enterprising writers, not
just chasing down stories that are already out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That will be Wallace's job. Formerly a producer for ABC News and
editor at Rolling Stone magazine as well as a book editor, Wallace
said he planned to bring more investigative pieces to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make news and break news and that means looking for
stories with a lot of journalistic calories,'' he said. ``I have
been around long enough to take the long view on a story.''
</P>
<P>
   From a business perspective, the formula may be working _ for
now. Because Ronald A. Galotti, the magazine's publisher, required
that advertisers sign on for the first four issues, the magazine is
enjoying a steady stream of advertising revenue. Galotti said that
advertising revenue for the first four issues was $19 million. By
contrast, advertising revenue for Esquire's 12 issues in 1998 was
an estimated $42 million, for Details $31 million, and for Vanity
Fair $109 million. If Talk kept up its pace for all 10 of its first
year's issues, ad revenue for the first year would be $47.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Galotti said that the first issue sold extremely well on
newsstands but conceded that subsequent issues had sold far fewer
copies. Still, he said that newsstand sales would average 247,000
copies an issue for the first six months and that he would promise
advertisers a circulation rate base of 650,000 in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Jordan, the president of Circulation Specialists Inc.,
said that according to figures from New York newsstand wholesalers,
the first issue sold 100,000 copies on newsstands in New York, and
about half that for the second issue. He had no figures for the
third or fourth issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are very good numbers for New York, which is one of the
key markets for newsstand sales,'' Jordan said. ``A lot of other
fairly major national magazines put out fewer magazines than Talk
has actually sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Galotti said that he would have 300,000 subscribers in hand by
February, though there is no way to verify that number or to figure
how much is being spent to get each subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers remain cautiously optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Doyle, the managing director for media at Lowe, Lintas &AMP;
Partners, said: ``The early indications are that they
overdelivering their rate base significantly. From what we can
tell, in the early stages, it's an affluent educated audience. But
the big question is, is there continued consumer interest? If we
see that consumer interest continues to be as strong as Ron says,
then the advertising support will certainly be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein's view? Business is booming. He said: ``Count the
pages, please, and call the advertisers. Ron Galotti wouldn't give
a discount to his grandmother.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 1951EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
