<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-WRAP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane season known for big miss, little hit
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The 1999 hurricane season, which ends
Tuesday, will be remembered for Floyd, the big one that got away,
and Irene, the little one that didn't; for a late season hurricane
that reminded us to be wary into November; and for an ominous
first: five storms of Category 4 or higher in one year _
miraculously, none coming ashore at that strength.
</P>
<P>
   The five storms that killed people _ none stronger than Category
2 on the Saffir-Simpson scale when they made landfall _ may have
been responsible for the deaths of nearly 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   After bracing for Hurricane Floyd, which threatened to be the
most powerful hurricane strike on Palm Beach County and the
Treasure Coast since the great 1928 storm, people were caught off
guard when Irene slipped up the peninsula and drenched South
Florida on Oct. 15 and 16.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Irene brought gusts as high as 92 mph to the
Glades, but never brought hurricane-force winds across the
mainland. Still, its rains _ Boynton Beach alone experienced nearly
16 inches in two days _ brought flooding that took days to
dissipate. Winds and flooding caused at least $200 million in
insured damages.
</P>
<P>
   Irene killed seven people in South Florida, all in Broward
County. A mother, her two sons and a neighbor boy were electrocuted
in Weston in calf-deep water when they stepped into a puddle
containing a downed power line while walking their dog during a
lull in the storm. A 13-year-old Cooper City boy died when he
grabbed a downed power line as he waded through 18 inches of water
during the storm. And two people drowned after driving into canals
next to flooded roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irene is a reminder that October is a busy month,'' National
Hurricane Center forecaster Richard Pasch said last week. ``Florida
gets a lot of hurricane hits in October; we saw it frequently in
the 1930s and 1940s. That's a reality check.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd was larger than life as it bore down on the Florida
peninsula Sept. 12, with top sustained winds of 155 _ about the
same strength as Andrew. Florida's salvation was a giant trough
that forecasters said would begin steering Floyd away from shore
about 24 hours ahead of projected landfall, which at the time
looked more and more like downtown West Palm Beach. The storm did
turn on time that night, but not before nerve-wracked residents
boarded up and chewed fingernails. Procrastinators fighting for
plywood caused turmoil at home improvement stores.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd later straddled the coast through the Carolinas to New
England, bringing catastrophic flooding to North Carolina and New
Jersey and killing at least 69 people _ the largest U.S. loss of
life since Agnes in 1972. Early damage estimates were at least $3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Another storm, Dennis, had come ashore in the Carolinas on Aug.
30 and gone out to sea, but returned and savaged the North Carolina
coast for a week, bringing heavy rains, gale force winds and
flooding. Seven people died.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, the deadliest storm wasn't the strongest
or the wettest. It wasn't even a tropical storm. A tropical
depression formed off Mexico's Yucatan peninsula Oct. 4 and came
ashore northeast of the coastal resort of Veracruz; that weather
system and another one next to it brought torrential rains that
caused flooding and mud slides that may have killed as many as 400.
</P>
<P>
   Just as people were starting to take down their shutters, Lenny
sprang to life in mid-November, racing from the Gulf of Mexico east
through the Caribbean. It killed 13 people in the Virgin and
Leeward Islands before fizzling on Sunday, only nine days before
the official end of hurricane season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
