<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock Market's Success May Hinder Future Rally
</P>
<P>
   With about a month left in the millennium, the three main stock
gauges are poised to record annual returns of more than 10 percent
each for the fifth consecutive year _ an unprecedented streak. But
the wealth generated by those gains may also pose the biggest
threat to a repeat performance in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If the gauges keep rising, some economists argue, the stock
market will continue to fuel consumer spending, which could prompt
the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest rates. Higher
rates could spook equity investors if they conclude that the
economy and earnings growth will finally slow significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Music TV Shows May Have Peaked
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm for music-based television miniseries is starting
to cool, largely because the most ambitious music project this fall
was undone by ABC's rampaging _ and inexpensive _ ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' game show. CBS promoted ``Shake, Rattle and Roll,''
a fictionalized journey through the early rock 'n' roll years,
heavily, and scheduled it on the first Sunday in November. But
``Millionaire'' pushed the miniseries to a poor first-hour rating,
and the show never recovered. CBS has no music-based movie projects
on its development slate, although NBC has ``The '70s'' ready for
May. And it may commission a film on the '50s rocker Little
Richard.
</P>
<P>
   The Architect of a Wireless Empire
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Gent, the chief executive of Vodafone AirTouch, has
moved with dizzying speed to fulfill his vision of a company that
would operate the world's largest wireless network, positioning it
smartly for the future. But his hostile offer for Mannesmann was
rejected by the company's supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Online Ad Crowd for Super Bowl
</P>
<P>
   The scramble by Internet companies to increase recognition of
their brand names by advertising in traditional media outlets will
accelerate on Super Sunday. Dot-coms are paying record prices _ an
estimated average of more than $2 million for each 30-second
commercial during the Super Bowl, which is at least 25 percent
higher than the 1999 rate.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson of Britain Bids for Pioneer
</P>
<P>
   Hanson, the British building-materials producer, said that it
had offered to buy Pioneer International of Australia for $2.51
billion to strengthen its global position.
</P>
<P>
   Dispute Over Customized Music
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of Web sites are offering customized music
programming. What the listeners are not hearing is a
behind-the-scenes dispute between the sites and record labels over
how much these sites should reimburse record labels each time they
play recordings owned by the labels.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout From `Y2K: The Movie'
</P>
<P>
   After the broadcast of ``Y2K: The Movie,'' in which computing's
millennium glitch leads to industrial apocalypse and sets off a
nuclear meltdown, a manager at Charles Schwab in San Francisco
rushed to calm the gullible. In an e-mail memo to employees, a
manager involved with Schwab's Year 2000 preparedness effort
assured employees that the Year 2000 movie ``would not be the
typical scenario.'' Needless to say, the note elicited a few
derisive snorts from the technology-savvy employees.
</P>
<P>
   Cities Take Sides in Soft-Drink War
</P>
<P>
   To raise money, nearly a dozen cities have sold the exclusive
rights to soft-drink sales on their property to Coca-Cola or
PepsiCo. In addition to eliminating competition, the soft-drink
companies hope the access will allow them to build customer loyalty
and create a sense of goodwill in the community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
