<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PLO-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS ARREST SIGNERS OF ATTACK ON ARAFAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Palestinian Authority arrested seven prominent
Palestinians on Sunday after they signed a statement accusing
Yasser Arafat's administration of ``tyranny and corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the strongest crackdown by the Palestinians to date on
peaceful dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The protest statement, distributed on Saturday, was signed by 20
influential academics and political leaders, including nine members
of the Palestinian Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alarm bells should sound in every village, town and refugee
camp, and in every corner, shop, home and office,'' they wrote.
``Our homeland is being sold out, and our people are being
betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us join together to confront this tyranny and
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Though accusations of corruption are often aired in opposition
circles, the statement was notable for the prestige of the signers,
who include several legislators for Arafat's own Fatah political
faction.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual direct attack on Arafat himself was even more
striking. They accused him of ``opening the door to opportunists
who are spreading corruption throughout Palestinian society.''
</P>
<P>
   In raids beginning at midnight and continuing through midday
Sunday, Palestinian security agents in Nablus and Ramallah seized
five of the signers: two doctors, a writer, an economist and a
university professor. The professor's computer and some of his
personal papers were confiscated, associates said.
</P>
<P>
   Two others were placed under house arrest, including Bassam
Shakaa, a popular former mayor of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
   The government ``was surprised by this statement, because it was
the most direct statement yet of its kind,'' said Abdel-Jawad
Saleh, one of the legislators who signed the document. ``They have
been trying to keep these feelings quiet through intimidation, and
this statement knocked those barriers down. By their actions today,
they are trying to put those barriers back up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not known whether further arrests were contemplated. The
nine legislators are legally protected against prosecution, but
they were told privately Sunday that Arafat may ask the council to
strip them of their immunity.
</P>
<P>
   No formal charges have yet been filed, but Palestinian security
officials acknowledged that the arrests were an effort to squelch
public criticism of the Arafat government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very dangerous these days,'' said one
security official. ``We are in the middle of final status
negotiations. This is not the right time to demand accountability.
There are other ways for constructive criticism, in the parliament
and in other institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian human rights organization, LAW, condemned the
arrests as ``a grave violation of the right to freedom of
expression'' and called for the immediate release of the five
arrested men. ``The illegal measures taken are not based on any
warrants issued by court,'' the group said in a statement Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary detention without charges is permitted under
Palestinian law, however, legal analysts noted. The arrest order
was reportedly issued by Ghazi Jabali, the Gaza-based Palestinian
police chief and a close Arafat confidant. He refused to comment on
Sunday's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider these arrests to be political, and we demand their
release,'' said Hasam Khrasheh, a Palestinian legislator who also
signed the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be happy to face trial, so that the judiciary could
take a decision without political interference,'' Khrasheh said,
referring to the lawmakers who signed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its statement, the group also voiced frustration with
Palestinian economic stagnation and the slow pace of peace talks
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian leadership said after Oslo that the agreement
with Israel would create a state with Jerusalem as its capital,
bring back refugees to their homeland, dismantle settlements,
release prisoners and lay the economic foundation for us to become
the Singapore of the region,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, after six years of Oslo, more land has been stolen, the
settlements have expanded, there are back-room deals over the cause
of the refugees, and Palestinian jails are locking their doors on
our sons. And we don't have Jerusalem, and we are not Singapore.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the direct accusation of corruption that was viewed
as the trigger for Sunday's punitive action. Legislators complain
that as much as a fifth of the government's revenues do not appear
in the budgets that they are asked to pass into law, and Western
government donors to the Palestinians have echoed those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is money that the president is taking, and nobody knows
how it is being spent,'' Saleh asserted Sunday, referring to
Arafat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
