<HEADLINE>
HORRY HAVING TROUBLE CRACKING LAKERS LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This just in: Robert Horry is still a Laker.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you were uncertain, what with Horry seeming to have fallen
off the Los Angeles Lakers' radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   But the 6-foot-10 forward is alive and well, even if out of any
perceptible rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Horry is finding playing time difficult to come by. Bothered by
chronically sore knees, he missed the start of the season,
struggled when he returned, and gets inconsistent playing time off
Phil Jackson's bench.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a small forward who started on Houston's two
championship clubs in 1994 and 1995, executive vice president Jerry
West envisioned Horry as the perfect complementary outside piece to
Shaquille O'Neal. In 1996, Horry averaged 12 points and 5.8
rebounds per game, while connecting on 142 3-pointers for the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Horry, however, has not been the same player as a Laker. Last
year he was converted to power forward with mixed results. This
season he is shooting just 33 percent from the field, and has
missed on his only three 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite averaging only 14 minutes per game, Horry said he is not
frustrated at trying to win Jackson's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope, not at all,'' Horry said. ``I think it's one of those
situations where everybody has to get used to everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you do (have to win a new coach's confidence),
sometimes you don't. I think he's trying to get a feel for what I
can do, and I'm just trying to get a feel for what he's looking
for. We're feeling each other out.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry said his knees have improved, but said it with both
wrapped in ice after Sunday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel good now _ I haven't been playing,'' he said. ``They
bother me a little bit, every now and then. I've been doing the
right things to keep them healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry said the trouble stems from ``too many days growing up,
playing on concrete. I should have spent more time inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have been looking for someone to spark an
underachieving bench, and Horry would seem a likely candidate. Yet
it's hard to have an impact or develop a rhythm when the playing
time is so irregular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to be patient,'' Horry said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting your guard up: With Tyronn Lue eligible to come off the
injured list but still out with a sore knee, and Brian Shaw sitting
on the sidelines Sunday at practice with a sprained ankle, Jackson
started preparing rookie Devean George.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played almost exclusively today at guard,'' Jackson said.
``He has a hard time coming in and focusing right now. He has kinda
rookie-itis thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to come here and focus all the time and look at
this as a chance to be a proving ground. He thinks the game is his
chance. We're still working on that aspect, for him to come to
practice and get something from practice he can carry through to a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   George, never shy about putting it up, is averaging 3.8 points
per game, while shooting .438 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Layups: Forward Travis Knight cut the bottom of his chin during
practice and left to have stitches: ``I hit somebody's head.'' ...
Lue practiced without difficulty and is close to being activated.
Then Jackson will have to determine if he can keep both rookie John
Celestand and Lue on the roster. Said Jackson: ``There are a lot of
small guards in this league now. We could possibly have them
together. I haven't made that as a declaration yet. I'm still
looking at that as a possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
