<HEADER>
A3340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-28 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS AND PUNDITS HOLD ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBC-TOP25) 
 (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In six days the computers will make it official: top-ranked and
11-0 Florida State vs. No. 2 and 11-0 Virginia Tech for the
national championship in the Sugar Bowl. In 12 days, Heisman voters
will do the same: Ron Dayne of Wisconsin will win the trophy as the
best college football player of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But should those things happen?
</P>
<P>
   Before that is answered, here are some mysteries that show that
this season has hardly played to form. On the pleasant side, there
are the remarkable turnarounds that landed Hawaii, Boston College
and Stanford in bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   With 19 starters back from a Hawaii team that went 0-12 last
year, the new coach, June Jones, installed the run-and-shoot
offense and led the Rainbow Warriors (8-4) into the Oahu Bowl
against Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since the seniors were able to walk
around the field and then come back for another game,'' the
sophomore guard Manly Kanoa III said after Hawaii lost Saturday at
home, 22-14, to Washington State. ``These seniors are awesome. They
deserve one last game to go out as winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years removed from a gambling scandal and after
back-to-back 4-7 seasons, Boston College (8-3) will face Oklahoma
in the Insight.com Bowl. How unlikely is that? Coach Tom O'Brien
recalled that when he asked one of his seniors what he thought of
the Eagles' chances after they concluded spring practice, tight end
Bryan Arndt deadpanned, ``I hope the freshmen are good.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is Stanford (8-3), which got blown out by Texas,
69-17, in its opener and lost to lowly San Jose State, 44-39, but
is bound for the Rose Bowl as the Pacific-10 champion against Dayne
and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it shows you our heart and character,'' wide
receiver Troy Walters said after the Cardinals outlasted Notre Dame
on Saturday, 40-37. ``We could have easily thrown in the towel.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing side of the mystery ledger is just as crowded.
Remember the pre-season credibility invested in Arizona's national
title aspirations? The Wildcats lost to Arizona State, 42-27, on
Saturday, finished 6-6 and won't play in a bowl. For nine weeks,
Penn State too had designs on the national championship until three
consecutive losses have the Nittany Lions remembering the Alamo _
the bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Notre Dame, whose loss to Stanford sent the Irish
(5-7) to their first losing season in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt we've ever given up as many big plays as we've given
up this year,'' Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie said after the Stanford
game. ``When you can't cover and you self-destruct and turn the
ball over, you can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing those teams and players have in common is that their
destinies were decided on the field. It's not clear yet if Virginia
Tech and Ron Dayne can say the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia Tech somehow doesn't make it to the title game, it
will be a shame and rightfully blamed on computers. If Dayne
doesn't win the Heisman, it will be unfortunate and the human
voters will have to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies are in limbo because of the Bowl Championship Series
ranking, a mathematical formula that determines the No. 1 and No. 2
teams to match them in a championship game. Because the formula
includes eight computer rankings, the BCS' No. 3 team, Nebraska,
clings to an ever-so-slight possibility of bumping Virginia Tech
from the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers have lost once, but some computer rankings
reward their tougher schedule. To sustain the suspense, Nebraska
needs to avenge its loss to Texas in the Big 12 title game on
Saturday. The Cornhuskers would benefit by doing so in
running-up-the-score fashion after needing overtime to beat
Colorado, 33-30, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Nebraska does win big, BCS officials are in for a tense
Saturday night wondering whether artificial intelligence will
override the votes and wisdom of the coaches and news media polls _
also components of the formula _ both of which say Virginia Tech is
the No. 2 team.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Dayne wins the Heisman has more to do with style than
substance. He's a big, hard runner who broke the career rushing
record set by Ricky Williams of Texas last year. He isn't
particularly highlight-reel friendly and doesn't have a colorful
tale to engage reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne doesn't excite the same constituencies that like big-play
sparks and have touted the candidacies of Florida State wide
receiver Peter Warrick, Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton or
even Virginia Tech quarterback Michael Vick, who developed a
belated following as a Heisman contender.
</P>
<P>
   But each player's campaign ran into trouble. Warrick
participated in a shopping scam that led to a misdemeanor guilty
plea and cost him a two-game suspension. Hamilton's chances were
snuffed when Georgia Tech lost for the third time, to mediocre Wake
Forest. Vick was noticed only late in the season and is penalized
for being a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest knock against Dayne is that the Heisman isn't a
career achievement reward but a trophy for the season's best
player. Yes, he broke Williams' record, but he also rushed for
1,834 yards and 19 touchdowns this year and led the Badgers (9-2)
to the Rose Bowl as Big Ten champions for the second consecutive
year. Those are pretty good numbers in a pretty good season.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the focus is kept on the field, there really isn't much
mystery left in this season.
</P>
<P>
   Only Nebraska fans can honestly believe that their 10-1 team
deserves a chance to play Florida State for the title. Despite the
human hand-wringing, the computers will compute the right thing and
send Virginia Tech to the Sugar Bowl, just as voters will vote the
right way and award the Heisman Trophy to Dayne. This is the era,
after all, in which mankind is in harmony with technology, isn't
it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECONOMY-MARKETPLACE-7     11-28 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-MARKETPLACE-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EYE ON THE ECONOMY, TO 2000 AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ With about a month left in the millennium, the three
major stock indexes are poised to record annual returns of more
than 10 percent each for the fifth year in a row _ an unprecedented
streak.
</P>
<P>
   But the wealth generated by the indexes' gains may also pose the
biggest threat to a repeat performance in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If the indexes keep rising, some economists argue, the stock
market will continue to fuel consumer spending. Such buying makes
it unlikely that the economy, which surged at a 5.5 percent annual
growth rate in the third quarter, will slow enough to satisfy
Federal Reserve policy-makers. The Fed will then be forced to raise
short-term interest rates, adding to its three quarter-point
increases since June. And higher rates could spook equity investors
if they conclude that the economy and earnings growth will finally
slow significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stock market continues to go up at the rate we have had
in the last couple of months, the Fed will be unhappy and raise
interest rates,'' said Stephen Slifer, the chief U.S. economist at
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average has jumped almost 1,000 points,
or 9.7 percent, in six weeks. In the same period, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's index of 500 stocks is up 13.6 percent , while the Nasdaq
index has surged 26.2 percent. In light holiday trading Friday, the
Dow slipped 19.26 points to 10,988.91, while the S&AMP;P 500 fell 0.46
point, to 1,416.62. But the Nasdaq rose 27.31 points to a new high
of 3,447.81.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were higher earlier in the day after the government
reported that personal income jumped 1.3 percent in October, the
largest monthly gain in five and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Slifer suspects that these rallies have given a new impetus to
consumer spending and housing construction, and in turn may reverse
the slight slowing in economic growth that was reflected in flat
retail sales in September and October, a slowdown in automobile
sales those months and a plunge in new home sales in September.
</P>
<P>
   While he cannot be sure yet, he sees possible signs of new
economic vigor in the jump in the consumer confidence index back to
its recent highs and the return to the highs of this summer in the
home purchase index.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are seeing a few signs of slower growth right now,''
he said, ``if these new signals are right, we will see faster
growth a couple of months down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, he said, he is tempted to raise his already
strong outlook of 4.3 percent growth for the fourth quarter and is
considering the addition of a Fed rate increase to his 2000
forecast. He had expected the increase earlier this month to be the
last for the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., has
already added a Fed rate increase to his forecast. ``I think the
economy is going to remain strong through all of next year,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Fed raised its interest rate target on federal funds,
which is the rate banks lend money to one another overnight, a
quarter of a percentage point to 5.5 percent on Nov. 16, bond
investors have worried about the persistent strength in the economy
and the possibility of more rate increases. But stock investors do
not appear to have skipped a beat.
</P>
<P>
   The divergence in views is obvious in the markets' performance.
Since then, the Nasdaq index has moved to six new highs, the S&AMP;P
500 to two and the Dow, until Friday, was back to more than 11,000
points the first time since Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   But the bond market has sold off. In a short day of trading
Friday, the price of the 30-year bond fell 13/32, while the yield,
which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 6.23 percent from
6.20 percent Wednesday and 6.02 percent the day before the Fed rate
increase. The yield on the two-year note, which is more sensitive
to the threat of a Fed rate move, rose Friday to 5.98 percent from
5.94 percent Wednesday and 5.75 percent before the Fed's action.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that has blunted fears about a strong economy next
year is the belief that the Federal Reserve's speed limit for
acceptable growth has risen. While no one knows the actual number,
analysts suspect it is about 3 percent to 3.5 percent, rather than
the 2 percent to 2.5 percent of years past. The reason for the
change is a sharp rise in productivity, which means workers are
producing more goods at the same cost and keeping inflation
pressures more subdued.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg expects the gross domestic product to grow 3.7 percent
next year, while Slifer sees a more modest 3.4 percent. So the
economy may attain an acceptable level without more rate increases.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But if growth in the fourth quarter comes in as expected at more
than 4 percent, the pace of the last six months will be about 5
percent. And assuming that the economy will be easy to slow
contradicts its performance over the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers signaled this problem in the statement that
accompanied their last rate increase. ``Despite tentative evidence
of a slowing in certain interest-sensitive sectors of the economy
and of accelerating productivity,'' they said, ``the expansion of
activity continues in excess of the economy's growth potential. As
a consequence, the pool of available workers willing to take jobs
has been drawn down further in recent months, a trend that must
eventually be contained if inflationary imbalances are to remain in
check and economic expansion continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers added that the three rate increases this year,
along with the rise in market interest rates, ``should markedly
diminish the risk of inflation going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Slifer, who has been confident that prices are in check, admits
to ``getting a tad nervous'' as he looks at the recent rise in the
prices of oil and new and used cars. ``We are pushing this envelope
as far as we can push it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
