<SLUG> BC-WTO-LOGS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WANTS TARIFFS ABOLISHED ON WOOD PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sidebar to WTO-Environment)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT McCLURE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Somewhere behind the posturing and speechifying of the
World Trade Organization conference this week, the ministers might
actually agree on something: abolishing border taxes on logs, wood
products and paper.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you believe, such an agreement could mean more
jobs for U.S. workers, cheaper housing worldwide and increased
environmental protections; or it could mean more endangered
species, fewer jobs for U.S. workers and, in the Third World,
flooding, landslides, hobbled agriculture and ruined fishing.
</P>
<P>
   United States trade representatives are pushing hard for what
they call ``accelerated tariff liberalization'' and what
environmentalists term a ``global free logging agreement.'' It
would phase out all tariffs on wood, wood products and paper goods
almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an economic standpoint, it would be promoting highly
inefficient trade and it would be ecologically damaging,'' contends
Dave Batker, an economist with the Asia Pacific Environmental
Exchange. He points out that forests help provide clean water that
nourishes farm crops and keeps fisheries healthy, and also help
stabilize hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``These forests provide economically valuable services. We need
to measure the value of those services versus having a little more
wood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Counters Toby Murray of the Murray Pacific Corporation in
Tacoma, Wash., a member of Washington's Forest Practices Board:
``When free markets are opened up, wealth flows. When wealth flows,
the environmental standards start going up.''
</P>
<P>
   World trade in paper, timber and other ``forest products'' has
quadrupled since 1970. This new proposal would accelerate that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Abolishing tariffs on wood products would boost timber-cutting
worldwide by half a percentage point during the next decade, the
Clinton administration estimated in a report released earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   There would be little effect on the amount of lumber cut in the
United States, but U.S. exports of some finished ``value-added''
products such as some paper and board products would increase,
while U.S. exports of raw logs and wood chips would probably
decline, administration economists project.
</P>
<P>
   The effect overseas? Depends on where you live. Malaysia might
see timber-cutting increase 2.6 percent and Indonesia 4.4 percent.
Mexico could expect logging to fall 2.1 percent and Russia 4.1
percent, the report estimated. The largest increases in timbering
would be Sweden's 7.6 percent and Finland's 11 percent, with those
boosts coming out of timber plantations rather than natural
old-growth forests, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admittedly, overall it is a small increase,'' says Dan
Seligman, the Sierra Club's point person on the WTO. ``But more
importantly, logging will increase in some of the world's most
threatened and fragile rain forests, such as Indonesia and
Malaysia.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the biggest fear of environmental activists is that
once tariffs are eliminated, trade ministers will start talking
about trimming back so-called ``non-tariff barriers to trade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be the Endangered Species Act. That could be the
Northwest Forest Plan,'' charges Marty Bergoffen of the Southern
Appalachian Biodiversity Project. ``That could be anything that
keeps them from cutting as many trees as they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists also worry that the WTO could eventually target U.S.
laws requiring a certain percentage of recycled material in
government-purchased paper goods, overrule U.S. requirements to
label wood and paper products as ``eco-friendly'' and force the
importation of wood products with invasive pests.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials contend that they will be able to
maintain U.S. laws, although they do acknowledge non-tariff
barriers including environmental laws could well become part of
negotiations once tariffs are killed.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the touchiest possibility raised by this is abolishing
U.S. laws barring the export of logs cut on public property in the
United States. The laws were passed to protect the jobs of U.S.
millworkers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ban has been in place for a decade, Japan considers
it protectionist and has threatened to raise it in negotiations.
Could the ban someday be overturned?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an open question,'' said a senior Clinton
administration official. ``It is a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically, that poses problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an esoteric concept. This is food on people's
tables in my community,'' said Washington state Rep. Hans Dunshee,
D-Snohomish. ``Those are public trees for a public purpose, and a
public purpose is not sending jobs to Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Washington tree exporters point out that many of their
number are small- to medium-sized family-run operations, and that
exporting trees does provide jobs for dockworkers.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, the Tacoma tree grower and exporter, said being able to
send his best wood overseas for top dollar enables him to afford
environmental protections here. For example, he said, he must agree
not to cut 18 percent of his trees. In a family-run operation such
as his, a drop in profits might force him to sell his land, Murray
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmental protections and set-asides are very expensive.
Don't hit me from the other end on price,'' he said. ``You can
drive around and see plenty of places that were forested a month
ago that are growing houses today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-NY     11-28 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS KEEP THE PUNCHLESS PATRIOTS IN NOVEMBER FREE FALL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ A month ago the Patriots were one of the
teams to beat in the American Football Conference East. They raced
out to a 6-2 record and were riding high on a wave of confidence
they felt would carry them into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots team that played Buffalo here Sunday afternoon did
not resemble that squad from four weeks ago. And the Bills
exploited the difference, taking a 17-7 victory in a crucial AFC
East game that puts Buffalo (8-4) in third place in the division
behind Indianapolis (9-2) and Miami (8-3). New England (6-5), loser
of three AFC East games in a row, is now ahead of just the Jets
(4-7) in the division and gasping for air as it tries to make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go back to work, hang together and create our
offense again, because right now we don't have anything that is
giving us a chance to win football games,'' New England Coach Pete
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   That lab work will start with quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who is
playing like a gun-shy gunslinger. Bledsoe was sacked six times and
threw one interception against the Bills Sunday. That is an
improvement from his game against the Dolphins last week when he
threw five interceptions and was sacked five times. In the
three-game losing streak, Bledsoe has eight interceptions and has
been sacked 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty down,'' Bledsoe said. ``To lose three weeks in a
row and feel like you're ultimately responsible is a very
depressing and disheartening thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills knew exactly how to make Bledsoe blue. They rushed
five, played bump-and-run, man-to-man coverage on the two outside
receivers and dropped the remaining defenders into zone coverage
deep in the middle. They wanted to limit the big plays by New
England's receivers, particularly Terry Glenn. Buffalo conceded
very little, but what it did give, Bledsoe was not inclined to
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw on film that he's holding the ball longer,'' said
Buffalo defensive tackle Ted Washington, who had two sacks. ``He's
trying to make the big play. He's trying to carry the team. He
can't do that. He's trying to be the man. He needs to get help from
the rest of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe completed 18 of 34 for 205 yards and his lone big play
came too late in the game to matter when he hit Glenn on a 45-yard
touchdown pass that made it 17-7 with 2 minutes 41 seconds to play.
He said his recent woes are a combination of his receivers not
getting open quickly and his not being able to get them the ball
quickly enough for them to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were not that efficient on offense, either, but they
did enough to win. Buffalo jumped out to a 3-0 lead on a 28-yard
field goal by Steve Christie late in the first quarter. Early in
the second, the Patriots were trying to answer that score when
Bledsoe's pass to Troy Brown was intercepted by Bills cornerback
Ken Irvin at the Buffalo 17-yard line. That was the first New
England scoring chance that was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second quarter, Bills quarterback Doug Flutie saw
that receiver Eric Moulds had a step on Patriots cornerback Steve
Israel. By the time Flutie released the ball, Israel had slipped at
the Patriots' 40-yard line and Moulds was wide open. He caught the
ball and scored on a 54-yard pass play, which helped give Buffalo a
10-0 lead before the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric got an outside release on him so I tried to lay it up
over him and as I released it the defensive man started to
stumble,'' said Flutie, who was nine of 16 for 207 yards and two
touchdowns with no interceptions. ``I thought I might have
overthrown it, but Eric ran it down and got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Patriots went through a complete remodeling in the
locker room at the half, nothing from the first half suggested that
they had a chance to beat Buffalo in the second half. Late in the
third quarter, Patriots running back Kevin Faulk fumbled at the
Bills' 8 on first-and-goal from the 6-yard line. Buffalo linebacker
Sam Rogers recovered it at the 8.
</P>
<P>
   New England was flat, listless and inept on offense. And when
Bills fullback Sam Gash, a former Patriot, pushed his way past
Patriots linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer on a 31-yard touchdown pass
play to help make it 17-0 with 10:21 remaining in the third
quarter, the New England defense could be placed in the same
category as its offense.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 100th victory of the decade for Buffalo, one of the
most resilient franchises in the National Football League. But it
was bigger than that, particularly in light of the fact that
Buffalo has a bye on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This win puts us in position that it gives us separation from
New England,'' Flutie said. ``It keeps us within striking distance
of the AFC East title. We won't lose next week, but some teams
might.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
