<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-SENATE-RACE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTATORS TURN TO GIULIANI FOR DECISION ON SENATE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armed with Hillary Rodham Clinton's announcement last
week that she is committed to running for the U.S. Senate in New
York next year, commentators on Sunday morning television news
programs and advisers to the first lady sought to turn up the
pressure Sunday on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to formally declare his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   With the election nearly a year away, the New York Senate race
continues to dominate the weekend programs on network and cable
television, and on program after program Sunday, commentators
questioned when Giuliani would announce his bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Rudy Giuliani definitely be a candidate for the U.S.
Senate from New York?'' asked Tim Russert, the host of the NBC
program ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   The commentators were spurred on by the Clinton camp. On
separate programs, Mrs. Clinton's chief political adviser, Harold
Ickes, and a media adviser, Mandy Grunwald, both demanded that
Giuliani state his intentions. Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, Howard
Wolfson, reiterated those demands and issued a news release that
goaded the mayor, asking, ``What is he afraid of?''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, the director of Giuliani's Senate exploratory
committee, appearing on ``Meet the Press,'' said the mayor would
not be pressured and would make a decision ``in due time.'' But
later in the day, as the chorus grew louder, Teitelbaum said Mrs.
Clinton had been forced to state her plans because of doubts about
her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been suggested by many people that Mrs. Clinton made her
announcement with her intention to announce because of her
plummeting poll numbers, disarray in her campaign and defections
from her own party,'' he said. ``We don't find ourselves in the
same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The continuing news media attention to the New York Senate race
is unusual considering that neither Mrs. Clinton, a Democrat, nor
Giuliani, a Republican, is expected to face a primary challenge,
while in the presidential race, highly competitive primaries in
both parties will begin within three months.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mrs. Clinton nor Giuliani appeared on any of the
programs Sunday, but their surrogates were out in full force,
hammering away at issues like abortion, security for Israel,
campaign finance, health care and negative advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson appeared on ``Fox News Sunday.'' Sen. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J., supported the first lady on ABC's ``This Week'' while Sen.
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., went on to speak out for Giuliani.
Teitelbaum appeared with Ms. Grunwald on ``Meet the Press.'' And
Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough president and close friend
of the mayor's, faced Ickes on ``CNN Live.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nearly every program raised the issue of the first lady's
appearance earlier this month with Suha Arafat, the wife of the
Palestinian Authority president, Yasser Arafat, and Mrs. Clinton's
silence as Mrs. Arafat accused Israel of poisoning Palestinian
women and children with toxic gases. Wolfson defended the first
lady and accused Giuliani's supporters of wanting Mrs. Clinton to
cause a diplomatic debacle by reacting to Mrs. Arafat's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum denied suggesting that Mrs. Clinton should have made
a scene. ``There are times when it is appropriate and even
necessary to stand up and put down that kind of anti-Semitic,
anti-Israel rhetoric,'' he said. ``And the fact is that Mrs.
Clinton failed to respond in a timely and forceful action. Mayor
Giuliani would have acted completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the programs also took up abortion. Although Mrs.
Clinton and Giuliani both favor abortion rights, one question is
whether Giuliani will change his view on a form of late-term
abortion. Giuliani has opposed banning the procedure and has
suggested he will not change that position, but support for a ban
could win him the endorsement of the New York State Conservative
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is a very principled person, and right now the mayor
is pro-choice,'' Teitelbaum said. ``He believes in a woman's right
to choose. That's his position, and that's his position and it
hasn't changed, and the mayor believes what he believes in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
