<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-JACKIE-BOS &LR;      11-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JACKIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JACKIE' LOOKS GOOD DESPITE ALL ITS FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
JACKIE: BEHIND THE MYTH 
Directed by: Suzanne Bauman 
On: PBS, Monday at 9 p.m. 
Rating: TV-G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jacqueline Kennedy was just 34 years old when John F. Kennedy
was assassinated, awfully young to be cast as an icon of grief in a
shattering national psychodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that she spent the next three decades trying to
forge an identity beyond the First Widow role that many would have
been happy to see her play indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The patent goal of ``Jackie: Behind the Myth,'' a two-hour
documentary airing at 9 p.m. on PBS, is to remind us that Jackie
went on without Jack, not just raising her two children but
becoming a respected book editor who worked on nearly 100 books
over 16 years, and continuing the passionate advocacy of the arts
that began during her White House years.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers deserve credit for enlarging the lens to
encompass Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis's life, not just the White
House years. Still, any film that promises to get ``behind the
myth'' should make more of an effort to do so, rather than just
enshrine the myth. Ultimately, this is a biography that falls down
the slippery slope into hagiography.
</P>
<P>
   However flawed ``Jackie'' may be as a documentary, though,
there's no denying that Onassis shines as a subject. She had an
idiosyncratic beauty and a little-girl voice that belied a steely
strength. The images of her make this film compulsively watchable
even at its most cloying. Director Suzanne Bauman takes full
advantage of the fact that few public figures have been more
photographed, or more photogenic, than Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of images includes not just the familiar ones but
pictures of Onassis as a young debutante in Paris, nourishing a
hunger for culture, and wandering through the capital in 1952 as
the ``inquiring photographer'' for the Washington Times-Herald, in
which occupation she met JFK. ``I think I look up to newspaper
people the way you join movie-star fan clubs when you're 10 years
old,'' Onassis said at that time. Chances are her opinion changed
in later life when she became a favorite target of the paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie'' might have benefited from a tough-minded analysis of
the artifice behind the art form Onassis made of public
appearances. (Surely Diana, Princess of Wales, learned a thing or
two from her example.) While the documentary explains how JFK's
widow orchestrated his funeral into a powerfully moving pageant, it
passes over the way she wrapped a posthumous aura of ``Camelot''
around his administration _ defining its image for the ages _ by
telling reporter Theodore White of the slain president's fondness
for the musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie'' does reward viewers with some unstaged moments that
pierce the enigma, as when Onassis, an accomplished equestrienne,
displays unalloyed joy while watching a horse show in Pakistan.
It's easy to see why Parisians were captivated by her after
witnessing her interview with a French TV reporter on the White
House lawn, which she conducted in fluent French, to pave the way
for a trip to France.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a philandering father, Onassis would go on to
marry a philandering husband. How did she cope with the pain of it?
How did she reconcile her own personal dignity and accomplishment
with the humiliation of being cheated on?
</P>
<P>
   Exploring these questions could offer clues to her character,
but viewers who turn to ``Jackie'' for answers will be
disappointed. The film touches glancingly on the subject of JFK's
infidelities and then skitters away, as if afraid to tamper with
the portrait of martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   She will, of course, be forever linked to JFK, despite this
documentary's laudable attempt to present a fuller portrait. But
looking at the old black-and-white footage of the White House years
in ``Jackie,'' it is intriguing to see how she seemed less stilted
and more natural when she appeared in public alone, without JFK.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the throat-catching moments are all here: Jackie's
massive dignity in the wake of her husband's murder, and the moment
when that stoicism crumbled as she dropped her head, sobbing, while
his funeral cortege passed by; the picture of the dazed widow
standing next to Lyndon Johnson while he took the presidential
oath; John-John pulling at her pearls, and later, offering that
immortal salute to his father. ``Jackie'' also offers an absorbing
glimpse into the mutual respect between the president's widow and
his successor, LBJ. Her personality is sketched in anecdotes
supplied by such onetime Kennedy aides as John Kenneth Galbraith
and Pierre Salinger, and from musicians Andre Previn and Isaac
Stern.
</P>
<P>
   The film passes quickly over her marriage to Aristotle Onassis,
and does not mention her relationship with New York
journalist/novelist Pete Hamill. The latter seems an odd omission
for a film (produced by WNET in New York) that focuses so intently
on Onassis's years in New York, including a lengthy segment on her
efforts to prevent the construction of an office tower at Grand
Central Station.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from the testimony of the authors, artists, and
preservationists with whom she worked in the last two decades of
her life that Onassis remained a compelling presence and a loyal
friend. Without question, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis was worthy of
great admiration, if not the uncritical worship of this
documentary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
