<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDAHO-CROSS-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDAHO CHRISTIANS RALLY ROUND A CROSS ON A HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ore.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ For 43 years, a 60-foot white cross has stood
like a Christian beacon on the eastern skyline of this city.
</P>
<P>
   Lighted at night, the cross looms 1,000 feet over Boise atop a
bluff called Table Rock. On any given day, Christians visit the
cross to pray, sing or shout hallelujah to the setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   No one objected when the Idaho Jaycees built the cross on public
land in 1956. To avoid a potential constitutional challenge from
the American Civil Liberties Union, the Jaycees bought the tiny
spit of land on which the cross sits for $100 in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Rob Sherman, a Chicago talk-radio host and an
atheist, ignited a passionate debate here in a speech to Idaho
atheists by suggesting that the land transaction was rigged and
that a federal lawsuit should be filed to bring down the cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's blatantly unconstitutional,'' said Sherman, a former
spokesman for the American Atheists Inc., a nonprofit group that
promotes separation of church and state. ``Whenever government
editorializes about religion by putting a religious symbol on
public land, it creates a climate of bigotry, intolerance, hatred
and tyranny against non-Christians in general and against atheists
in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's statements galvanized an outpouring of support for the
cross.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, the police said, 10,000 people marched
down Capitol Boulevard carrying ``Save the Cross'' signs and
singing religious music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a symbol of peace, and at night it's real
pretty,'' said Laura Hogan, 10, of Boise.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have seized the issue as a political opportunity in
a largely conservative state.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Butch Otter, a Republican who is running for the House
seat being vacated by Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, said at
Saturday's rally that the cross was protected because it was on
private property.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to build a church, if you want to start a
religion, go get yourself a piece of private property,'' Otter
said. ``That's how it is, and that's the way it should be, and
that's the way that cross is up on that hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Dirk Kempthorne, a Republican, pledged to support the
cross, as did Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``The separation of church and state was never intended to
suggest or promote atheism,'' Kempthorne wrote in a Nov. 23 letter
to the Jaycees.
</P>
<P>
   In Rocky Mountain political terms, Sherman has hit two hot
buttons: Westerners do not take kindly to outsiders telling them
what to do, and property rights are considered sacrosanct here.
</P>
<P>
   Letters to the editor in local newspapers have been running
10-to-1 in support of the cross. Talk radio stations have buzzed
with irate callers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Larry Butler, a truck driver, got so mad when Sherman challenged
the cross that he has used donated lumber to make and distribute
7,000 small crosses. ``I'm going to be a thorn in Rob Sherman's
side from now on,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   A few opponents have politely noted that the cross is not a
universal religious symbol. ``Regardless of the legalities of the
case, Boiseans should know that for a minority of its citizens, the
everyday sight of that cross is highly distressing,'' said Martin
Seidenfeld, who has lived in Boise for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cronin, a new Boise resident who recently worked at the
Jaycees' world headquarters in Miami, says the Idaho Jaycees ought
to reconsider. ``For Buddhists, Jews, Muslims and other
non-Christians in Boise,'' Cronin said, ``the cross only drives
home the point that they are strangers in a strange land.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the issues of diversity and tolerance have been on the
front burner in Boise lately. Corporations like Hewlett Packard and
Micron Technology have expressed concern about their ability to
recruit workers, because Idaho is sometimes seen as a refuge for
white supremacists and racists.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is not limited to Idaho. American Atheists Inc. is
challenging a 109-foot cross on Mount Davidson near San Francisco.
A cross on public land in Eugene, Ore., has already been removed
after a challenge by the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jaycees here vowed to stand their ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our cross,'' said Eric Landaluce, president of the
Idaho Jaycees. ``I challenge Rob Sherman to take this all the way
to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
