<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BULLYING THE HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Away from the parade, hunched in doorways or curled
up in boxes soggy from the steady rain, the street people passed
the Thanksgiving holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Some were lucky enough to catch a meal at a soup kitchen. Some
reaped a small bonanza in donations from passers-by in a holiday
mood. But others, less fortunate, were rousted and handcuffed and
taken away to jail.
</P>
<P>
   New York's current mayor, as cold a politician as you'll ever
see, has chosen this moment in the city's history, this moment of
great prosperity and good cheer, to sic the police on the homeless.
So on the day after Thanksgiving, you had the following headline in
Newsday: ``Arrests Feed Anger of Homeless.'' And in the Daily News:
``The mayor targets us like prey, say needy.''
</P>
<P>
   And even in The Post, as good a friend as the mayor is likely to
find, you had a homeless man named Harry Reynolds quoted as saying:
``It's a shame! I'm not on crack. I'm not mentally ill. I just
could not afford to pay rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Giuliani's latest approach to the devastating problem of
homelessness is not just cruel, it's incoherent. A month ago he was
threatening to throw people out of the homeless shelters and onto
the streets if they refused to work. Now he's got the police
arresting people who are on the streets for refusing to go to a
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   This is not policy-making. This is not a reasoned attempt to
deal with a complex problem. It's a mayor with a whip lashing out
blindly at some of the weakest, most troubled people in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those arrested are back on the streets a day later, back
to the cardboard box or the dark alley or the tiny corner of a park
that they've turned into a wretched approximation of home. I doubt
that a night in jail has made them any wiser, or the city any
safer. What it does, according to homeless advocates, is make the
street people a lot more frightened. Perhaps the mayor, who has
bullied people throughout his public career, thinks that's just
what they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   This official assault on the homeless is the mayor's response to
the attack on Nicole Barrett, who was almost killed by a man who
smashed her skull with a paving stone at a midtown intersection on
Nov. 16. Witnesses said the man might have been homeless, and it is
generally assumed he was mentally ill. New Yorkers were both
chilled and saddened by the apparently random attack, and many were
angered. But there is no sense that the public supports an
arbitrary crackdown on the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by New York 1 News last week found that 77 percent of
respondents opposed the arrest of homeless people who refuse
shelter. And several members of the clergy have let it be known
that they do not want the police to disturb homeless people who
seek refuge outside their churches.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Holy Apostles on Ninth Avenue in the Chelsea
section of Manhattan, which runs the city's largest soup kitchen,
was especially vehement in its response to the mayor's actions. It
issued a public statement that assailed the mayor's
``mean-spiritedness'' and asserted: ``The policy of attacking the
most vulnerable of our city in the midst of an economic boom for
the majority is unworthy of the values we celebrate this holiday.
This is another instance of `criminalizing' the homeless, not for
what they have actually done, but for simply who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Homeless advocates have reacted bitterly to the mayor's
crackdown. ``There is no logic here,'' said Mary Brosnahan of the
Coalition for the Homeless. ``It runs counter to everything we've
learned over the past 20 years about how to help the homeless. The
solution is to have legitimate outreach, not outreach with a
sidearm.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani himself has long said he agreed with advocates that the
way to help the homeless who are mentally ill is to get them into
community-based mental health facilities _ residences in which
troubled individuals can receive the services and medication they
need.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of difficult but worthy effort is the opposite of
throwing the homeless in jail.
</P>
<P>
   With his police force at the ready, the mayor now says, ``We're
going to spend a lot of time removing homeless people from the
streets.'' And he speaks contemptuously of those who truly want to
help the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The problem may be complex, but the current policy of the
current mayor is a cold and simple one: Cuff 'em, and lock 'em up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
