</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' VAUNTED DEFENSE HUMBLED IN 34-24 LOSS TO ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Jim Fassel, the New York Giants' coach,
said he was disappointed and accepted blame. Michael Strahan, the
defensive end, said he was shocked. Kerry Collins, the new
quarterback, said he was discouraged and encouraged. Jessie
Armstead, the talkative linebacker, spoke loudly with his absence,
leaving Giants Stadium without comment. Sam Garnes, the strong
safety, said what he saw was ``totally ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   After the most disheartening regular-season loss in Fassel's
Giants tenure, there was no shortage of opinion or angst Sunday in
the Giants' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona Cardinals team with the third worst offense in the
National Football League pushed around the haughty Giants defense,
amassing Arizona's highest point total ever in Giants Stadium. The
Giants' offense blundered its way to four turnovers. A tight,
3-point game in the fourth quarter became a numbing 34-24 Cardinals
rout, a defeat that so dims the Giants' playoff chances that they
are drifting toward the fantasy category.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-6 Giants, who at the midpoint of their season were
first-place contenders, have lost three consecutive games just as
their schedule grows more daunting. After a distracting week that
included a quarterback change, a holiday and the death of Fassel's
mother, the Giants played Sunday without poise or skill on either
side of the ball, a combination that has the team reeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still trying to figure it out,'' Strahan said. ``I don't
know how in the world they scored 34 points. I don't see how it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants lost to the Cardinals at home for just the second
time in 16 years and was swept in the two-game season series
between the teams for the first time in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   With Collins at quarterback the Giants scored more points
Sunday, but the Giants' defenders, who just a week ago were
critical of the team's lack of offensive output, allowed the
Cardinals (5-6) and their spellbinding quarterback Jake Plummer to
steal the game.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer replaced the former Giant quarterback Dave Brown in the
second half and threw for two touchdowns while completing 12 of 18
passes without an interception. Most conspicuously, Plummer and the
Cardinals went after Giants cornerback Phillippi Sparks six times,
and completed a pass each time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, midway through the final quarter, after Collins led the
Giants on an impressive 13-play, 88-yard touchdown drive, Arizona's
lead was just 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a pivotal stop, the Giants' defense, which has talked of
being among the league's elite, stumbled at the worst possible
time. First, it gave up an 11-yard completion from Plummer to Frank
Sanders on a third-and-8 play _ with Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn
just missing an attempt to bat away the pass. On the next down, the
Giants blitzed from Plummer's left, but the shifty quarterback was
already looking to his right, where he had called for a screen
pass.
</P>
<P>
   When Plummer found running back Adrian Murrell in the flat,
there was no Giant in his path for 20 yards. The play gained 23
yards, and five plays later Mario Bates scored on a 2-yard run that
gave the Cardinals a 10-point lead with 4 minutes 16 seconds left
in the game. The teams traded meaningless touchdowns but Arizona's
lead was never seriously threatened.
</P>
<P>
   As porous as the Giants defense looked at game's end, to be
fair, they may have been exhausted from playing all but 3:09 of the
third quarter. Because if the Giants defense lost its chance to aid
the cause in the fourth quarter, the Giants offense squandered its
opportunity in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, starting his first game at Giants Stadium, had opened
the game nervous and hurrying his passes as he completed just 1 of
9. But in the second quarter, Collins connected on 10 of 13 passes
for 141 yards. He scored on a 1-yard touchdown run after an 11-play
drive and moved the Giants 66 yards in less than two minutes as the
Giants took a 10-6 lead on a 24-yard field goal by Cary Blanchard
with six seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Collins had provided hope, if for no other reason than the
promise of talent, his 33-yard pass to Ike Hilliard in the second
quarter _ perfectly thrown over one defender and in front of
another to a streaking Hilliard _ had the Giants Stadium crowd on
its feet cheering the Giants offense, something it hasn't done in
months.
</P>
<P>
   This display might have moved Fassel to try to run away with the
game in the third quarter. Sunday's game was played in blustery
conditions, the wind blowing from east to west across the stadium.
Given the option of taking the wind in the third or final quarter,
Fassel took it in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins' first pass of the second half was deflected and
intercepted by Arizona's Rob Frederickson _ the first Arizona
interception in 21 quarters of play. Plummer turned this into a
touchdown when he threw to wide receiver Rob Moore, who took the
football out of the hands of Sparks in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   On the Giants' next possession, Collins, who completed 22 of 45
passes for 298 yards, scrambled to his right looking for a receiver
when he was sacked from behind by Simeon Rice, who had another
field day running around the Giants left tackle Roman Oben. Rice
stripped Collins of the football and recovered the fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Giants drives in the third quarter lasted no more than
three plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the wind in the third quarter backfired on us
completely,'' Fassel said. ``It was probably the thing that hurt us
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, who on Monday was scheduled to fly to California for his
mother's funeral, seemed to be taking Sunday's loss particularly
hard. Asked to describe his feelings as he prepared the team this
weekend, Fassel said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been difficult to keep my focus. There has been a lot
going on in my mind. Obviously, I didn't do a good enough job for
this team to go out and play. Obviously, it's been a tough week.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fassel wasn't alone when it came to taking blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly can't say anything about the offense when they
score 24 points,'' Garnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Collins: ``We made some nice plays, but I was also sloppy
with the ball and we can't win like that. So I feel encouraged and
I feel exasperated.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Giants, improving on last year's 8-8 record, making the
playoffs, even Fassel's future with the franchise, now hinges on
the final five games _ three of them road games at Buffalo, St.
Louis and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest,'' Collins said of the Giants' playoff
chances. ``We're probably going to have to win them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
