<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-COLLAPSE-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIEF FOR IMMIGRANT WHO LIVED AND DIED FOR HIS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico)  (lb) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his two years in New York, Eduardo Daniel did
little other than work, friends and relatives said. He had plenty
of cousins and friends across the city, Mexican immigrants who,
like him, had arrived to toil and scrimp and save so they could one
day return to their homeland with a tidy nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   But working six days a week as a construction worker didn't
leave Daniel, who lived in Brooklyn, much of a chance to see his
cousins in the Bronx or form bonds with the friends he made at
construction sites. Like countless other illegal immigrants who
come to New York, Daniel came with a specific purpose: to work,
save and go home, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, though, those relatives and friends, accompanied by a
handful of reporters and representatives of a Manhattan law firm,
descended on a small funeral home in Brooklyn from far corners of
the city and from New Jersey to pray, grieve and remember Daniel at
his wake.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old from San Matias Cocoyotla _ a small village in
southern Mexico where poverty has prompted dozens, if not hundreds,
of residents to head for New York _ died last Tuesday when the
unfinished building where he was working in Brooklyn collapsed in a
cascade of steel beams and wet cement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come here and be with family and friends. These
are the times when we must be most united,'' said Augustina Torres,
who arrived from San Matias in 1988 and counts herself as among the
first from the town to make the trek to New York. ``You don't know
how much it hurts to have one of us die here. We consider ourselves
from one family.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel, who sent about $150 a week to his parents and saved the
rest so he could one day build a house in his hometown, will now
return for burial in San Matias Cocoyotla. On Tuesday, his body
will be shipped to Mexico City and then south to the village, in
the parched southern state of Puebla.
</P>
<P>
   In San Matias Cocoyotla, a community of about 5,000, relatives
and townspeople are to conduct a wake for the young worker for at
least two nights.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative plans call for Daniel's coffin to be paraded through
the town on Thursday, in a traditional funeral march, a mariachi
band leading the way, until his burial at the walled cemetery on
the village outskirts, said Martha Ramirez, a cousin who lived with
Daniel in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, though, it was time for relatives and friends in New
York to grieve. Wearing workmen's boots and jeans, dozens arrived
at the funeral home, where they sat quietly in folding chairs and
stared at Daniel's body as it lay in a white coffin in the front of
a wood-paneled room. His hair combed neatly back, Daniel's body was
dressed in a starched white shirt and his large hands held a
rosary. His black Nike baseball cap sat at the head of the casket.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daniel had, like many Mexicans in New York, arrived in the city
and immediately undertaken a variety of jobs, from washing dishes
to working in a market. Unlike many of his countrymen here, he did
not have a wife and children to support in Mexico. But his
immediate family, his parents _ Eduardo Daniel and Teresa Gutierrez
_ and four siblings, were relying on the money he sent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked to get ahead, to help his family get ahead in
Mexico,'' said Braulio Daniel, 36, a cousin who lives in the Bronx.
``He worked to help his family and his brothers and sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Daniel found employment in construction, although it
is unclear how long he had been with the contractor that was
working on the site where he suffered his fatal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   By union standards, the pay was slight, but the $8 an hour
allowed Daniel to sent back as much as $150 a week, said Ms.
Ramirez. After paying rent at the apartment, which he shared with
five others, he saved what he could for the dream house he hoped to
build back home, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Daniel, 28, a cousin who lives in the Bronx, said he
hadn't seen Daniel in months. But he said he was shaken that
someone he had known since childhood had died here in New York, in
_ of all things _ his workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel hurt, to lose a cousin like this,'' said Daniel. ``We
came here to this city to work, and then this, but what can we do?
We can only feel bad to lose a relative here in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for workers at the wake, Daniel's death has been a cold
reminder that the American dream that they all seek can be elusive.
They all know that high living costs coupled with poor pay and
exploitive working conditions often mean people have to return to
Mexico without much in the way of savings.
</P>
<P>
   They also know about the risks inherent in some jobs. But for
someone to lose a life is almost incomprehensible, said some
friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Hernandez, a co-worker on the construction site who was
among several Mexicans injured when a floor collapsed under the
weight of wet cement, said he had never thought of the possibility
that he or any one else could be badly hurt or killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so bad because for me, he was my comrade, my good
friend,'' said Hernandez. ``He was a great guy. He was the one who
died, but I tell you it could just as easily have been me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
