<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-COLTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS LET A GAME _ AND LIKELY THEIR SEASON _ SLIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The tantalizing hope that the New York Jets could
salvage their season all but disappeared Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indianapolis Colts halted the Jets' three-game winning
streak after Wayne Chrebet failed to hold a pass on a play he had
helped draw up seconds earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets held the Colts to their lowest point total of the
season but lost by 13-6. The defeat dropped the Jets' record to 4-7
while the Colts (9-2) extended their winning string to seven games.
</P>
<P>
   With 95 seconds remaining, there was a sense of momentum that
had been missing most of the game from the Jets' offense. Ray Lucas
was directing a drive that had started on his 25. He had converted
a fourth-and-7 pass to Curtis Martin. Now the Jets were on the
Colts' 26, a third-and-19 pass to Dedric Ward had been batted away
in the end zone, and the Jets called time. They huddled on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Then they tried a pass play that Chrebet helped design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pass I've caught thousands of time in practice and
games,'' Chrebet said later. ``I told them the middle of the field
probably will be open.''
</P>
<P>
   He hoped to get behind a linebacker and between the safeties and
that somehow Lucas could get him the ball. Lucas did, but Chrebet
had to leave his feet for the football, and twisted his smallish
body for it. He had it in the hands that have led the league in
clutch third-down receptions. This time, though, the ball sailed
right into his face mask and ricocheted out of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   It sailed with what already was a long-shot chance by the Jets
to make the playoffs. The club had talked of winning its final nine
games for a 10-6 record. On Saturday night, linebacker Mo Lewis had
told the team: ``Let's show them we've got the heart of a champion.
Champions don't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Coach Bill Parcells was moved to say, ``This is
probably the worst loss of the season. Even worse than the Raiders
because I know it should have been better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets took the field late Sunday afternoon in better shape
than they had started Sunday morning. For the Patriots (6-5) had
lost to the Bills, and a Jets' victory not only would have moved
them closer to .500, with the Giants on next week's schedule, but
would have produced a better East Division record than New England,
a tie-breaking factor for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But reality set in for Lucas, who has now failed to direct a
touchdown drive for six straight quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' said the emotional Lucas later. ``We gave
this game away. We may be out of it for real right now, but in my
heart and mind _ no way.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Jets could squeeze out of the RCA Dome Sunday was a pair
of field goals, coming on their opening drives. Lucas' passes
failed to average even 5 yards apiece and his 12 for 22 effort
gained only 102 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the remarkable Jets' defense did even better this time
against the American Conference's highest-scoring team. The Colts
came in averaging 29.4 points a game. The last time the teams met,
the Colts won by 16-13. This time Peyton Manning was held to under
200 passing yards for the only time this year, the Colts produced
their lowest point total, and he was intercepted twice for the
first time in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets cannot afford the several mistakes they made even
though they did not turn over the ball once Sunday and generated
three turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells talked about the ``critical mistake'' on the final
drive that had put the Jets in that last-ditch pass situation.
Curtis Martin had run the ball to the Colts' 10, but Kerry Jenkins
was called for holding. It was the Jets' 10th penalty of the game,
and put them in the position of needing a miracle play.
</P>
<P>
   And there was also the third play of the game _ a potential
touchdown pass that went awry. For this play they employed Jerald
Sowell, the fullback who hadn't seen any action since Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets began the game with one of their most entertaining
drives of the season, one that almost sucked the din out of the
dome.
</P>
<P>
   First, Lucas spotted Keyshawn Johnson for 21 yards as the
defense overcommitted against the big receiver. Then Lucas faked a
handoff and rocketed a pass to Johnson slanting over the middle for
17 more.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the Colts' 32, Lucas handed off to Sowell, a reserve
back who had been recruited by Tulane as a quarterback. He threw
the first pass of his NFL career, to a wide open Johnson in the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I completed that pass twice in practice this week,'' said
Sowell. ``I overthrew him.''
</P>
<P>
   The pass was far off the mark. Still, the Jets got down to the
18. But the red zone _ the sector inside the 20 _ has not been
hospitable territory for them this year. They are the worst team in
the American Conference at producing touchdowns from this area,
crossing the goal line barely a third of the time.
</P>
<P>
   They failed this time, too, settling for a 33-yard field goal
from John Hall and a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the Colts' first play from scrimmage, Edgerrin James fumbled
his 5-yard pass from Manning as Marvin Jones snared him and the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Again the Jets got into the red zone, and again came away with
only a field goal, a 30-yarder from Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Manning seemed concerned at the line of the scrimmage.
Repeatedly he shouted to his receivers to notice something unusual
the Jets' defense was doing. Once, from the shotgun, he even ran up
to his center to scream into his ear, then dashed back into
position.
</P>
<P>
   But if he was confused, he quickly solved the problems. He
directed an 84-yard drive in which he converted a pair of third
downs to set up a 2-yard scoring pass to tight end Marcus Pollard,
who put a little move on Victor Green in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties continued to prevent the Jets from sustaining drives
in the second quarter _ they committed six by halftime. And they
would make only one third-down conversion in 11 attempts for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts made few mistakes on their final drive of the half,
and when Mike Vanderjagt kicked a 22-yard field goal, Indianapolis
had a 10-6 lead. His fourth-quarter field goal put the Jets a
touchdown and extra point away from tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet almost had that touchdown, but the ball and, seemingly
the Jets' season, went bounding away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
