<HEADER>
A3384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-TWINS-BOOM-ART-N     11-28 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-TWINS-BOOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS NUMBER OF TWINS RISES, SO DOES PARENTAL STRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jonathan Alexander was sitting comfortably in his
stroller, ready to roll. His twin sister, Rachel, was screaming.
She did not want to wear a jacket. She did not want to take a walk.
She did not want to do much of anything, it seemed, but arch her
back and wail in protest. Suddenly, as if in sympathy, Jonathan
joined her.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Robin Pollock, quickly attached Rachel to a baby
carrier on her chest, while a baby sitter on standby stuck a
pacifier in the little girl's mouth. One 13-month-old twin in the
stroller, one attached to her mother's chest, out of their
apartment and into the elevator they went. Making their way through
the lobby was akin to a final maneuver in a playoff game: a quick
move to the left, a fast pull to the right &UR; .  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In New York City on any day of the week, one is bound to
encounter a harried parent like Ms. Pollock, pushing a pair of
matching faces in their double stroller. Since 1987, the number of
twins has grown 20 percent in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the boom is everywhere. At an elementary school in
Brooklyn, 26 sets of twins showed up this year. Lamaze coaches, who
used to see one set of parents expecting twins a year, now report
one a month.
</P>
<P>
   It is much the same in the rest of the country, where a
significant rise in the use of fertility treatments has largely
contributed to a 55 percent overall jump in the births of twins
since 1980, according to figures from the National Center for
Health Statistics. &UR;  &LR;  For many parents of twins, the obstacles can
be daunting, starting with pregnancy. Women who become pregnant
with twins are automatically put into a high-risk classification by
their doctors, and require more monitoring and appointments and
often have more emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that twins tend to be more labor intensive in
terms of their management,'' said Dr. Michael Strongin, an
obstetrician at Lenox Hill Hospital in Manhattan. But because
insurance companies do not consider the extra time and care these
patients need when they set reimbursement rates, the cases tend to
go to a few doctors specializing in multiple births, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for women pregnant with twins to require bed
rest or very curtailed activity, which comes as a big shock to
someone who has spent the last decade of her life powering ahead in
a busy career.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Nachmanoff, a vice president of NBC News, who gave birth
to twins three years ago, was told she needed to lie down on her
left side several hours a day in the final stretch of her
pregnancy. The news came just as she was hiring 250 people for a
new division. So she interviewed them all while reclining on her
office couch. ``People went along with it,'' Ms. Nachmanoff said.
``What could they do? I went into labor that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians say that their roles, too, have altered as more
twins have come into their practices. They have had to learn to
comfort parents who have one child who is ready to go home but must
leave one behind in the intensive care unit, a not uncommon
situation, since multiple births often result in premature babies
and complications.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that pressing parents to treat each child as a
complete individual _ not dressing them alike or assuming that they
will develop on the same track _ often takes precedence over
treating head colds.
</P>
<P>
   Once children are old enough for school, parents of twins say,
the stress automatically doubles as they race with ``singletons'' _
twin world argot for single children _ to get spots in private
schools and the elite public school programs.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, a dozen parents all insisted that private schools
were loath to give two coveted spots to one family with twins
because two families produced more fund-raising power. Private
school admissions officers uniformly denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Having one twin get accepted into a school when another does not
is one of the most painful, and logistically difficult, problems
their parents often face.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Berg prayed that his sons, Bryan and Gregory, would get
into a public school kindergarten program for gifted children. But
only one of the twins, now 7, got into the program, so the two went
to different schools their first year. ``In one way it was good
because it allowed them both to explore their own way,'' Berg said.
``But then they had different friends and different play dates, and
that was difficult, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Smadar Levy, who lives in Brooklyn with her twin fourth-graders,
said that going to a public school, P.S. 276 in Canarsie, that was
chock full of twins was a boon for her children, Briana and Seth
Zeltzer. ``Teachers have become sensitive to it,'' Mrs. Levy said.
``There are some stronger sibling rivalry issues with twins. They
try to foster each special talent each child has, and know not to
refer to them as `the twins.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the tension, isolation and difficulties, parents of
twins say things do get better, especially when their children
develop a symbiotic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first year, many parents say if the house hadn't burned
down it was a successful day,'' said Kathy Junior, the co-director
of Mothering Multiples, a support group. ``But then there is
something so magical about watching these two beings share a
budding relationship together. In the end, they have to say that it
was a wonderful experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
