<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET EQUIPMENT MAKER PLANNING TO MAKE A $4.3 BILLION
ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (jw) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Redback Networks, a maker of equipment to help Internet service
providers transmit data more easily, is acquiring Siara Systems for
about $4.3 billion in stock, company executives said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Redback makes a box called a subscriber management system that
helps Internet service providers, like telephone companies and
cable operators, send data quickly over high-speed broad band
networks. In buying Siara Systems, Redback hopes that the optical
networking equipment and software Siara is developing will turn
Redback into one of the first one-stop shops for products needed to
run the next generation of computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   Optical networking, which makes it easier to send more
information quickly across broad band networks, is all the rage
among technology companies in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those companies are paying astonishing prices for
enterprises that have no products or revenues but that hold promise
in the race to offer high-speed Internet access to homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, for one, raised eyebrows recently when it agreed
to buy Cerent Corp &UR; . &LR;  and Monterey Networks, two networking
concerns, in deals with a combined value of more than $7.5 billion.
And several public companies are already developing products in
this field, too, including Sycamore Networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all taken aback by where the valuations are,'' said
Dennis Barsema, Redback's chief executive. ``Cisco's payment for
Cerent was sort of a new benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   But what Redback is really paying for is talent _ 170 engineers
_ and the promise that their ideas will be more market-worthy than
those of their competitors. Siara sells no products but is expected
to begin testing some in the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redback is a very bold company,'' said Barsema, who will
remain as chief executive in the combined company. ``We think this
is a key strategic move to broaden the reach into the new access
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Redback, based in Sunnyvale, Calif., recently sold shares in one
of the most watched initial public offerings of the year. On
Friday, Redback's stock closed down $3.1875 a share, at $137.375,
in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   A combination with Siara, a privately held company based in
Mountain View, Calif., would give it a market value of $11.2
billion and, Barsema said, increase the available market for the
combined company's products 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   Siara was formed in July 1998 by a group of engineers who had
left Cerent. During the last 16 months, Siara has hired 170
engineers and several high-level executives from competitors like
Lucent Technologies, Cisco, Advanced Micro Devices and Nortel
Networks.
</P>
<P>
   One of Siara's first proponents was Vinod Khosla, a general
partner of Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, the venture capital
firm, and co-founder of Sun Microsystems, who will become a
director of the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Khosla has had a golden touch this year. Not only was he the
driving force behind Cisco's acquisition of Cerent, but he was also
a key supporter of Juniper Networks, a maker of telecommunications
gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago, we adapted a vision of how to build a
next-generation network,'' he said in an interview Sunday. ``So we
started building these companies around how we thought networks
should be built. The fact that they are valuable is because they
had one, two, three years of development. Now that vision is being
validated.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives for the two companies began negotiating their
agreement three weeks ago, though Bersema said they had previously
discussed a merger as much as nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key things that Vivek Ragavan, chief executive of
Siara, said he wanted to ensure, though, was that his executives be
treated as equals in any transaction. He said that access to
Redback would give his company a better idea about how to develop
products that customers could use.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will keep the Redback name; Ragavan will be
named president of the combined operation.
</P>
<P>
   Once the merger is complete, Redback shareholders will own 62
percent of the new company and Siara stakeholders will own 38
percent. The boards of both companies have approved the
transaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
