<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOOLISH ERRORS MAKE FOR LOST WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The weekend held such promise for Bill Parcells,
before it eventually crumbled into a devastating loss to
Indianapolis, which all but eliminated the New York Jets from the
playoff race. The head coach lambasted his team afterward, scolding
players by name for blowing opportunities. And their season, too.
It wasn't supposed to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' not-so-excellent adventure began on a warm note
Saturday night, when his buddy Bob Knight, the Indiana basketball
coach, trotted through the Jets' team hotel and paid a visit.
Knight proved to be good luck for about a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells opened up the offense, and for a while the Jets looked
more like the Colts than the Colts did. There were halfback passes
and deep balls to Keyshawn Johnson, all of which led to two John
Hall field goals. The Jets were ecstatic on the sideline, knowing
that this was not going to be a Colts blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a series of frustrating, horrible mental errors on the
way to a 13-6 loss. And it all began in the second quarter, with
one of the dumbest mistakes Parcells has ever made as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   After Jets safety Victor Green was penalized for pass
interference, Parcells lost his legendary temper disputing the
call, and began yelling at the head linesman, Earnie Frantz. During
Parcells' rant, he used an obscenity that would make the
foulest-mouthed comedian blush. That led to Parcells' being flagged
for a 15-yard unsportsmanlike-conduct penalty and it gave
Indianapolis a first down at the Jets' 12-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said something I shouldn't have said,'' Parcells explained.
``First time in 15 years. I apologized to the guy and said sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said that though he made a mistake, the Colts did not
profit from his blunder. And they did not, because defensive
lineman Jason Wiltz later caught a tipped Peyton Manning pass,
ending that Colts' drive at the Jets' 1-yard line. But that's not
the point. On the road, in a huge game, a coach's getting that kind
of penalty is inexcusable, especially when Parcells is always
preaching to his players about how there is no margin of error for
this team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's nothing. The season is over. The Jets are not
officially eliminated, but that is like saying Donald Trump has a
chance to become president. He has a shot, but it's on the
probability list in around the same place as winning the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   This loss will stick in the stomachs of Parcells and his players
for a long time. Now Parcells, besides washing his mouth out with
soap, must make certain that his players do not go into a complete
tailspin, knowing the season is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kinds of losses you want to forget about,''
running back Curtis Martin said. ``You don't like them sitting in
your mind. They frustrate you and anger you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put this behind us,'' he added. ``But at the same
time, I'll be saying for weeks, `What if?'''
</P>
<P>
   What if the Jets did not have 10 penalties for 72 yards? What if
running back Jerald Sowell does not overthrow a wide-open Johnson
in the end zone by 5 yards on that halfback option? What if the
Jets converted more than just one of 11 third downs?
</P>
<P>
   And what if wide receiver Wayne Chrebet catches that ball in the
end zone with less than two minutes to go? That is the biggest
``what if?'' of them all. Parcells, Chrebet and quarterback Ray
Lucas basically drew up the play on the sideline. Lucas did his
part by getting the ball to Chrebet in the back of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet is the last guy you would expect to drop a pass that was
right in his hands. But he did. The ball actually went through his
paws and hit him in the head. Afterward, Chrebet called it a drop
and blamed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was asked about the loss in general, but he seemed to be
speaking about Chrebet when he said: ``Anytime it's money time
you've got to come through. I can only do so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets lost this game because of their own mistakes. Yet the
final touch was applied by Manning. He finished a solid 23 of 31
and made some nice passes late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Jets would blanket the Colts' dangerous receivers,
especially Marvin Harrison, who had only 58 yards receiving,
Manning would simply scramble. Nothing irks a defensive player more
than to see a pretty-boy quarterback run for a first down and then
slide out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Belichick, the Jets' brilliant defensive coordinator, threw
everything he had at Manning. Manning was rarely rattled. Standing
on the sideline, Belichick often had a pained look on his face, as
if he had eaten three cups of prunes. Belichick should not be
ashamed. He is not the only one of his coaching brethren to watch
Manning ruin a perfectly good game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the Jets had not committed so many foolish errors,
Manning would have been the one explaining to the news media why
the Colts lost, instead of Parcells glumly discussing how this was
by far the worst loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells let the Jets know his feelings behind closed doors,
using more choice words than he did with the news media, loudly
scolding some of the players.
</P>
<P>
   But this time many of them tuned out Parcells' shotgun blasts.
They knew what had just happened. They did not need his
play-by-play.
</P>
<P>
   They knew it was over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
