<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOALIE OF THE FUTURE LIFTS ISLANDERS PAST BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What do you do with a 20-year-old goaltender who has
already been anointed as one of the brightest prospects in the
National Hockey League?
</P>
<P>
   If you are New York Islanders coach Butch Goring, you have no
choice. You play him.
</P>
<P>
   With the backup goalie Wade Flaherty out indefinitely with a
sprained shoulder and Felix Potvin having played in 17 of the
Islanders' first 21 games, Goring _ to no one's surprise _ gave
Roberto Luongo his first NHL start in tonight's game against
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a gratifying 2-1 victory keyed by Luongo's 43
saves _ 15 in the first period, 16 in the second and 12 in the
third. His only lapse, if one could call it a lapse, came at 6
minutes 2 seconds of the second period, when left wing Anson Carter
broke through after the Bruins had amassed 20 shots on Luongo,
taking Jason Allison's pass from behind the net and putting it in
for the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, looking to rebound after Saturday's loss to
Washington, had struck first, with Jorgen Jonsson scoring his
fourth goal of the season on a pass from Jamie Heward at 1:31 of
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   After taking just five shots on goal in the second period, the
Islanders went ahead, 2-1, at 19:05 on an odd but effective play by
defenseman Zdeno Chara. Chased by left wing Sergei Samsonov, Chara
skated back and forth behind the net, finally reaching around the
left side and poking the puck past Byron Dafoe for his second goal
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Luongo's play was impressive from start to finish. He made glove
save on top of kick save on top of stick save, smothering the puck
after several dramatic stops in the final seconds of play after the
Bruins pulled Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Goring was hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have him up here and sitting all the time,'' Goring
said of Luongo, who was recalled from Lowell on Nov. 22 to fill in
for the injured Flaherty. ``He's earned his start. He played well
in training camp and in the exhibition games. He's here and he's
capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Luongo, whom the Islanders made their first choice in the 1997
entry draft (fourth overall, the highest-selected goalie ever), was
6-6-3 in 15 games with a 2.98 goals against average and a .906 save
percentage for the Lock Monsters. The 6-foot-3-inch, 198-pound
left-hander, who spent four years in the Quebec League, was second
in the American Hockey League in saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fairly sharp,'' Goring said. ``It doesn't do him any good
to sit, and Felix is playing a lot of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Luongo will remain with the Islanders is uncertain.
Goring said he wanted to determine Flaherty's status before taking
a next step with Luongo, although Sunday night's effort had to help
the youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to decide what Flaherty's status is,'' Goring
said. In any event, he added, ``Luongo is a fine prospect and will
be a great player for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty was downgraded from day-to-day status Saturday night
before the Islanders' frustrating 4-3 home loss to the Washington
Capitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
