<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- NY-HOMELESS-SHELTERS, 11-28
-- Living arrangements for Jose Torres and his family were
makeshift after they were expelled from a shelter in Long Island's
Suffolk County. Shelter expulsions have become almost routine in
Suffolk, which for four years has strictly applied the rules that
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani intends to enforce in New York City for the
first time in December. Social services say that families brought
expulsion on themselves, by ignoring the rules and refusing ample
social service help. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) FORT LEWIS, Wash. -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- MILITARY-MOMS-2,
11-28 -- Col. Nancy Bickford, a 44-year-old Army logistics expert
and mother of two children, has passed up several steps necessary
for promotion, because of her family. First she deferred a
battalion command when her husband, who was also in the Army, was
not given an appointment at the same post in Germany. She was given
a second chance and commanded 800 soldiers in a battalion at Fort
Lewis, but then she passed up the Army War College, again for
family reasons. Next summer she is retiring. (Dan Lamont/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) FORT LEWIS, Wash. -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- MILITARY-MOMS-1,
11-28 -- Lois and Glenn Beard, both Army colonels, with their
children, Rachel, left, Ryan and Megan. Col. Lois Beard was likely
to become the first mother promoted to Army general when she
retired, citing excessive demands. Of all the subjects that
preoccupy women rising through the ranks, few are more pressing
than how to balance motherhood with the all-consuming commitment
required to become a general or an admiral. If the corporate world
has a glass ceiling, women in the military say the Pentagon has a
brass ceiling. (Dan Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- NY-TWINS-BOOM, 11-28 --
Public School 276 in Brooklyn has 26 sets of twins this year, 25 of
which are pictured here. The teachers at the school know enough not
to refer to a matching pair of siblings as ``the twins,'' says one
mother of twins at the school. Since 1987, the number of twins has
grown 20 percent in New York City and it is much the same in the
rest of the country, where a significant rise in the use of
fertility treatments has largely contributed to a 55 percent
overall jump in the births of twins since 1980, according to
figures from the National Center for Health Statistics. (James
Estrin/ New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOISE, Idaho -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- IDAHO-CROSS, 11-28 --
Sightseers visiting a cross above Boise, which is at the center of
a debate about church and state. For 43 years, the 60-foot white
cross, built by the Idaho Jaycees, has stood like a Christian
beacon on the eastern skyline of Boise. To avoid a potential
constitutional challenge from the American Civil Liberties Union,
the Jaycees even bought the tiny spit of land on which the cross
sits for $100 in 1972. Earlier this month, Rob Sherman, a Chicago
talk-radio host and an atheist ignited a passionate debate in a
speech to Idaho atheists by suggesting that the land transaction
was rigged and that a federal lawsuit should be filed to bring down
the cross. (Glenn Oakley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SEATTLE -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- TRADETALK-PROTESTS-2, 11-28
-- In what is shaping up as one of the biggest protest efforts in
years, people from more than 500 organizations have poured into
Seattle. They came to accuse the World Trade Organization, the
135-nation, Geneva-based group that is holding its ministerial
meeting in Seattle this week, of favoring free trade at the expense
of the environment, consumer safety and workers' rights. (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SEATTLE -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- TRADETALK-PROTESTS-1, 11-28
-- In what is shaping up as one of the biggest protest efforts in
years, people from more than 500 organizations have poured into
Seattle. They came to accuse the World Trade Organization, the
135-nation, Geneva-based group that is holding its ministerial
meeting in Seattle this week, of favoring free trade at the expense
of the environment, consumer safety and workers' rights. (Larry
Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HARGEISA, Somalia -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- SOMALIA-PACESETTER,
11-28 -- Edna Adan Ismail, a former first lady of Somalia from 1967
to 1969 and a public health expert, has poured $300,000 of her own
money into what she calls ``the monster,'' a maternity hospital for
poor women in the city of Hargeisa. But her money is running out
and finishing the hospital is turning out to be difficult. Some
fans of Ms. Ismail say that the difficulties are a likely symbol of
the place where it located: in the self-proclaimed Republic of
Somaliland, which declared independence from the rest of Somalia in
1991. (Ian Fisher/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- TAFEL-PROFILE, 11-28 -- An
outspokenly gay Republican, Richard Tafel, is executive director of
the Log Cabin Republicans, a gay political group. But Tafel sees
his steadfast Republicanism as a matter of stubborn principle, not
pathology. He grew up as one of six children in Bucks County, Pa.,
with a set of Republican beliefs. ``It didn't make sense that I
should jettison everything that I was, my family, my faith, my
political principles, because I was gay,'' he says. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LONDON -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- COVENT-GARDEN-2, 11-28 -- The
facade of the Royal Opera House, at Covent Garden. After four years
of melodrama, the Royal Opera House has completed a $360 million
redevelopment and will reopen on Dec. 1 with a gala attended by
Queen Elizabeth. (Jonathan Player/New York Tmes Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LONDON -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- COVENT-GARDEN-1, 11-28 --
After four years of melodrama, the Royal Opera House, at Covent
Garden has completed a $360 million redevelopment and will reopen
on Dec. 1 with a gala attended by Queen Elizabeth. While the Royal
Opera and the Royal Ballet can now boast a home fit for the 21st
century, the price has been high, and not simply in monetary terms.
By seeking a $125 million grant from National Lottery profits to
add to its annual subsidy from the government, the opera house
invited scrutiny by press, Parliament and public. The resulting
verdict was ferocious: that Covent Garden was overstaffed, badly
managed and elitist. (Jonathan Player/New York Tmes Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- CYNTHIA-NIXON-PROFILE, 11-28
-- Cynthia Nixon, far left, with Amy Hohn, in the ``Country Club''
at the Greenwich House Theater. Ms. Nixon, 33, has appeared in 25
plays on and off Broadway over the last 19 years and has been
called a perennial of the New York theater. ``I always say that at
my funeral I want them to play Judy Garland singing 'I Happen to
Like New York,''' says Ms. Nixon. ``Because I do.'' Ms. Nixon has
achieved her biggest success as the corporate lawyer Miranda on the
hit HBO comedy series ``Sex and the City,'' the city, of course,
being New York. (Sara Krulwich/New York Tmes Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- MILLENIUM-ON-STAGE, 11-28 --
Willem Dafoe and Kate Valk in the Wooster Group's ``North
Atlantic'' at the Performing Garage in SoHo. The Group, under the
direction of Elizabeth LeCompte, is a fierce, iconoclastic
repertory company. ``North Atlantic'' is set in the Reagan 1980's
on an aircraft carrier, so the feel is strictly Evil Empire,
1950s-style. (Sara Krulwich/New York Tmes Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 28, 1999 -- TALK-MAGAZINE-MEDIA, 11-28
-- Harvey Weinstein, right, co-chairman of Miramax Films, one of
Talk magazine's corporate parents, says he merely lends a hand at
the magazine, which is run by Tina Brown, left, and Ronald A.
Galotti. ``It takes time for a magazine to establish its identity,
and when you're in the early stages of a product's life, you need
all the help you can get,'' says Ms. Brown. ``It's taken time to
organize our approach to Hollywood, which is very much organized
around the world of celebrities.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
