<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1ST     11-28 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GIANTS ARE GETTING WHAT THEY PAID FOR
</HEADLINE>
 (CORRECTS ``three'' to ``two'' in 4th graf) 
 (nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Late Sunday afternoon Wellington Mara
stood in a New York Giants locker room soaked in gloom and
disappointment after a 34-24 thrashing by the Arizona Cardinals.
The loss sunk the Giants to 5-6. But for playing in a miserable
division, the loss would have ended the Giants' playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Mara, who turned 83 in August, is a good person to talk to at
times like these, times when the ship is sinking, despair is
descending. He always has the same unflappable expression, a
bemused smile _ sometimes happier, sometimes a bit more pained,
always barely discernible. He has seen so many highs and lows with
this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Mara was 9 years old when Jim Thorpe lined up for the Giants'
inaugural game against the Providence Steam Rollers in 1925. In the
intervening decades, the Giants have won 17 division titles and six
National Football League championships.
</P>
<P>
   But the past two seasons have been rough. Jim Fassel, the
Giants' head coach since 1997, has been pummeled by the news media.
After a surprisingly good first season in 1997 _ a 10-5-1 record
and a playoff berth _ he has presided over a listless offense.
Touted as a quarterback doctor, Fassel has been unable to mold a
quarterback to provide a spark: Dave Brown, Danny Kanell, Kent
Graham and now Kerry Collins have revealed one fatal flaw after
another.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after a 23-13 loss to Washington, the Giants' defense
lashed out at the offense for failing to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the defense was thrashed by Arizona, on the ground and in
the air. After the game, the defense was contrite, the offense
subdued.
</P>
<P>
   But longtime Giants fans realized _ probably a few games back,
maybe months ago _ that the Giants' problems in this 75th season
run deeper than an internecine feud between the offense and
defense, deeper even than whether Fassel should stay or go.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the hierarchy's failure _ or fear _ of matching
the strength of leadership with the depth and strength of its
organization. The Giants' success was engineered by coaches with
dominant personalities and vision and the Giants' willingness to
seek them out, hire them, give them latitude.
</P>
<P>
   Lately the Giants in the ivory tower have clung to control, have
lost the force behind their foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Mara's eyes twinkled when the names of Steve Owen and
Jim Lee Howell were invoked. Owen coached the Giants for 23 full
seasons, 1930 to '53. His 153 victories are the most of any Giants
coach. He was the captain of the 1927 championship team. More than
that, Owen realized in the early 1950s, when his team was still
running a single-wing offense, that it was time to switch to the
new T formation. He hired Allie Sherman as a coach to teach the
team the new offense.
</P>
<P>
   Howell coached from 1954 to 1960 and led the Giants to a league
championship and three division titles. ``He had such great
manners, you'd never guess he was a Marine company commander,''
Mara said. ``He was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells rescued the Giants after two decades of
mediocrity. His 77-49 record puts him second in victories to Owen.
Parcells took the Giants to Super Bowl victories in 1986 and '90.
He walked away when the Giants were unwilling to cede greater
control of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves rebuilt a crumbling franchise left by Ray Handley.
Reeves left after the 1996 season, also as a result of struggle,
less over power than control.
</P>
<P>
   The parting with Reeves was so nasty that it seems the franchise
was determined not to hire a dominant personality to replace him.
In this respect the Giants are no different from any other
corporate culture. Managers subconsciously hire those who defer,
who won't challenge, won't resist.
</P>
<P>
   After Reeves resigned, the Giants desperately wanted Nick Saban
of Michigan State. In Saban the Giants saw the fiery young coach of
its future. In the Giants Saban probably saw a franchise unwilling
to yield the control he would need to be successful. The Giants
lost Parcells. Lost Reeves. Lost Saban. They settled for Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel just wanted to be a head coach. Did not want to grab
power, did not want control. Just wanted a chance to do whatever
the organization wanted him to do.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of winning, the organization is not sure what it wants
to do, and, outside of some vague notion of developing a
high-powered offense, how to do it. The Giants touted the fact that
Fassel was an offensive innovator. He doesn't have the offense with
which to innovate. The Giants have not supplied him with the power.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a call for the Giants to fire the coach: Fassel is a
river that the Giants will have to let run its course. When the
river is through, they should look at their history. The Giants'
foundation is too solid to be damaged by the strength of a coach's
personality. The franchise is more likely to be done in by a
captain so willing to please that he won't deviate from a
disastrous course.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Owen was smart enough to switch from the single wing to
the T formation. Jim Lee Howell oversaw the flex defense. Howell
and Owen, strong personalities, did not destroy the Giants'
foundation. ``They were part of the foundation,'' Mara agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the Giants were more interested in a coach who would
genuflect than a coach who might forge a new path and needed added
power do it.
</P>
<P>
   Now they pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
