<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3438 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-HKN-NHL-MESS-AZR &LR;      11-28 2069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-MESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THIN ICE  
 WITH SOARING PAY ROLLS SPURRING TALK OF A LABOR STANDOFF, THE NHL
MAY
 FACE HARD TIMES SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Scotty Bowman doesn't want to say the NHL is in
serious trouble. That would be un-Bowman-like. That would be
focusing on negative energy. After all, Bowman always prefers to
take a positive approach first when problems arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game, itself, has never been better,'' the future Hall of
Famer said. ``The players are more exciting. The equipment is
better. The buildings are better. The TV contract is better. And
the fans are just great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I hate to say it. I really do. But I've got some concerns
about where we're headed. I don't know if we can survive at this
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   As the NHL skates closer to the new millennium, there are grave
concerns about the future of the league. Salaries have escalated
beyond belief, revenue streams reportedly are down, and several
teams are in such financial disarray, some owners are threatening
to either relocate to larger markets or sell their franchise to get
out from under the muck.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has lost two teams to Denver and Phoenix. A third, the
Ottawa Senators, also may flee to the United States to escape a
massive tax crunch and resistance from government officials to give
monetary aid. Senators owner Rod Bryden will announce his
intentions next week at league meetings in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say the apocalypse is coming. I think we're there
now,'' said Brian Burke, general manager of the Vancouver Canucks.
``It's not a healthy industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the New York Islanders, who are struggling to make ends
meet in the antiquated Nassau Coliseum after gutting their roster
of top players. Or the Pittsburgh Penguins, who were nearly
disbanded before being sold to Mario Lemieux in bankruptcy court.
And just last week Florida Panthers owner Wayne Huizenga put his
team up for sale because it was too tough for him to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, the league is treading on dangerously thin ice.
The NHL is locked into its collective bargaining agreement through
2004, but many believe it may have to be re-opened well before then
to ensure long-term peace and stability. &QL; 
Payrolls crushing teams &QL; 
There is talk of adding a hard salary cap to help keep small-market
clubs, especially those in Canada, on a competitive balance.
Canadian teams are getting crushed by the weight of the weak
Canadian dollar while being forced to pay top U.S. dollars to keep
their star players.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly have the payrolls skyrocketed? Just two years ago,
the New York Rangers, with the top payroll at $59.4 million, had
$43.7 million in salaries, according to the ``Hockey News'''
1999-2000 salary survey. On the other end, the New York Islanders,
who rank 26th out of 28 teams this season with $18.1 million
payroll, have dumped salaries to avoid increases since paying $18
million in salaries two seasons ago. The Coyotes, who had a $24
million payroll two seasons ago, now have a $31 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Owners and GMs have taken note. This summer, many of them took a
hard-line stance on this year's crop of free agents, refusing to
dole out big bucks to big-time players. Privately, the skaters and
their agents complained of collusion. Bettman steadfastly denied
the innocuous, subtle charges, saying teams have a right to spend
as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   But during an interview last spring, when revealing player
salaries had topped team revenue earnings, Bettman said that if
clubs don't take matters into their own hands, the league would
``make sure they know what they're getting themselves into.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to realize what's happening,'' Bettman said. ``If
teams don't get the picture, we're going to have to remind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Economics blow your mind &QL; 
Bowman, who has coached teams to a record-tying eight Stanley Cups,
chuckles when he looks back and sees all the changes during his
legendary career, which includes an unprecedented 1,109
regular-season victories entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first team in St. Louis in '67, 32 years ago, we had a
payroll budget of $425,000,'' Bowman said. ``That was for all 22
players. Steve Yzerman's contract in '89, just 10 years ago, was
something like $490,000 _ and that wasn't one of the poor ones.
He's making $5 or $6 million now and next year it's going to be
something like $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be tough for players in the 80s who are out of the
game now to see what guys are making. The economics just blow your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The average NHL salary this season is $1.3 million. And Bowman's
Red Wings, who meet the Coyotes today at Joe Louis Arena, have the
third-highest payroll in the league at $46.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Hayward, a goalie who spent 11 seasons in the NHL with
Winnipeg, Montreal, Minnesota and San Jose, made $65,000 as a
rookie. He retired in 1992 with a salary of $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really an issue, though,'' said Hayward, now a
television analyst for the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim. ``Am I envious
of today's contracts? Sure I'm envious. But Bobby Orr is envious,
too. All the truly great players are envious. But the game
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ice, Hayward said the game is in better shape than ever.
He cites the NHL's successful expansion into the Sun Belt, where
teams are thriving in Florida and California, not to mention
Phoenix and Dallas, which won the Stanley Cup last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That being said, I think there are big-time financial problems
that need to be addressed,'' Hayward said. ``A lot of teams are
losing money out there and I think we're in for a very long war in
2004 when the CBA expires. I don't think that's any revelation.
Everybody feels that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for a possible work stoppage in another four years,
the NHL Players Association has been building a significant war
chest through the sale of trading cards and other licensing
ventures. The union doesn't want to be caught with its guard down,
which some players claim was the case in 1994-95, when the season
was reduced to 48 games due to a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   And the NHL is getting ready, too. It was revealed recently that
the league is assessing each of its teams $10 million for the war
chest that Bettman wants as financial protection against a possible
lockout or strike in four years. Bettman was given owners' approval
for the fund in December. The league is requiring teams to make
their contribution to the fund by April 15, 2003, according to a
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filing by Florida Panthers
parent Boca Resorts Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Payout exceeds payoff &QL; 
Have the NHL's problems gone through the roof and left clubs unable
to repair the damage? Boston Bruins President and General Manager
Harry Sinden is just one of many executives who grumble the payout
far outweighs the payoff and that rising salaries could be the
death of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden made waves for asserting that more than 20 of the team's
28 clubs are losing money and that players are gobbling up 72
percent of league revenues, a figure Bettman could neither confirm
or deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're paying 133 percent of our gate receipts to players,''
Sinden told the ``Boston Globe.''``'' ``Take every single ticket
that is sold across the league and we've got to find 33 percent
more than that to pay them. Just them. We've got problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden was so fed up with the salary demands of Bruins forward
Dmitri Khristich this summer, that after Khristich won a $3 million
arbitrator's judgement, the Bruins' boss exercised a rare
``walk-away'' clause that allowed Khristich to become an
unrestricted free agent. He later signed with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Other GMs followed his lead, refusing to pay what had become the
standard market value to re-sign their own free agents. As a
result, many of them went unsigned for several weeks. Many more,
including goalie Nikolai Khabibulin and center Robert Reichel of
the Coyotes, have been told negotiations are off and they won't
play in the NHL this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel's agent, Paul Kraus of Edmonton, has said repeatedly
that Phoenix General Manager Bobby Smith is simply towing the NHL
company line to try and drive down salaries. He doesn't believe the
Coyotes are in any real cash crisis and has his doubts about Owner
Richard Burke's claim that the club, four seasons removed from
playing in Winnipeg, will lose as much as $10 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very hard to swallow that a team would move from one
small-market city to another small-market city,'' Kraus said,
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with sitting out the season and not collecting a dime
because of the virtual league-wide, hard-stance policy of
management, some free agents worked out new deals with their clubs
on their own, either abandoning their agents or simply not telling
them. Such was the case with Buffalo's Miroslav Satan and Boston's
Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk of the Dallas Stars also negotiated his own deal
with General Manager Bob Gainey and was granted a three-year
extension worth $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Arliss or anything, but it wasn't that hard to do,''
Nieuwendyk said, referring to ``Arliss Michaels,'' a fictional
sports agent from a series on Home Box Office.
</P>
<P>
   Union won't buckle &QL; 
Privately, owners and GMs would love to see this trend continue. If
players leave their agents in the dust, think of what that could do
to the NHLPA? Imagine the long-term consequences? How would that
affect negotiations on a new collective-bargaining agreement?
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect the union to buckle under Bob Goodenow,
executive director of the Players Association, who is prepared for
the inevitable when the CBA expires on Sept 14, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a possibility that another owner lockout or
strike could occur,'' he told the ``Toronto Sun.'' ``The best thing
would be to have discussions between the parties and for a program
to evolve without that kind of disruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen the cost of the approach when they locked the
players out for more than 100 days last time. It was a great cost.
It's incumbent upon the people involved, myself included, to do
everything in their power to avoid a problem and I'm focused to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A new agreement and a hard salary cap might not be enough to
save some clubs in Canada, where hockey dominates the landscape and
the soul. Not even the fabled ``bleu-blanc-rouge,'' the Montreal
Canadiens, can feel safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their local tax bill from a year ago was $11 million, which is
more than the local tax bills of all the U.S.-based teams,
combined,'' said Vancouver's Burke, the NHL's former vice president
in charge of hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our local tax bill is somewhere in the neighborhood of $3
million. The withholding on our players' salaries and staff
salaries alone _ forget what we do for the economy and the image of
Vancouver and the restaurants on game nights _ just on what I have
to pay to the provincial and federal governments on withholding for
our staff and players is $29 million a year.''
</P>
<P>
   How long can clubs continue to pay that amount in a gate
receipt-driven sport that already carries the most expensive ticket
among the four major professional sports? The only viable
alternative, short of drastic political changes, is to relocate to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a hypothetical thing. We don't have to wait to see
when Armageddon will occur. It's occurred,'' Burke said. ``We've
lost two teams and the fans of Phoenix are the beneficiaries of one
of those teams. But the fact of the matter is, if (the Coyotes)
were still in Winnipeg and if (the Avalanche) was still in Quebec
City, and if they had payrolls about like ours, that's $29 million
a year from both those teams that's gone from Canada forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know how politicians can look at that and not
say, `You know what? That was a mistake.' If they had been willing
to pay them $10 million a year to stay, and preserve that asset
that generates an annual amount of money . . . but I guess I'm not
as smart as the politicians up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government doesn't step up, I think we'll lose three
teams, minimum, in Canada. We'll lose, I think, both our baseball
teams in Canada. And I think we'll probably lose both our NBA
teams. If that's what the government wants . . . then I say
everyone start the clock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
