NYT-11-28-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3440 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-HKN-NHL-MESS-PLAYERS-     11-28 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-MESS-PLAYERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION CHIEF SAYS `NO' TO REOPENING PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Any talk of a adding a possible salary cap or
reopening negotiations on the collective bargaining agreement would
need approval first by the NHLPA, and the chances of that happening
are about as good as Wayne Gretzky coming out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Goodenow, executive director of the Players Association,
declined interview requests by ``The Arizona Republic.'' However,
he told the ``Toronto Sun'' last week he doesn't think a salary cap
is fair to the players _ regardless of the dollar amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a matter of what is the number,'' Goodenow
said. ``For 10 years now, since I became involved, we as an
association have looked at the markets. Markets can go up and down.
The idea of the players to accept a salary cap system is really a
notion for them to accept less than they might otherwise have been
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   And Goodenow and agents say the players are just trying to get
their fair share of a growing product. Players can ask for more,
the union says, because of:
</P>
<P>
   Expansion fees. Each existing club will have reaped more than
$15 million with the additions of Nashville, Atlanta, Columbus and
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's new $600 million television contract with ABC and
ESPN, which began this season.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury suites and club seating at new arenas. By next season, 23
of the NHL's 30 teams will be playing in new buildings or in arenas
less than 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Appreciating values of franchises. In 1995, the Coyotes were
purchased from former owner Barry Shenkarow for $67 million. An
estimate by ``Forbes'' predicts the team's value today is closer to
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   To the players, Goodenow has become Gretzky-like is his ability
to transform the union into a powerful wing of the NHL
establishment. Under the direction of Alan Eagleson, who was in bed
with the owners and turned his back on the players, the
organization carried little weight and had no direction.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years on the job, Goodenow has made the rank and file
forget Eagleson. Under his Goodenow's watch, player salaries have
quadrupled in worth and the skaters are more unified and informed
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   NHL management, of course, blame him for much of today's state
of affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do look upon him as Satan,'' player agent Brian Lawton
said. ``But I don't know where the players would be without him.
The NHLPA was in complete disarray when he took over for Alan
Eagleson. Bob brought organization and unity to the PA that it
never had before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salary increases speak for themselves. A player like Paul
Kariya would probably be making only $2 million and the average
salary would be around $400,000 now if it weren't for Bob. That's
how much he has meant to the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of player salaries, now readily available on the
NHLPA's Internet site, is thought to be one of the major reasons
why contracts have soared in recent years. Salaries used to be kept
secret from the media and other agents. Now, they are used as
measuring sticks for every deal that gets done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has to apologize for what they make,''
Philadelphia Flyers goalie John Vanbiesbrouck said. ``If that's
what helped escalate salaries, though, that's great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991128.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
