<SLUG> BC-ISP-UNRELIABLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CONSUMERS SAY YOU CAN'T RELY ON GETTING, STAYING ONLINE  &HT;     By TOM STEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A s consumers, we have certain expectations.
</P>
<P>
   When we pick up the telephone, we expect to hear a dial tone.
When we switch on the television, we expect to see flickering
images. And when we turn up the furnace, we expect to feel heat.
</P>
<P>
   Logging on to the Internet, however, is another story
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first Internet provider was a nightmare that I'm still
recovering from,'' said Marlis Ertl of Pinole, Calif. Ertl was
among scores of San Francisco Bay Area residents who shared their
online trials and tribulations with The San Francisco Chronicle in
response to our question: How reliable is your Internet connection?
``It took weeks to get going . . . and then the cutoffs, outages
and hard-to-log-on problems started. Mostly I ask myself why I took
the abuse so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Ertl _ who until recently used a small Internet service
provider, or ISP, called InfiNet _ is not alone. While a handful of
readers responded positively about their ISPs, it seems many Bay
Area residents believe that spotty service is an unfortunate, but
inevitable, reality of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it works, I love it,'' said Noah Cole of Berkeley,
Calif., describing his experience with AT&AMP;T AtHome. ``But I'm no
longer surprised by a flashing `no connection' light.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online customer Nell Fraser of Walnut Creek, Calif.,
complained: ``Routinely the modem dials six to 10 numbers before
getting a response from the carrier. This delays getting online by
15 to 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My Internet connection is AT&AMP;T Worldnet, and on a scale of 1
to 10, I would rate this service as a 1,'' griped Walter Blum of
Millbrae, Calif. ``Every time I try to access my e-mail or the
Internet . . . I am told the primary access number is down, or the
server does not exist, or there is some sort of obscure Windows
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   So what can consumers do to get more reliable Internet service?
</P>
<P>
   The sad fact of the matter is, not much. While it's true that
ISPs shouldn't be going down regularly, we have reached a point
where seemingly daily problems are not unusual. ``Unfortunately,
we're not living in a perfect world,'' said Jeannette Noyes, an
Internet analyst with computer research firm International Data
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Her simple advice to consumers: Vote with your pocketbook. ``If
problems persist, you can always switch Internet providers,'' she
said. ``But also understand that if the whole East or West Coast is
down, the problem is more than just your provider.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States alone, there are several thousand ISPs,
whose services range from nonexistent to excellent. Industry
observers have speculated for years that only the strongest will
survive. And ISPs do seem on a march toward consolidation. Leading
ISPs EarthLink and MindSpring announced in September they would
merge their operations, making them the second largest ISP, after
America Online /CompuServe. Last week, Baby Bell SBC Communications
invested in ISP Prodigy Communications, and said Prodigy would take
over management of SBC's 650,000 customers, including its Pacific
Bell Internet customers in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the big guys are getting together and getting
bigger, so far the smaller players haven't been adversely affected.
``We have claimed for a long time there are too &LR;   &LR; many little ISPs
who can't stay in business,'' said Joe Laszlo, an analyst with
Internet consulting firm Jupiter Communications. ``But some of
these smaller players provide better customer service (than their
larger competitors) and offer good local content.''
</P>
<P>
   Market research firm J.D. Power and Associates recently
conducted a customer satisfaction survey of the seven leading
national ISPs. The firm polled 131,401 households. Based on such
factors as cost, speed/ availability, ease of use and customer
care, the survey ranked MindSpring first, followed by EarthLink,
AT&AMP;T Worldnet and Microsoft Network. Coming in below average were
AOL, CompuServe and Prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ISP29 (p59651 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  On the bright side, analysts believe that consumer expectations
are steadily rising. In the early days of the commercial Internet,
or about four years ago, most people would casually shrug off
outages and temperamental connections. But because our lives and
our livelihoods are increasingly tied to the Internet, people are
less like to tolerate problems. This change in attitude is slowly
forcing ISPs to improve their service _ or risk going out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Providers like AOL and AT&AMP;T Worldnet, for instance, said they
are continually adding more dial-up numbers to their arsenals.
Their stated goal is to reduce busy signals and allow customers to
log on quickly and easily _ even during peak hours _ by giving them
more local numbers to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have thousands of access numbers for people across the
country,'' said AOL spokesman Nicholas Grahan. ``In San Francisco,
for instance, we have about eight local numbers that our members
can access.''
</P>
<P>
   But many users are still subject to surfing sluggishness or
outright disconnection if they happen to be logged on during peak
traffic hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been encountering severe connection problems around 9
p.m. almost every evening,'' said James Coffey of San Francisco,
who uses both AT&AMP;T Worldnet and Flashcom. ``I have come to suspect
that the problem is that Internet usage has grown to the point that
the system cannot handle the demand at peak usage times.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman Ritch Blasi said his company this year has spent
$20 million on upgrading its facilities to add capacity and
minimize the number of disconnects. ``The whole industry is growing
at such a rapid rate,'' he said. ``We are making big investments in
our network, but sometimes you have bumps in the road and we just
have to ask people to bear with us.''
</P>
<P>
   According to J.D. Power, approximately one-third of U.S.
households now subscribe to an ISP, up from one in five households
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And Pacific Bell admits that demand for its new high-speed DSL
Internet service is so great that it is struggling to keep pace.
The company said that its DSL subscriber base tripled from 32,000
to 100,000 between the second and third fiscal quarter of this
year. By the end of the year, the company expects to have a total
of 200,000 DSL subscribers in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our customers are extremely satisfied with the
service,'' said Pac Bell spokesman John Britton. ``But we did have
some problems, like being slow to get the service installed and
having technicians who were not fully trained. But now our
technical people have learned to overcome most obstacles and are
getting faster and more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every Pac Bell customer would agree. ``I received Pac Bell
DSL service (in early November) and it's been one nightmare after
another,'' said Marc Itzkowitz of Palo Alto, Calif., who
experienced e-mail outages as well as run-ins with Pac Bell
technicians and customer support reps.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell customer Guy Lion of Mill Valley added, ``The DSL line
connection, so far, has been highly unreliable. It is down at least
one-fourth of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from readers' experiences, what really irks Internet
users is poor customer service and general unresponsive on the part
of ISPs when problems do crop up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down during an online session,'' said Flashcom customer
Philip Weingrow. ``I called tech support. I was left holding for
over one hour on three separate occasions. I also tried Customer
Care. Ironically, each time I tried to reach them, my call was
dropped. Since I work from home . . . the outage was more than an
inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   For the average consumer, an Internet outage is a real pain in
the neck. But for business owners who rely on the Internet to run
their companies and communicate with customers and suppliers,
connection problems can be truly devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for instance, Pac Bell's DSL Internet service went
down for more than 24 hours in some areas, nearly crippling many
local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is completely killing us,'' said Brett Adam, who runs
Verve, a software company in San Francisco. ``When our link is
down, we're cut off from the world and that means our customers
can't reach us.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid such a catastrophe, advise analysts, is to sign
up with more than one Internet provider. That way, if your primary
provider goes down, you can still access the Net through an
alternate account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson companies always learn after they've had an outage
is that they need multiple providers,'' said Charles Carr, an
analyst with research firm Dataquest. ``Everyone needs to have
backup.''
</P>
<P>
   With more and more Internet providers starting to offer free
Internet service, getting backup is easier _ and cheaper _ than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a couple of times when I was unable to get
online,'' said San Francisco Chronicle reader Tim O'Boyle. ``But I
have a backup ISP . . . for free. I have NetZero. And even though
my regular ISP is down, I can check my e-mail, check up on my
stocks and anything else that seems important to me at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that not all readers hate their ISPs. ``I am
used to writing scathing letters about incompetent service
providers of all kinds,'' said self-proclaimed corporate basher
Nancy Levine of Berkeley, Calif. ``Pac Bell DSL? They're nice,
they're local, they're available, they're reliable. Just don't tell
'em I said so.''
</P>
<P>
   Additional reporting by James Temple.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of ISP29 (p59651 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
