<SLUG> BC-WTO-ILO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL LABOR GROUP BRINGS MESSAGE TO WTO MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tuesday's march of organized labor will be just as
important as the World Trade Organization's conference itself. So
said Juan Somavia, director-general of the International Labor
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Member governments of the WTO are not likely to adopt a
convention on labor rights, because low-wage countries oppose it.
But the AFL-CIO marchers will remind the world public _ and the
governments who are assembled here _ that labor rights can't be
ignored. And that message is music to the ears of the ILO.
</P>
<P>
   The ILO, as Somavia's group is known, was founded by
governments, labor and employer organizations in the ``red year''
of 1919, which saw the Seattle General Strike.
</P>
<P>
   The ILO's mission is to promote international labor standards by
working within the system. Its big issues today are guaranteeing
the freedom of association and ending forced labor, child labor and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Somavia is a Chilean who was a diplomat for the Allende
government in the 1970s, and again, for Chile's restored democracy
of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe you can shut off globalization,'' Somavia
said. ``It is a reality. But there are ways to make it much better
for people than it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``What people want everywhere in the world is decent
work. This is sometimes seen as a `soft' issue. But at the risk of
appearing soft, I keep insisting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Somavia is in Seattle to show the ILO's flag at the WTO
ministerial meetings this week. And that's a change. His
predecessor, the Belgian Michel Hansenne, was invited to the
Singapore WTO Ministerial by the Swiss but refused to go because of
the hostile views of low-wage countries.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, the United States and the European Union pushed
a labor agenda. The low-wage countries, who fear that labor
standards will bar their products, shunted the labor issue off to
the ILO.
</P>
<P>
   The ILO has seven key ``conventions,'' which are to be ratified
by its members. These include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A ban on forced labor, excepting military service, certain
convict labor and civil emergencies. Adopted 1930.
</P>
<P>
   _ Freedom of association and the right to form unions and
chambers of commerce independent of the state. Adopted 1948.
</P>
<P>
   _ The right to bargain collectively without interference and
punishment. Adopted 1949.
</P>
<P>
   _ Equal pay for men and women doing work of equal value. Adopted
1951.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ban on forced labor as punishment for political views or for
strikers. Adopted 1957.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ban on discrimination because of race, ethnicity, sex,
religion, or social origin. Adopted 1958.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ban on the employment of children who by law should be in
school. Adopted 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has adopted only one of these conventions, on forced
labor. The U.S. position is that the federal government cannot bind
the states. ``Our position is that this is a shame,'' said the
ILO's director of information, Michel Barton.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that President Clinton is scheduled Thursday
to sign the ratification of a lesser ILO standard, abolishing the
worst forms of child labor, including child pornography and
children sold into bondage by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the WTO, the ILO has no power to authorize sanctions. The
most it can do is to bar a member from all assistance, as it has
done with only one member, Burma, over the issue of forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   But the ILO takes itself seriously. ``We don't have sanctions,''
said Barton. ``But public opinion has many. We feed public
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the opinion of agencies with clout. When Indonesia
asked for billions from the International Monetary Fund, the IMF
consulted with the ILO first. As a result, said Barton, Indonesia
released labor leaders from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Another example: Next year Congress will vote on giving China
permanent access to U.S. markets on normal commercial terms.
Critics of China may turn to the ILO report on labor rights, which
declares that China, an ILO member for 80 years, is in violation of
the ILO guarantee of independent unions.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of that, the Chinese have been coming by the hundreds
to the ILO's labor institute in Italy, where labor leaders,
corporate directors of labor relations, and labor-ministry
officials learn the principles of labor relations in a modern
economy. Most of these Chinese, he said, are human resources
manages from factories in Guangdong province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
