<SLUG> BC-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FROM A COFFEE SHOP IN HANOI TO TOOLBARS FOR THE INTERNET  &HT;     By JAN BOYD and STAN BUNGER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thumb through Ly Tran's resume, and you find the
usual hints of success: undergraduate degree from Princeton,
Harvard MBA, a stint with a multinational bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Tran, co-founder of an Internet company called AtHoc, has
one bit of experience that sets him apart from the overachieving
Silicon Valley crowd. That would be his coffee-roasting business in
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Tran, 29, co-founded Moca Cafe three years ago. It's quite a
story.
</P>
<P>
   Tran was born in the Vietnamese beachfront town of Quin Hon. His
father served as a captain in the South Vietnamese army, and at the
end of the Vietnam War, the family fled its homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The Trans wound up in San Francisco, where Ly graduated from
Lowell High School before heading off for his Ivy League education.
After completing his Princeton degree, Tran went to work for Chase
Manhattan Bank and was assigned to a post in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   One of his jobs was to buy sand for Japanese factories, and as
fate would have it, that took him back to Quin Hon. Though he
admits he didn't speak Vietnamese particularly well, Tran says he
felt like he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Tran quit his job with Chase and decided to become an
entrepreneur. His first deal involved an oceanfront resort at Nha
Trang, and then came Moca Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee roasting company was founded in an old French convent
in Hanoi. It now employs 50 people, and there's pride in Tran's
voice when he explains what a steady paycheck means to those
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Moca Cafe generates a modest profit: about $10,000 a month. But
Tran believes the venture has given him the sort of education money
can't buy. ``Operating in the highly unregulated third world
environment has taught me a lot about entrepreneurship,'' said
Tran.
</P>
<P>
   Once Moca Cafe was up and running, Tran decided to return to the
states and do what every young entrepreneur does: Go to business
school.
</P>
<P>
   While completing his MBA at Harvard, he met Israeli entrepreneur
Guy Miasnik and the two decided to cash in on the Internet boom.
</P>
<P>
   Their San Francisco company, AtHoc, uses technology developed in
Israel to improve on the personal toolbars on Web browsers.
Existing toolbars let users jump to specific sites without typing
in a Web address.
</P>
<P>
   AtHoc's toolbar lets users set up shortcuts that take them deep
within Web sites with just one click. The company has cut deals
with several Web sites to create branded versions of its toolbar.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one partner is Raging Bull, an online investor
information site. A Raging Bull patron could set up a shortcut to
Microsoft's stock price. Clicking on that icon on the toolbar would
automatically take the user from the browser to the Raging Bull
page that displays Microsoft's stock price _ saving a few interim
steps.
</P>
<P>
   Tran thinks his company has a bright future. But if things don't
work out, there's always that coffee thing to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   CAD ARTISTS: Some of the best work being done at Hewlett-Packard
happens after hours every Tuesday night. Jim White, a longtime
engineer, unlocks the door to a corporate training room and lets in
Tom Bakey and his students.
</P>
<P>
   The students, about a dozen disabled children and adults, find a
spot in front of a computer and sit down next to a volunteer. They
watch attentively as Bakey stands at the front of the room with a
felt pen and quickly sketches a dolphin. Then the fun begins.
</P>
<P>
   Russell _ sitting in the second row, wearing a cowboy hat
adorned with tinsel, various buttons, a jack-in-the-box ball, an
eagle and a big plastic rat _ quickly moves through a Windows paint
program. He clicks and drags lines around the screen until a
dolphin appears.
</P>
<P>
   Russell sometimes has a little trouble counting past three, but
the paint program is a snap. He can create a full-screen view of a
Hawaiian beach or a detailed scene of the Tech Museum and downtown
San Jose. He's also working on a series of cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Vanessa, who has been attending the class for several
years, works on creating the dolphin's arch. When Vanessa first
came to the class, she was so reserved she didn't move or talk
during the session. Now she laughs with her volunteer tutor as they
struggle to make the line arc gracefully. Bakey comes by and
encourages Vanessa to try again.
</P>
<P>
   Another volunteer whispers that Bakey challenges the students to
push themselves; if the drawing doesn't look like a dolphin, he
tells them so, no matter what their disability. And the students
respond. In fact, these CAD artists have gotten so good that some
of their drawings have appeared on the cover of brochures or as
posters. And once a month, a small group travels with Bakey to the
San Jose Tech Museum, where they teach nondisabled children how to
create computer drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Russell finishes his drawing in record time and starts talking
with Brian Cardello, a photographer for New Media News who's
shooting Russell's work. While the two chat about the color of the
sky at the horizon line, Bakey shares one of his favorite stories
about his students.
</P>
<P>
   The CAD artists, who designed the artwork in a brochure for a
local multimedia design conference, attended the event. During the
conference, a speaker, unaware that the art was created by disabled
students, pointed to the brochure as an example of computer art of
the future. Later, an executive vice president from Disney, also
unaware of the students' background, walked up to Russell to
congratulate him on his work. `'Did you use clip art?'' he
inquired. ``No,'' responded Russell, ``I'm an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   You can view some of their work, along with instructions on how
to draw your own dolphin, at CADartists.org.
</P>
<P>
   Outtakes is a biweekly column that takes you behind the scenes
at New Media News, which appears on KRON-TV Sundays at 9:30 a.m.
and several times during the weekend on Bay TV. Stan Bunger reports
for the show; Jan Boyd is the producer. Send feedback to
talk &LR; newmedianews.com
</P>
</TEXT>
