<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Nov. 29. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
RAGE _ (PHOENIX) Gregory Francis Schmidt could spend 25 years
behind bars for not controlling his anger when a truck cut him off
on the Black Canyon Freeway last year. Instead of handling it as a
daily irritation on a Phoenix-area Valley freeway, Schmidt squeezed
off eight shots. In an instant, Gillis Champagne, 21, a passenger
in the truck, was dead. A bullet passed through his neck, severing
an artery. The Phoenix area is a hotbed for such hotheaded drivers,
and prosecutors and judges in Maricopa County show no mercy for
such violent reactions. Prison sentences are sought for anyone who
flashes or uses a gun on a roadway. When he is sentenced in
January, Schmidt, 29, can expect to join a string of Phoenix-area
men spending decades in prison because of a flash of fury behind
the wheel. By VICTORIA HARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HISPANIC-CENSUS _ (PHOENIX) Seven months after Arizona Gov. Jane
Hull signed a law that governs how boundaries for Arizona voting
districts are drawn, local and national Hispanic leaders remain
hopeful that it will be struck down on the basis that it weakens
the political power of Latinos and other people of color. A score
of national civil rights groups and Hispanic politicians, mostly
Democrats, contend that the U.S. Justice Department should block
the law, which requires the Arizona Legislature to use exact head
counts in redrawing political boundaries after 2000. Critics say an
exact head count is a flawed method that was shown to undercount
Hispanics by more than 1 million people during the 1990 census. By
ELVIA DIAZ. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY (UNDATED) _ If you're searching for a television heroine,
look no further than Iree Bowling. She's lived all but five months
of her 68 years in dirt-poor Mudlick Hollow, a valley in eastern
Kentucky. But her presence _ to say nothing of her pride _ rivets
you to the screen in American Hollow, the excellent HBO documentary
produced and directed by Rory Kennedy, in a way whippet-thin
Hollywood actresses only wish they could manage. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (UNDATED) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews. By
ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
