<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON NOW IN SICK BAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In toasting the return of Maurice Taylor, the Los Angeles
Clippers must bow to the misfortune of franchise protocol by
drinking from a half-empty cup.
</P>
<P>
   The premature gulp was in honor of Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has just finished a three-game recovery after
missing the previous three games by virtue of concussion, did not
attend Sunday's practice. His lingering sinus problem seemed to
reach its full potential during Saturday night's 88-71 stinker
against Portland, during which Anderson struggled for 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on post-concussion fumes the previous two games,
Anderson had ripped New York for 23 and Seattle for a season-high
29.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave him some medication so he can get some rest,'' Coach
Chris Ford of Anderson, who is not expected to practice today and
seems like a shaky bet for Tuesday's game vs. the tempo-maniacal
Phoenix Suns at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   At least Taylor is making a vigorous attempt to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, I felt great,'' said Taylor, who talks as if the
sprain of his left foot is healing with every few words. ``I was
excited to get back out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clipper power forward injured the foot two weeks ago at
Vancouver and has been sidelined for 7} games since. Sunday's
workout marked his return to a team that has won half of its last 6
games (4-9 overall), but lost its last 2.
</P>
<P>
   In attempting to accelerate the pace of his conditioning, Taylor
was in full attack mode during a full-court scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad,'' said Ford when asked for a first-sight appraisal of
the third-year Clipper who averages 16 points and 5 rebounds. ``He
seemed pretty lively. But he just can't come in and jack up the
ball every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor took the jibe in stride - and without a limp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an aggressive attitude,'' he said, making no apologies
for his hunger to score. ``I wanted to make it seem as game-like as
possible. But I know that when I get back in a real game situation,
after the first two trips down the court, I'll be tired as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Clippers, who have been wasting possessions on
3-point scuds, now have a low-post option to take the heat off of
rookie forward Lamar Odom and center Michael Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's carried too much of a burden,'' Taylor said of
Olowokandi, but the judgment goes double for Odom, who will be
double-teamed less with Mo in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't mean Ford and Taylor will abandon a rising,
pre-injury strategy that would allow the 6-8 power forward to step
out, face the basket and take bigger foes to the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That helps me, because they can't double me as easily,''
Taylor said. ``He (Ford) told me `Just don't get jump-shot happy.'
But I know where I get paid - it's on the blocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
