<P>
   ALASKA-CRUISESHIPS (Juneau, Alaska) _ The cruise ship industry,
once embraced as a savior for a lagging state economy, has worn out
its welcome here. Fed up with giant ships that discharge waste in
their pristine waterways and tourists who flood their downtown,
residents of Alaska's capital approved a $5 tax on every passenger
last month. The small town of Haines voted to limit the number of
cruise ships allowed at its dock. And several people have suggested
publicly that one cruise line be barred from the state's waters.
But in fighting to restrict the $12 billion cruise ship industry,
Alaskans also have a powerful opponent they may not have expected
-- their own representatives in the U.S. Congress. By Douglas
Frantz.
