<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-HERMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO'S MOORE URGES LABOR TO BE OPEN TO TRADE EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The head of the World Trade Organization reached out
to the world's union leaders yesterday, urging them to view trade
expansion as a tool to create jobs and boost economies.
</P>
<P>
   WTO director-general Mike Moore said labor groups shouldn't view
the growth of trade as a threat. The growth will give a boost to
the global economy, helping to create jobs, according to Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is the ally of working people, not their enemy,'' Moore
said in a speech to the International Confederation of Free Trade
Unions at Bell Harbor Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   Moore cited economic data that said exports surged by 51 percent
in the United States in the last six years, accounting for a
quarter of the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The role of organized labor in the creation of global trade
rules promises to be one of the most controversial issues at this
week's WTO ministerial meeting. Unions from around the world are
gathering here this week to press the trade body for more
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders say they want more than promises from the 135
member nations. They want trade ministers to stitch commitments to
labor standards _ such as the right of workers to organize _ into
the mandate that guides the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade group ignores the demands of unions they risk
losing both influence and power, said Bill Jordan, general
secretary of the International Confederation of Free Trade, a labor
group meeting here alongside the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   It ``could well be (the) beginning of the end of the WTO if they
ignore'' labor, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But Moore called for a truce in the dispute between free-trade
and labor activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is destructive because it obscures the underlying consensus
that exists about the social problems all countries face,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore admitted the WTO is ``not perfect. It can be improved, but
the world would be a more unstable and more dangerous place without
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, even though some nations are enjoying healthy
economies, not everyone is benefiting from the prosperity, Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day companies announce their highest profits, and the next
a thousand layoffs,'' Moore said. ``People want answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman voiced the Clinton
administration's support of some of the labor movement's demands.
Also speaking at yesterday's meeting, Herman said the WTO should
open its doors, at least at certain times, to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to ensure that you have access to the deliberations,''
Herman told the labor representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is walking a fine line this week
between President Clinton's support of free-trade policies and the
traditional alliance between U.S. unions and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton already has suggested that the WTO should create a
working group to examine the intersection of trade and labor
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But some union leaders say that isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for a process to address issues of core labor
standards,'' John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, unions at least have an official who was sympathetic
to their concerns in the past, when he served in the New Zealand
government as a member of the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he is attempting to address the issues we have
raised,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
