u i BC-URUGUAY-VOTE-1STLD-WR     11-28 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URUGUAY-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING PARTY CANDIDATE WINS PRESIDENCY IN URUGUAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) 
 (sw3) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay _ The candidate of the governing Colorado
Party won the Uruguayan presidency on his fifth try on Sunday by
beating back a strong challenge from a leftist coalition that
included Socialists, Communists and former guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Batlle, the governing party candidate, promised in his
campaign to pursue a vigorous foreign policy that would open
markets for Uruguay's dairy and wool products and to improve
educational opportunities by broadly expanding computer and
internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But what caught the attention of analysts throughout Latin
America was the impressive showing by Batlle's challenger, Tabare
Vazquez, the former mayor of Montevideo, the capital. Vazquez, an
oncologist, challenged the free-enterprise policies that are now
fashionable around the region and pledged an aggressive campaign
against poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Sunday night, with all the ballots counted, the Interior
Ministry said Batlle, a 72-year-old former senator known for
bluntly speaking his mind, had won 1,138,067 votes, or 52 percent.
Vazquez, 59, won 972,197 votes, or 44 percent, with the rest of the
2.2 million ballots either annulled or blank.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Vazquez's Broad Front party could claim a victory
of sorts since it won the largest bloc of votes in the Uruguayan
Congress in the Oct. 31 first-round balloting.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech, Batlle promised to lead ``a government
with the active participation of all the people to promote the
ideals of democracy, tolerance and liberty.'' Vazquez conceded
defeat, saying, ``We accept the decision of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Batlle was able to defeat Vazquez by forming an alliance with
the center-right National Party three weeks ago, so the two
traditional parties that have dominated this tiny country of 3.2
million people for most of the last 150 years will now form a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Batlle (pronounced BAH-jay) has been a candidate four times
before, in 1966, 1971, 1989 and 1994, but he lost to other Colorado
or opposition candidates under a previous system that combined
primary votes with the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Batlle is likely to follow the policies of the current
president, Julio Maria Sanguinetti, of seeking out more foreign
investment for the tourism industry and cautiously privatizing some
government services to cut a bloated bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Uruguay is well behind neighboring Argentina and most other
Latin American countries in privatizing industry because its voters
continue their strong support for welfare-state policies that go
back to the presidency of Batlle's grand-uncle at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   In a historical twist, it is the Tupamaros, the former
guerrillas, and other left-wing groups that once attacked Uruguay's
social democracy as a liberal trick to subdue the masses that now
most strongly defend the cradle-to-grave welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez led in the polls for most of the last year, but
previously undecided voters appeared to be swayed by a Batlle media
blitz in the final weeks of the campaign suggesting that a leftist
victory would mean higher income taxes and economic and political
instability.
</P>
<P>
   But Vazquez's strong showing, combined with his winning a
plurality in the first round of voting, has put the two traditional
parties on notice that voters are growing restless with what is
widely perceived as their uncreative leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The Broad Front has become increasingly popular since it was
founded 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez was able to tap into growing popular frustration with a
recession that has left 11 percent of the work force unemployed and
an economy that shrank this year, instead of growing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-28-99 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
