<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-28 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-SECEDE-LADN     11-28 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-SECEDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. GETS HOSTILE OVER HOLLYWOOD SECESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles city leaders said they will fight a
proposal by Hollywood residents and business owners to break away
and form their own city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they should go out to the desert and start their own
city,'' said Los Angeles City Council President John Ferraro, who
represents the western parts of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a bad idea to break up the city,'' said Ferraro,
who also opposes the cityhood bids by residents in the San Fernando
Valley and San Pedro-Wilmington. ``I don't know if they are
elitists who are just trying to get away from the problems we have
in the city or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan will fight secession in Hollywood, just as
he has argued against the Valley and Harbor area efforts, said his
chief of staff, Kelly Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't think it's a good idea for the city to break up,''
Martin said. ``We're very concerned about secession already, and
having more different groups who express a desire to secede is
troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Saturday of Thanksgiving weekend, members of a group
calling itself Hollywood VOTE _ after Valley Voters Organized
Toward Empowerment, the group backing the San Fernando Valley
cityhood effort _ announced their plans to make Hollywood an
independent city.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the group said they want to piggyback onto secession
efforts already under way in the Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could conceivably be on the ballot for cityhood with the
Valley and Harbor votes,'' said Mitchell Green, a lawyer who is one
of the leaders of Hollywood VOTE. ``If we don't do it at this time,
the opportunity will be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Brain, president of Valley VOTE, agreed that the timing is
right for Hollywood to try to break away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It demonstrates the discontent, not just in the Valley or San
Pedro, that Los Angeles residents have about the quality of life
and leadership in Los Angeles,'' he said, adding that other
communities may join the breakup movement.
</P>
<P>
   Brain said about two-thirds of the LAFCO study involves taking
an inventory of the assets of the city of Los Angeles. Since that
study is already being done for the Valley and San Pedro, it will
not be too difficult for LAFCO to add Hollywood to the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Hollywood VOTE was created about four weeks ago and
has 15 core members. The group currently only has cash on hand to
cover operating expenses, but Green said supporters have pledged to
give $40,000 to launch a petition drive to force a secession study
in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   A signature-collection drive could begin in mid-January, Green
said.
</P>
<P>
   Secession leaders in the Valley and San Pedro have already
completed petition drives to force studies of the financial effects
of breaking apart Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Local Agency Formation Commission is expected to begin the
analyses in March. It could take about two years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO would then hold hearings on the proposal to break up Los
Angeles before placing it on a citywide ballot. A majority in the
city and the detaching areas would have to approve the proposals
before the Valley and San Pedro could become independent cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood residents contend smaller cities in Los Angeles
County _ Beverly Hills, West Hollywood and Santa Monica, for
example _ are run better and are more successful at meeting the
needs of businesses and homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we can make it a lot better place for people who
live here, who work here and visit here,'' said Fares Wehbe, the
financial director at the Little Red School House and a longtime
Hollywood resident.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Hollywood cityhood proponents say most outsiders think
Hollywood is a separate city already, rather than a part of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already we are an internationally known city that doesn't
actually exist,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood group has yet to finalize the borders of its
independent city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of still casting our net to see which communities
are interested in joining us,'' Wehbe said.
</P>
<P>
   However, members suggested the border could go as far east as
the intersection of Riverside Drive and Hyperion Avenue. Under that
scenario the new city would include not only Hollywood but also
large parts of Los Feliz and Silver Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The southern border would be Melrose Avenue. On the west, the
new city could stretch all the way to La Cienega Boulevard. The new
city may also take in the Hollywood Hills, stretching all the way
up to Mulholland Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, Riordan's chief of staff, said it is not clear whether
the secession movements will gain popular support at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of these areas you have a relatively small group of
people organizing the efforts. I don't think the people have voted
to say goodbye yet,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the Valley and San Pedro proposals are already in
conflict because the two communities have different ideas about how
to split up the assets of Los Angeles. Adding Hollywood into the
equation could confuse voters even more. ``Maybe these communities
will all vote for one another. Or maybe everybody throws their
hands in the air and says it can't be done,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its worldwide fame, the community of Hollywood has
struggled for decades to live up to the expectations of the
millions of tourists who flock there every year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several revitalization efforts, Hollywood has been
unable to recapture the magic of its early years as the city's
movie glamour centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ferraro noted that Hollywood is finally back on the
right track. Several major projects are in the works, including a
city-assisted $300million development at Hollywood Boulevard and
Highland Avenue by Trizec-Hahn Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The city is contributing $90million in public funds for an
underground parking garage and a 3,300 seat, live-broadcast theater
that will serve as the new home for the Academy Awards telecast
starting in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood was dormant for a long time. It's now coming back,''
Ferraro said. ``Hollywood is a great asset for the city of Los
Angeles, and we have to do everything we can to promote it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the effort is still in its formative stage, it has a fan
in vamp screen star and longtime Hollywood resident Elvira.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Hollywood would (become its own city) because all the
money that comes in wouldn't go downtown. Millions of people come
here, and what's on Hollywood Boulevard? Nothing,'' she said at
Sunday's Hollywood Christmas Parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Hollywood would secede. It would be my dream come
true.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
